57
00:02:30,550 --> 00:02:31,759
-(Daniel mumbling)
-(clamoring in distance)

58
00:02:31,843 --> 00:02:34,762
(objects thumping in distance)

59
00:02:34,846 --> 00:02:37,181
SANDRA (in English):
What would you write about?

60
00:02:37,265 --> 00:02:39,433
It's Samuel working upstairs--
my husband.

61
00:02:39,517 --> 00:02:40,935
(thumping continues in distance)

62
00:02:42,895 --> 00:02:45,314
So, what interests you?

63
00:02:45,398 --> 00:02:47,692
What makes you so mad
you want to explore it?

64
00:02:47,775 --> 00:02:49,569
Forget about your thesis,
your studies...

65
00:02:49,652 --> 00:02:51,362
I don't want to be a writer.

66
00:02:51,445 --> 00:02:53,030
SANDRA:
Well, it's okay.

67
00:02:53,114 --> 00:02:54,532
You don't have to write, just talk.

68
00:02:54,615 --> 00:02:55,992
Like we're talking now.

69
00:02:56,075 --> 00:02:57,493
You don't want to go on
with my questions?

70
00:02:57,577 --> 00:02:58,744
SANDRA:
Of course I want to go on

71
00:02:58,828 --> 00:03:00,288
because... Of course!

72
00:03:00,371 --> 00:03:01,914
But we could chat too.

73
00:03:01,998 --> 00:03:04,250
Maybe we ask one question each?

74
00:03:04,333 --> 00:03:07,712
So nobody's frustrated,
like a normal conversation.

75
00:03:07,795 --> 00:03:09,255
(laughs)

76
00:03:09,338 --> 00:03:11,132
Are you really interested
in what I...?

77
00:03:11,215 --> 00:03:12,884
In what interests you? C'mon!

78
00:03:12,967 --> 00:03:14,677
Sure.

79
00:03:14,760 --> 00:03:15,928
I never see anybody.

80
00:03:16,012 --> 00:03:17,513
I work here all day long.

81
00:03:17,597 --> 00:03:19,390
You come to see me.
Of course you interest me.

82
00:03:20,808 --> 00:03:23,269
Okay, um...

83
00:03:23,352 --> 00:03:25,146
-I run.
-SANDRA: Mm-hmm?

84
00:03:25,229 --> 00:03:27,607
It's one of
my favorite things to do.

85
00:03:27,690 --> 00:03:29,692
It makes me feel high,
like I'm on drugs.

86
00:03:29,775 --> 00:03:30,943
(Sandra laughs)

87
00:03:31,027 --> 00:03:32,945
What do you know
about drugs then?

88
00:03:33,029 --> 00:03:35,323
-Oh, a lot...
-That's the next question.

89
00:03:35,406 --> 00:03:38,242
-(Sandra laughs)
-Big subject.

90
00:03:38,326 --> 00:03:40,077
SANDRA: Maybe you don't write
everything down...

91
00:03:40,161 --> 00:03:41,954
No, no, surely not. Mm.

92
00:03:42,038 --> 00:03:44,123
("P.I.M.P." restarts playing
over speakers in distance)

93
00:03:50,546 --> 00:03:52,005
(laughs)
I told you...

94
00:03:52,089 --> 00:03:54,300
we should've done this in Grenoble.

95
00:03:54,382 --> 00:03:55,885
ZOE:
Ah... It's fine.

96
00:03:55,968 --> 00:03:57,928
I'll write your answers down.

97
00:03:58,012 --> 00:03:59,972
But, uh, I have many, many questions,

98
00:04:00,056 --> 00:04:01,933
maybe you don't have the time--

99
00:04:02,016 --> 00:04:03,809
Ah, don't-- Don't worry about time.

100
00:04:03,893 --> 00:04:05,937
Time is not a problem here.

101
00:04:06,020 --> 00:04:07,271
Okay. Cool.

102
00:04:07,355 --> 00:04:08,689
Uh, I'd like to discuss

103
00:04:08,773 --> 00:04:10,066
storytelling as an investigation...

104
00:04:10,149 --> 00:04:11,317
I don't like sports.

105
00:04:11,400 --> 00:04:12,693
That's the first thing.

106
00:04:12,777 --> 00:04:14,946
Walking, yes, maybe, running, no.

107
00:04:15,029 --> 00:04:16,531
(laughs) No!

108
00:04:16,614 --> 00:04:18,324
-Okay, right. I get it.
-SANDRA: No...

109
00:04:18,407 --> 00:04:21,702
Um, so, your...

110
00:04:24,872 --> 00:04:28,000
(power tools buzz in distance)

111
00:04:30,962 --> 00:04:33,256
It's not really possible anymore, is it?

112
00:04:33,339 --> 00:04:35,132
-ZOE: Yeah. It's complicated.
-So, yeah.

113
00:04:35,216 --> 00:04:36,676
I think we have to stop, Zoé.

114
00:04:36,759 --> 00:04:40,638
(power tools buzz in distance)

115
00:04:40,721 --> 00:04:42,348
You know what,
I'll be in Grenoble soon,

116
00:04:42,431 --> 00:04:44,225
I'll give you a call, how about that?

117
00:04:44,308 --> 00:04:45,351
Okay.

118
00:04:45,434 --> 00:04:47,395
(hammering in distance)

119
00:04:50,898 --> 00:04:52,066
Sorry about that.

120
00:04:52,149 --> 00:04:54,735
(loud pounding in distance)

121
00:04:55,152 --> 00:04:56,487
-SANDRA: Okay. Bye.
-ZOE: Bye.

122
00:04:56,571 --> 00:04:57,697
-See you soon.
-Yeah, definitely.

123
00:04:57,780 --> 00:04:58,865
SANDRA: Yeah?

124
00:05:29,854 --> 00:05:31,606
(car engine starts)

125
00:05:52,752 --> 00:05:54,378
(panting)

126
00:05:54,462 --> 00:05:56,339
("P.I.M.P." playing faintly in distance)

127
00:06:29,413 --> 00:06:31,999
(water rushing in river nearby)

128
00:06:41,384 --> 00:06:42,927
(groans, clears throat)

129
00:06:49,851 --> 00:06:50,977
Whoa.

130
00:06:51,060 --> 00:06:52,478
Whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa!

131
00:06:52,562 --> 00:06:53,688
(in French)
Careful.

132
00:06:53,771 --> 00:06:55,022
(Daniel chuckles)

133
00:06:55,815 --> 00:06:58,025
(speaks French)

134
00:07:00,903 --> 00:07:04,866
(speaks French)

135
00:07:04,949 --> 00:07:07,660
("P.I.M.P." continues playing)

136
00:07:20,882 --> 00:07:21,799
(barks)

137
00:07:21,883 --> 00:07:22,925
(Daniel exclaims)

138
00:07:24,135 --> 00:07:25,303
(Snoop panting)

139
00:07:26,470 --> 00:07:27,930
(Daniel whispers in French)

140
00:07:28,014 --> 00:07:29,682
(Snoop barks and grunts)

141
00:07:31,851 --> 00:07:33,477
DANIEL: Dad! Mom!

142
00:07:34,312 --> 00:07:35,438
DANIEL: Mom!

143
00:07:37,190 --> 00:07:38,900
Mom!

144
00:07:38,983 --> 00:07:40,401
-Mom!
-(Snoop barking)

145
00:07:40,484 --> 00:07:41,777
Mom, come quick!

146
00:07:42,570 --> 00:07:43,738
(cries)

147
00:07:46,365 --> 00:07:48,409
Mom!

148
00:07:49,118 --> 00:07:50,369
Mom!

149
00:07:50,453 --> 00:07:52,330
(Daniel sobbing)

150
00:07:52,413 --> 00:07:53,581
Mom!

151
00:07:53,664 --> 00:07:55,374
("P.I.M.P." continues playing)

152
00:08:17,813 --> 00:08:19,899
(Sandra speaking indistinctly in English)

153
00:08:22,568 --> 00:08:24,654
SANDRA (in English):
I don't know, because I...

154
00:08:24,737 --> 00:08:26,531
My child was calling me.

155
00:08:26,614 --> 00:08:28,491
Eh... Yes!

156
00:08:28,574 --> 00:08:30,326
No, he's... I don't know.

157
00:08:30,409 --> 00:08:32,203
I didn't move him.
No, I didn't touch him at all.

158
00:08:32,286 --> 00:08:35,790
I think... He's not breathing,
that's why I'm calling.

159
00:08:35,873 --> 00:08:38,084
(Sandra breathing heavily)

160
00:08:38,167 --> 00:08:41,504
No, please come, I can't answer
all these questions.

161
00:08:41,587 --> 00:08:42,505
No.

162
00:08:42,588 --> 00:08:44,173
(Sandra sobs)

163
00:08:44,257 --> 00:08:46,133
No, he's not-- He's not moving.

164
00:08:46,217 --> 00:08:47,510
Please just come!

165
00:08:47,593 --> 00:08:49,428
-(vehicle door closes)
-(people chattering in French)

166
00:08:56,561 --> 00:08:58,229
FEMALE REPORTER (in French):
...Samuel Maleski,

167
00:08:58,312 --> 00:09:00,606
found dead below his chalet...

168
00:09:03,901 --> 00:09:06,112
(people chattering in French)

169
00:09:13,160 --> 00:09:15,329
(Sandra responding in French)

170
00:09:19,250 --> 00:09:21,043
(Sandra sobbing)

171
00:09:23,004 --> 00:09:24,463
(Sandra speaks through tears)

172
00:09:31,053 --> 00:09:32,096
(camera flash clicks)

173
00:09:33,097 --> 00:09:34,682
FORENSIC DOCTOR (in French):
Turning him now.

174
00:09:38,269 --> 00:09:39,729
Full shot.

175
00:09:40,646 --> 00:09:41,939
Closeup.

176
00:09:44,609 --> 00:09:46,611
FORENSIC DOCTOR:
I'll dictate the initial ideas.

177
00:09:46,694 --> 00:09:48,946
Insert them before the conclusion.

178
00:09:49,697 --> 00:09:53,659
The parallel, superficial abrasions
on the hands and forearms

179
00:09:53,743 --> 00:09:56,746
suggest the body slid
one or two meters upon impact

180
00:09:56,829 --> 00:09:59,248
before reaching
its final, supine position.

181
00:10:00,666 --> 00:10:04,378
A left temporal hematoma
related to the fatal brain trauma

182
00:10:04,462 --> 00:10:08,007
indicates collision with
a blunt object in the environment

183
00:10:08,090 --> 00:10:10,801
or a violent blow to the head.

184
00:10:11,844 --> 00:10:15,389
Injury location is inconsistent
with discovery position,

185
00:10:15,473 --> 00:10:19,143
thus impact occurred
before the body hit the ground.

186
00:10:20,937 --> 00:10:23,147
In conclusion,
we cannot yet determine

187
00:10:23,231 --> 00:10:26,192
if the injury resulted
from a collision or a blow.

188
00:10:26,943 --> 00:10:31,113
We cannot, at this stage,
rule out third party involvement.

189
00:10:33,407 --> 00:10:35,409
Then, the usual.

190
00:10:35,493 --> 00:10:37,745
Cause of death: head trauma.

191
00:10:37,828 --> 00:10:39,747
Forensic cause:

192
00:10:39,830 --> 00:10:42,124
accidental and/or deliberate.

193
00:10:43,042 --> 00:10:46,921
Toxicological analysis needed
to establish the truth.

194
00:10:50,675 --> 00:10:54,345
<i>(Daniel practicing Albeniz'
"Asturias (Leyenda)")</i>

195
00:10:55,471 --> 00:10:56,681
{\an8}<i>(piano pauses)</i>

196
00:10:58,474 --> 00:11:01,227
{\an8}<i>(composition continues slowly)</i>

197
00:11:01,310 --> 00:11:02,478
{\an8}<i>(pauses, backs up)</i>

198
00:11:02,562 --> 00:11:04,605
{\an8}<i>(repeats previous section)</i>

199
00:11:04,689 --> 00:11:07,108
<i>(plays section discordantly)</i>

200
00:11:07,191 --> 00:11:09,068
<i>(pauses)</i>

201
00:11:09,151 --> 00:11:11,737
<i>(playing section quicker
in different octave)</i>

202
00:11:11,821 --> 00:11:13,573
{\an8}<i>(hitting intermittent
discordant notes)</i>

203
00:11:17,076 --> 00:11:18,369
{\an8}<i>(pauses)</i>

204
00:11:19,787 --> 00:11:21,205
{\an8}<i>(playing same small section
successfully)</i>

205
00:11:23,749 --> 00:11:24,917
<i>(hitting several discordant notes)</i>

206
00:11:25,001 --> 00:11:27,044
<i>(pauses)</i>

207
00:11:27,128 --> 00:11:32,216
{\an8}<i>(repeating section,
with discordant notes)</i>

208
00:11:32,300 --> 00:11:33,801
{\an8}<i>(pauses)</i>

209
00:11:35,761 --> 00:11:37,889
<i>(repeating section,
with discordant notes)</i>

210
00:11:39,182 --> 00:11:41,517
{\an8}<i>(playing section repeatedly,
successfully)</i>

211
00:11:46,189 --> 00:11:47,231
<i>(pauses)</i>

212
00:11:49,650 --> 00:11:50,902
<i>(finishes end of section successfully)</i>

213
00:11:50,985 --> 00:11:54,155
ANATOMY OF A FALL

214
00:11:54,238 --> 00:11:56,949
<i>(car approaching)</i>

215
00:12:07,877 --> 00:12:08,878
(car engine shuts off)

216
00:12:10,129 --> 00:12:11,422
(car door closes)

217
00:12:38,783 --> 00:12:39,784
SANDRA (in English):
Thank you for coming.

218
00:12:39,867 --> 00:12:41,577
VINCENT (quietly):
Yeah, well...

219
00:12:41,661 --> 00:12:43,037
-This is really weird.
-Yes.

220
00:12:43,120 --> 00:12:44,121
-Seeing you again, like this.
-It is.

221
00:12:44,205 --> 00:12:47,416
-Okay.
-(Vincent sighs)

222
00:12:47,500 --> 00:12:49,961
I didn't realize it was so high...

223
00:12:50,878 --> 00:12:51,879
Yeah.

224
00:12:53,256 --> 00:12:54,507
-Come on!
-Yeah.

225
00:12:58,719 --> 00:13:01,138
(in French)
Have you lived here long?

226
00:13:01,764 --> 00:13:04,141
(in French)
Less than two years.

227
00:13:05,601 --> 00:13:06,894
(in English) It's Samuel,
he grew up here.

228
00:13:06,978 --> 00:13:09,272
-VINCENT: Mm-hmm.
-It's his...

229
00:13:09,355 --> 00:13:10,690
Well...

230
00:13:14,652 --> 00:13:16,654
Well, um...

231
00:13:19,407 --> 00:13:21,617
How... How...
How are we gonna do this?

232
00:13:21,701 --> 00:13:24,579
Do you... Will you
ask me some questions and...?

233
00:13:24,662 --> 00:13:25,830
-VINCENT: Yeah.
-I'm really sorry

234
00:13:25,913 --> 00:13:27,832
that my French isn't any better
than when we met...

235
00:13:27,915 --> 00:13:29,792
(in English)
No, uh, English is fine.

236
00:13:29,876 --> 00:13:31,043
SANDRA: Okay.

237
00:13:31,127 --> 00:13:32,295
Um...

238
00:13:34,797 --> 00:13:36,966
How many times
have you been questioned?

239
00:13:37,049 --> 00:13:40,678
It's been once here
by the policemen

240
00:13:40,761 --> 00:13:42,722
and once
by the investigative judge.

241
00:13:44,265 --> 00:13:46,017
VINCENT:
Okay. Can you tell me,

242
00:13:46,100 --> 00:13:48,853
um, what you told them
about the day he died?

243
00:13:48,936 --> 00:13:49,937
Yes, of course.

244
00:13:50,021 --> 00:13:51,397
SANDRA (in distance):
I told them everything

245
00:13:51,480 --> 00:13:53,274
about the moment
I was with the student

246
00:13:53,357 --> 00:13:55,401
until the ambulance got here.

247
00:13:55,484 --> 00:13:58,154
I was in the middle
of a meeting with this girl,

248
00:13:58,237 --> 00:14:01,115
and, um, Samuel started...

249
00:14:01,199 --> 00:14:02,909
blasting a song on repeat

250
00:14:02,992 --> 00:14:04,493
to piss me off
and make her leave.

251
00:14:04,577 --> 00:14:06,621
Is that what you told them,
that he'd played the song

252
00:14:06,704 --> 00:14:08,122
-to piss you off?
-No.

253
00:14:08,206 --> 00:14:09,248
No.

254
00:14:09,332 --> 00:14:11,209
I just said that

255
00:14:11,292 --> 00:14:13,336
he played the song super loud,
and that we had to stop--

256
00:14:13,419 --> 00:14:14,795
because she was recording
the interview

257
00:14:14,879 --> 00:14:16,297
and it wasn't possible anymore,
it was...

258
00:14:16,380 --> 00:14:18,049
VINCENT:
Hmm. Good.

259
00:14:18,132 --> 00:14:21,010
I-- I need you to be precise.

260
00:14:21,093 --> 00:14:24,347
Um, tell me everything, I mean
exactly the way you told them.

261
00:14:24,430 --> 00:14:25,389
Yes.

