292
00:15:33,207 --> 00:15:35,126
And...

293
00:15:35,209 --> 00:15:36,419
I fell asleep.

294
00:15:38,921 --> 00:15:42,717
And an hour later, I think,
I heard Daniel scream.

295
00:15:42,800 --> 00:15:45,094
And, um...

296
00:15:45,178 --> 00:15:47,471
(stammers, clears throat)

297
00:15:47,555 --> 00:15:49,223
One of the earplugs
must have fallen out, I guess,

298
00:15:49,307 --> 00:15:51,726
because
it woke me up, and...

299
00:15:51,809 --> 00:15:55,354
the music was still on,
and I ran downstairs, and...

300
00:15:55,438 --> 00:15:56,814
Yeah, that's it.

301
00:15:58,024 --> 00:15:59,525
I called the SAMU and they arrived

302
00:15:59,609 --> 00:16:00,902
30 minutes later.

303
00:16:01,736 --> 00:16:02,862
Okay.

304
00:16:07,700 --> 00:16:08,784
VINCENT: Um...

305
00:16:10,870 --> 00:16:12,330
Can I take a look around?

306
00:16:12,413 --> 00:16:13,456
Of course.

307
00:16:13,539 --> 00:16:15,499
-Yeah?
-Yeah.

308
00:16:15,583 --> 00:16:16,918
VINCENT: Um...

309
00:16:19,337 --> 00:16:20,963
Where do you want to start?

310
00:16:21,047 --> 00:16:22,757
Should I explain the...

311
00:16:22,840 --> 00:16:23,925
-Something?
-VINCENT: Yeah.

312
00:16:24,008 --> 00:16:25,259
Yeah, maybe, I don't know.

313
00:16:25,343 --> 00:16:26,469
Yeah. This is where...

314
00:16:26,552 --> 00:16:28,221
Come on. This is where we eat.

315
00:16:28,304 --> 00:16:29,430
(both scoff)

316
00:16:29,514 --> 00:16:30,848
-VINCENT: Sorry.
-No.

317
00:16:54,997 --> 00:16:58,084
So, ahem, he was
working over there?

318
00:16:58,166 --> 00:16:59,794
Yes, he was insulating the attic.

319
00:16:59,877 --> 00:17:03,631
Ah. And, uh,
and when you were having a nap,

320
00:17:03,714 --> 00:17:05,007
he was right above you?

321
00:17:05,091 --> 00:17:06,092
Yes.

322
00:17:06,175 --> 00:17:07,218
Okay.

323
00:17:15,977 --> 00:17:17,311
SANDRA: So...

324
00:17:18,479 --> 00:17:20,231
He was supposed
to get to that next.

325
00:17:20,314 --> 00:17:22,316
We wanted
to make rooms for a B&B.

326
00:18:02,356 --> 00:18:04,775
So he was working there?

327
00:18:04,859 --> 00:18:06,319
SANDRA:
These days, yes.

328
00:18:08,946 --> 00:18:11,282
VINCENT:
The... window?

329
00:18:11,365 --> 00:18:14,118
Do you remember when
the ambulance arrived, was it open?

330
00:18:14,202 --> 00:18:15,369
Yes, it was.

331
00:18:17,163 --> 00:18:19,290
VINCENT:
He used to keep it open?

332
00:18:19,373 --> 00:18:21,501
Um, I'm not sure of that really,

333
00:18:21,584 --> 00:18:23,878
because, uh, sometimes
he would air the room,

334
00:18:23,961 --> 00:18:25,213
you know, because
he wanted to get rid

335
00:18:25,296 --> 00:18:26,672
of the wood dust and...

336
00:18:26,756 --> 00:18:28,090
VINCENT: Was he reckless?
I mean, did he ever

337
00:18:28,174 --> 00:18:30,134
take some risks when he was working?

338
00:18:30,218 --> 00:18:32,803
No. He was very cautious
and meticulous--

339
00:18:32,887 --> 00:18:34,222
he worked slowly.

340
00:18:43,439 --> 00:18:45,525
VINCENT: Is there any reason
why he would have

341
00:18:45,608 --> 00:18:47,109
leaned out the window,

342
00:18:47,193 --> 00:18:49,320
for instance to call out
to you or Daniel?

343
00:18:49,403 --> 00:18:50,988
No. When he was working,

344
00:18:51,072 --> 00:18:53,533
especially when
he was playing his music,

345
00:18:53,616 --> 00:18:56,077
he, he kind of...

346
00:18:56,160 --> 00:18:58,621
he shut himself off
from the rest of the world.

347
00:18:58,704 --> 00:19:01,082
So he never called for me
or Daniel up here.

348
00:19:01,165 --> 00:19:03,000
VINCENT:
Mmm. Well, anyway,

349
00:19:03,084 --> 00:19:05,169
with the height of the...

350
00:19:05,253 --> 00:19:06,796
(speaks French)

351
00:19:06,879 --> 00:19:07,922
SANDRA:
Windowsill.

352
00:19:08,005 --> 00:19:09,966
-Windowsill...
-SANDRA: Yeah.

353
00:19:12,426 --> 00:19:13,970
Had he been drinking?

354
00:19:14,053 --> 00:19:15,638
SANDRA: No, he never drank
during the day,

355
00:19:15,721 --> 00:19:17,390
especially when he was working.

356
00:19:22,854 --> 00:19:24,313
(Daniel sobbing)

357
00:19:26,774 --> 00:19:27,775
SANDRA (in French):
Sweetie.

358
00:19:28,901 --> 00:19:29,944
(in English)
You need to wash up

359
00:19:30,027 --> 00:19:31,028
and get dressed. It's daytime,

360
00:19:31,112 --> 00:19:32,488
you need to get up.

361
00:19:34,365 --> 00:19:35,825
Honey, I know this is hard,

362
00:19:35,908 --> 00:19:37,785
it's hard for me too,

363
00:19:37,869 --> 00:19:39,328
and it's going to be hard for a while.

364
00:19:39,412 --> 00:19:41,122
-(sobbing continues)
-(footsteps approaching up stairs)

365
00:19:41,205 --> 00:19:42,665
But we have to try

366
00:19:42,748 --> 00:19:44,542
and do the things
that we did before.

367
00:19:44,625 --> 00:19:45,960
-Because I...
-(footsteps stop)

368
00:19:49,922 --> 00:19:52,341
Look, Monica came to see you,
she made you tiramisu.

369
00:19:52,425 --> 00:19:53,551
Yeah...

370
00:19:55,761 --> 00:19:58,222
You can't spend whole days
like this without going outside.

371
00:19:58,306 --> 00:20:01,017
It's beautiful out,
and Snoop needs to go out too.

372
00:20:09,567 --> 00:20:11,861
MONICA (in French):
Daniel, will you come eat with us?

373
00:20:12,445 --> 00:20:13,654
DANIEL (in tears):
I want to sleep.

374
00:20:13,738 --> 00:20:17,325
MONICA: Okay, first eat
with us, then you can sleep.

375
00:20:18,826 --> 00:20:20,411
(Vincent chatting outside)

376
00:20:34,926 --> 00:20:36,928
(Daniel sobbing quietly)

377
00:20:52,360 --> 00:20:53,819
DANIEL:
I don't understand.

378
00:20:55,238 --> 00:20:57,323
MONICA:
No one understands.

379
00:20:57,406 --> 00:20:59,033
We can't understand.

380
00:21:03,955 --> 00:21:05,414
DANIEL:
I have to understand.

381
00:21:11,629 --> 00:21:15,049
Remember the psychic
I told you about,

382
00:21:15,132 --> 00:21:17,593
the one I saw when Alain died?

383
00:21:18,553 --> 00:21:19,846
Monica.

384
00:21:20,137 --> 00:21:21,138
DANIEL:
I'd like to.

385
00:21:21,222 --> 00:21:23,140
I'd rather you don't...

386
00:21:23,224 --> 00:21:25,393
He helped me a lot.

387
00:21:25,476 --> 00:21:26,894
But he's a child.

388
00:21:26,978 --> 00:21:28,396
Don't confuse things.

389
00:21:28,479 --> 00:21:29,981
I'll discuss it with Monica.

390
00:21:30,064 --> 00:21:31,941
MONICA:
He's helped children before.

391
00:21:35,361 --> 00:21:36,445
SANDRA:
Want some?

392
00:21:38,823 --> 00:21:40,116
(Monica departs)

393
00:21:40,199 --> 00:21:41,576
(sobbing continues)

394
00:21:46,205 --> 00:21:48,457
(in English)
What do you need?

395
00:21:48,541 --> 00:21:50,042
DANIEL (in French):
Nothing, I'm okay.

396
00:21:50,126 --> 00:21:51,210
Okay.

397
00:21:52,962 --> 00:21:54,005
SANDRA: Mm.

398
00:22:00,720 --> 00:22:03,639
MONICA (in French):
Your doubts aside, it might help him.

399
00:22:03,723 --> 00:22:06,601
He senses things we can't.

400
00:22:08,352 --> 00:22:10,021
(in French)
Vincent, an old lawyer friend,

401
00:22:10,104 --> 00:22:12,190
Monica, Daniel's godmother.

402
00:22:12,440 --> 00:22:13,941
-Bonjour.
-Bonjour.

403
00:22:14,025 --> 00:22:16,444
-SANDRA: I'll call you.
-MONICA: Tell me if he eats.

404
00:22:19,155 --> 00:22:20,364
(door closes)

405
00:22:20,448 --> 00:22:21,490
VINCENT:
Uh...

406
00:22:21,574 --> 00:22:22,700
(in English)
Uh, the plates?

407
00:22:22,783 --> 00:22:23,910
-There.
-Yeah.

408
00:22:23,993 --> 00:22:25,536
(opens drawer)

409
00:22:25,620 --> 00:22:26,954
(plates clatter)

410
00:22:32,418 --> 00:22:33,711
(sobbing)

411
00:22:34,545 --> 00:22:36,797
I'm so tired of crying.

412
00:22:36,881 --> 00:22:38,883
It's really ridiculous.
I'm so exhausted.

413
00:22:40,259 --> 00:22:42,595
-You want parmesan?
-Yes. Yeah, it's perfect.

414
00:22:42,678 --> 00:22:43,888
And I don't know
where the pepper--

415
00:22:43,971 --> 00:22:44,972
VINCENT:
Don't worry,

416
00:22:45,056 --> 00:22:46,432
I'll take care of everything.

417
00:22:47,850 --> 00:22:50,311
So, as you know,
the autopsy report

418
00:22:50,394 --> 00:22:52,563
is inconclusive
about the cause of death.

419
00:22:52,647 --> 00:22:55,107
-Mm-hmm.
-The forensic pathologist

420
00:22:55,191 --> 00:22:57,485
didn't have enough
concrete elements.

421
00:22:57,568 --> 00:23:00,196
-But...
-(scribbling with marker)

422
00:23:00,279 --> 00:23:02,281
what we can defend is

423
00:23:02,365 --> 00:23:04,992
a fall from the attic window,

424
00:23:05,076 --> 00:23:09,497
with him "bouncing" off the shed's roof.

425
00:23:09,580 --> 00:23:11,457
His head may have hit the edge

426
00:23:11,541 --> 00:23:13,334
somewhere around here.

427
00:23:15,044 --> 00:23:16,003
You see?

428
00:23:16,087 --> 00:23:17,171
SANDRA: Okay.

429
00:23:17,255 --> 00:23:18,548
VINCENT:
Then he would have landed

430
00:23:18,631 --> 00:23:21,300
on the ground, approximately here.

431
00:23:21,384 --> 00:23:23,344
And it seems that he found the strength

432
00:23:23,427 --> 00:23:25,304
to crawl one meter or two

433
00:23:25,388 --> 00:23:28,933
before collapsing in this final position.

434
00:23:29,016 --> 00:23:32,019
That explains the blood on the snow.

435
00:23:32,895 --> 00:23:34,063
But there are several problems.

436
00:23:34,146 --> 00:23:35,648
First, they found nothing on the roof--

437
00:23:35,731 --> 00:23:37,692
no DNA, nothing.

438
00:23:37,775 --> 00:23:38,943
And there is this...

439
00:23:39,026 --> 00:23:41,195
three blood spatters here on the wall.

440
00:23:42,488 --> 00:23:44,073
It seems it doesn't really match

441
00:23:44,156 --> 00:23:46,826
with the... head impact on the roof.

442
00:23:46,909 --> 00:23:49,412
And the judge has asked
an expert to clarify this.

443
00:23:49,495 --> 00:23:50,830
SANDRA: Mm-hmm.

444
00:23:50,913 --> 00:23:53,332
And, when you see this,
what do you think?

445
00:23:55,084 --> 00:23:57,086
Um, I don't know,

446
00:23:57,170 --> 00:24:00,173
I'm not a spatter analyst,

447
00:24:00,256 --> 00:24:03,926
but, uh, I know a very good one.

448
00:24:04,010 --> 00:24:05,553
So, I'm gonna get her opinion.

449
00:24:18,900 --> 00:24:21,235
There's one last problem
for us, the...

450
00:24:21,319 --> 00:24:22,862
that bruise on your arm.

451
00:24:24,488 --> 00:24:28,284
It might look like the result
of a fight, struggle.

452
00:24:28,367 --> 00:24:29,744
SANDRA:
Oh, yeah. Ahem.

453
00:24:29,827 --> 00:24:31,495
Well, when did they see it?

454
00:24:31,579 --> 00:24:33,247
They examined me
that same night.

455
00:24:33,331 --> 00:24:34,999
My sleeve was rolled up
and they saw it.

456
00:24:35,082 --> 00:24:37,168
Okay, and you explained it
to them right away?

457
00:24:37,251 --> 00:24:38,586
Yeah, I knew exactly
how it happened.

458
00:24:38,669 --> 00:24:40,755
-Should I show you?
-Yeah, please.

459
00:24:40,838 --> 00:24:42,715
Ahem. So, when I'm here
in the kitchen,

460
00:24:42,798 --> 00:24:44,967
I bang my arm
on this all the time, you see?

461
00:24:45,051 --> 00:24:46,594
Like when I move. Heh.

462
00:24:46,677 --> 00:24:47,845
It's ridiculous.

463
00:24:47,929 --> 00:24:49,972
It happened several times that week,

464
00:24:50,056 --> 00:24:52,683
and, uh, I told them
that my skin marks easily,

465
00:24:52,767 --> 00:24:54,685
and they could ask Daniel
because he hears me

466
00:24:54,769 --> 00:24:56,312
bumping into it all the time.

467
00:24:56,395 --> 00:24:57,688
Okay, well...

468
00:25:01,984 --> 00:25:03,486
So, as you can see,

469
00:25:03,569 --> 00:25:05,571
an accidental fall
is gonna be hard to defend,

470
00:25:05,655 --> 00:25:08,407
given the height
of the... windowsill.

471
00:25:08,491 --> 00:25:09,909
-SANDRA: Mm-hmm.
-So that's why

472
00:25:09,992 --> 00:25:11,244
there's an investigation

473
00:25:11,327 --> 00:25:14,121
for "mort suspecte,"

474
00:25:14,205 --> 00:25:15,748
uh, and you're, you're,

475
00:25:15,831 --> 00:25:18,084
you're "mort susp--,"
suspicious death. Yeah.

476
00:25:18,167 --> 00:25:19,669
And you're a témoin assisté
because you were

477
00:25:19,752 --> 00:25:21,254
the only person there.

478
00:25:21,337 --> 00:25:22,839
Okay.

479
00:25:22,922 --> 00:25:24,674
And, of course, you're his wife.

480
00:25:25,967 --> 00:25:27,927
Um, now, looking for a stranger

481
00:25:28,010 --> 00:25:29,345
who walks in, kills him

482
00:25:29,428 --> 00:25:31,430
while you were sleeping right above

483
00:25:31,514 --> 00:25:34,517
and Daniel was out for a walk
is a shitty strategy:

484
00:25:34,600 --> 00:25:36,018
Samuel had no enemies

485
00:25:36,102 --> 00:25:38,145
-that make...
-Stop, stop.

486
00:25:38,229 --> 00:25:39,814
I did not kill him.

487
00:25:43,818 --> 00:25:45,653
That's not the point.

488
00:25:45,736 --> 00:25:46,946
Really.

489
00:25:47,029 --> 00:25:48,030
Um...

490
00:25:49,991 --> 00:25:53,286
We have to go through
Samuel's personality.

491
00:25:54,036 --> 00:25:55,621
What was he going through lately...

492
00:25:57,665 --> 00:26:01,919
Is there anything that would
seem consistent with a suicide?

493
00:26:08,593 --> 00:26:10,052
I thought about this, obviously,

494
00:26:10,136 --> 00:26:11,846
but I just can't imagine him jumping

495
00:26:11,929 --> 00:26:13,222
with Daniel so close by.

496
00:26:13,306 --> 00:26:16,100
It's just...
I just can't get it in my head.

497
00:26:19,520 --> 00:26:22,398
Yeah, but it's probably
our best defense.

498
00:26:22,481 --> 00:26:24,859
I mean, if they indict you,

499
00:26:24,942 --> 00:26:26,736
it's our only defense.

500
00:26:27,695 --> 00:26:29,113
But I think he fell.

501
00:26:30,656 --> 00:26:32,533
Yeah, but nobody
is going to believe that.

502
00:26:34,493 --> 00:26:35,870
I don't believe that.

503
00:26:38,748 --> 00:26:40,166
I need a smoke.

504
00:26:44,337 --> 00:26:46,255
(website playing Albeniz'
"Asturias (Leyenda)")

505
00:26:56,265 --> 00:26:59,435
(Daniel playing
"Asturias (Leyenda)" on piano)

506
00:27:09,529 --> 00:27:11,364
SANDRA: Vincent...

507
00:27:11,447 --> 00:27:13,908
there is something I, uh,
I want to tell you about.

508
00:27:13,991 --> 00:27:15,826
(Daniel continues playing)

509
00:27:15,910 --> 00:27:18,162
About six months ago,

510
00:27:18,246 --> 00:27:22,500
I wonder if Samuel
didn't swallow some pills.

511
00:27:23,459 --> 00:27:26,629
I found him passed out drunk
on the floor, he vomited.

512
00:27:26,712 --> 00:27:29,674
It was very early
in the morning. I...

513
00:27:29,757 --> 00:27:33,052
There were
some white spots in the vomit,

514
00:27:33,135 --> 00:27:36,639
and I remember wondering
if they were pills.

515
00:27:36,722 --> 00:27:38,933
VINCENT (over phone):
<i>Eh... really?</i>

516
00:27:39,016 --> 00:27:40,017
Yes.

517
00:27:40,101 --> 00:27:41,853
<i>And did you talk to him</i>

518
00:27:41,936 --> 00:27:43,896
<i>-after... afterwards?
</i>-No, he didn't want to talk about it.

519
00:27:44,981 --> 00:27:46,274
<i>Did Daniel see this?</i>

520
00:27:46,357 --> 00:27:47,650
No.

521
00:27:47,733 --> 00:27:50,069
<i>And you... called for a doctor or...</i>

522
00:27:50,152 --> 00:27:51,904
No. No, I didn't realize it

523
00:27:51,988 --> 00:27:54,073
back then,
but looking back at it now,

524
00:27:54,156 --> 00:27:57,702
it seems like it might have been
a suicide attempt, no?

525
00:28:03,541 --> 00:28:05,042
<i>Does anyone know about this?</i>

526
00:28:05,126 --> 00:28:06,586
No.

527
00:28:08,504 --> 00:28:10,965
<i>Okay. Uh, I call you back.</i>

528
00:28:11,048 --> 00:28:12,091
Yes.

529
00:28:12,175 --> 00:28:13,676
<i>-Okay, bye.
</i>-Bye.

530
00:28:16,053 --> 00:28:17,680
(continues playing
"Asturias (Leyenda)")

531
00:28:28,191 --> 00:28:29,650
(inaudible)

532
00:28:39,744 --> 00:28:40,745
(chuckles)

533
00:28:45,708 --> 00:28:47,043
(inaudible)

534
00:29:15,947 --> 00:29:17,323
JUDGE JANVIER (in French):
Is the light too bright?

535
00:29:18,533 --> 00:29:20,493
Want me to lower the blinds?

536
00:29:21,369 --> 00:29:22,787
I'm okay.

537
00:29:22,870 --> 00:29:23,955
JUDGE JANVIER:
Yeah?

538
00:29:24,038 --> 00:29:25,206
Okay.

539
00:29:25,289 --> 00:29:28,751
You didn't tell me
about your parents' arguments.

540
00:29:31,295 --> 00:29:34,715
What do you mean?
I don't really remember any.

541
00:29:36,843 --> 00:29:38,970
When they start yelling,

542
00:29:39,053 --> 00:29:40,555
I prefer to leave.

543
00:29:41,013 --> 00:29:44,141
JUDGE JANVIER:
Can you tell me who was angrier?

544
00:29:45,560 --> 00:29:46,644
No.

545
00:29:49,480 --> 00:29:51,232
JUDGE JANVIER:
Is that why you left

546
00:29:51,315 --> 00:29:53,401
the day your dad died?

547
00:29:53,484 --> 00:29:56,028
No, I just felt like a walk.

548
00:29:56,612 --> 00:29:57,572
JUDGE JANVIER: Okay.

549
00:29:57,655 --> 00:30:00,616
You say you heard your parents
when you left?

550
00:30:01,033 --> 00:30:03,411
Do you remember the conversation?

551
00:30:04,245 --> 00:30:06,539
More or less. It wasn't a fight.

552
00:30:08,875 --> 00:30:11,878
I couldn't hear the words,
but it wasn't...

553
00:30:11,961 --> 00:30:14,714
JUDGE JANVIER:
Then you don't know if it was a fight.

554
00:30:14,797 --> 00:30:18,384
I could tell...
I could hear it wasn't a fight.

555
00:30:18,718 --> 00:30:21,804
JUDGE JANVIER: Daniel, the music
was loud, you were outside.

556
00:30:21,888 --> 00:30:24,515
They were in her bedroom,
two floors up.

557
00:30:25,183 --> 00:30:26,767
How can you be sure?

558
00:30:27,435 --> 00:30:30,229
I wonder if you could hear them at all.

559
00:30:30,313 --> 00:30:32,982
I was just below the open window.

560
00:30:33,065 --> 00:30:34,734
I know what I heard.

561
00:30:37,028 --> 00:30:38,154
JUDGE JANVIER: Okay.

562
00:30:43,826 --> 00:30:44,869
DANIEL:
Is it over?

563
00:30:46,204 --> 00:30:49,624
How can you be so sure
where you were?

564
00:30:50,082 --> 00:30:52,126
DANIEL:
Because I touched the...

565
00:30:52,210 --> 00:30:54,086
gaffer tape on the woodshed.

566
00:30:55,505 --> 00:30:56,797
Gaffer tape?

567
00:30:57,173 --> 00:30:58,591
DANIEL:
When we moved in,

568
00:30:58,841 --> 00:31:02,094
Dad put tape
with different textures everywhere,

569
00:31:02,178 --> 00:31:03,846
-so I could feel my way.
-Right...

570
00:31:04,597 --> 00:31:08,392
I don't really need them now,
but I still touch them.

571
00:31:08,476 --> 00:31:10,436
Each piece feels different,

572
00:31:10,520 --> 00:31:11,938
I wouldn't get it wrong.

573
00:31:13,022 --> 00:31:15,024
I touched the woodshed tape.

574
00:31:16,817 --> 00:31:18,611
So I was under the window.

575
00:31:18,694 --> 00:31:19,820
Okay.

576
00:31:23,866 --> 00:31:25,910
(people chattering)

577
00:31:25,993 --> 00:31:28,120
JUDGE JANVIER (in French):
I transposed what you told me.

578
00:31:28,204 --> 00:31:30,289
But I didn't say it in French.

579
00:31:30,373 --> 00:31:32,542
JUDGE JANVIER:
The volume is what matters here,

580
00:31:32,625 --> 00:31:35,253
and French is easier for everyone.

581
00:31:36,087 --> 00:31:38,297
SANDRA GENDARME:
Hélène, start the music.

582
00:31:38,381 --> 00:31:41,217
("P.I.M.P." by Bacao Rhythm
& Steel Band playing over speakers)

583
00:31:44,428 --> 00:31:45,555
SAMUEL GENDARME:
Did it go well?

584
00:31:45,638 --> 00:31:47,723
Yes, nothing special.

585
00:31:47,807 --> 00:31:49,517
SAMUEL GENDARME:
What's next this afternoon?

586
00:31:49,600 --> 00:31:53,771
I don't know, I'm tired.
I need to work, then I'll rest.

587
00:31:53,855 --> 00:31:55,064
SAMUEL GENDARME:
Not asking me?

588
00:31:55,147 --> 00:31:57,942
SANDRA: I assume you'll
keep working in the attic?

589
00:31:58,901 --> 00:32:00,403
JUDGE JANVIER:
Stop the music.

590
00:32:00,486 --> 00:32:02,071
-ASSISTANT: Stop.
-(music stops)

591
00:32:02,154 --> 00:32:03,114
So?

592
00:32:03,197 --> 00:32:04,448
Did you hear anything?

593
00:32:05,700 --> 00:32:08,286
JUDGE JANVIER:
Let's go again, louder this time.

594
00:32:09,036 --> 00:32:12,373
Louder? But I didn't shout at all.

595
00:32:12,456 --> 00:32:14,000
JUDGE JANVIER:
The point of the reenactment is

596
00:32:14,083 --> 00:32:15,751
to determine a credible volume.

597
00:32:17,086 --> 00:32:18,921
Vincent, I never shouted.

598
00:32:19,672 --> 00:32:23,426
VINCENT: She spoke no louder.
Her son says the voices were calm.

599
00:32:23,509 --> 00:32:24,719
JUDGE JANVIER:
That doesn't hold up.

600
00:32:24,802 --> 00:32:26,345
The music drowns them out.

601
00:32:27,263 --> 00:32:28,639
VINCENT:
My client didn't shout.

602
00:32:28,890 --> 00:32:30,391
She won't shout now.

603
00:32:31,893 --> 00:32:34,979
JUDGE JANVIER:
Miss, please replace Ms. Voyter.

604
00:32:35,062 --> 00:32:37,565
-JUDGE: Come on in.
-ASSISTANT: Come on in, please.

605
00:32:39,150 --> 00:32:40,318
Play the music.

606
00:32:40,985 --> 00:32:42,069
SANDRA GENDARME:
Start the music!

607
00:32:42,153 --> 00:32:43,863
("P.I.M.P" playing over speakers)

608
00:32:44,739 --> 00:32:46,240
SAMUEL GENDARME (loudly):
Did it go well?

609
00:32:46,324 --> 00:32:47,658
(loudly)
Yes, nothing special.

610
00:32:48,117 --> 00:32:49,869
What's next this afternoon?

611
00:32:49,952 --> 00:32:52,872
I don't know, I'm tired.
I need to work, then I'll rest.

612
00:32:57,752 --> 00:32:58,836
(speaks French)

613
00:33:00,046 --> 00:33:01,839
JUDGE JANVIER:
Go again, much louder.

614
00:33:02,882 --> 00:33:04,008
SAMUEL GENDARME (louder):
Was it good?

615
00:33:04,091 --> 00:33:05,551
SANDRA GENDARME (louder):
Yes, nothing special.

616
00:33:06,511 --> 00:33:07,762
What's next this afternoon?

617
00:33:07,845 --> 00:33:11,265
I don't know, I'm tired.
I need to work, then I'll rest.

618
00:33:11,557 --> 00:33:13,476
Not asking me?

619
00:33:13,559 --> 00:33:15,937
SANDRA GENDARME: I assume
you'll keep working in the attic?

620
00:33:16,979 --> 00:33:18,022
SANDRA GENDARME:
Stop the music.

621
00:33:19,440 --> 00:33:21,025
-JUDGE JANVIER: Now they hear it.
-(music stops)

622
00:33:21,108 --> 00:33:21,943
Good.

623
00:33:22,902 --> 00:33:25,029
You do realize that was ridiculous?

624
00:33:25,112 --> 00:33:27,156
JUDGE JANVIER:
Spare me your comments.

625
00:33:27,990 --> 00:33:30,451
DANIEL:
It was calm voices, not like that.

626
00:33:30,535 --> 00:33:33,913
But see, you wouldn't have heard them.

627
00:33:35,998 --> 00:33:37,250
Right?

628
00:33:39,710 --> 00:33:42,797
DANIEL: Can we try
one last time, starting inside?

629
00:33:43,130 --> 00:33:44,924
With calm voices again.

630
00:33:46,842 --> 00:33:47,760
We can.

631
00:33:47,844 --> 00:33:49,136
("P.I.M.P" playing over speakers)

632
00:33:53,683 --> 00:33:55,351
(people speaking faintly in distance)

633
00:34:12,743 --> 00:34:14,411
I made a mistake.

634
00:34:14,495 --> 00:34:15,830
-JUDGE JANVIER: Cut the music.
-(music stops)

635
00:34:15,913 --> 00:34:18,666
This is the tape I touched. I was inside.

636
00:34:20,710 --> 00:34:21,918
I got mixed up.

637
00:34:22,003 --> 00:34:23,713
JUDGE JANVIER:
That's not what you told us.

638
00:34:23,795 --> 00:34:27,382
Zoé Solidor saw you
leave the house after she left.

639
00:34:27,466 --> 00:34:30,261
And your mom says
she spoke to your dad after  that.

640
00:34:31,262 --> 00:34:32,722
I got mixed up.

641
00:34:33,681 --> 00:34:35,099
You got mixed up.

642
00:34:38,561 --> 00:34:40,146
(piano playing "Asturias
(Leyenda)" in distance)

643
00:34:46,235 --> 00:34:47,862
(playing with inconsistent tempo)

644
00:35:18,142 --> 00:35:21,437
(playing Chopin's "Opus 28 No. 4")

645
00:36:01,978 --> 00:36:03,145
(both stop playing)

646
00:36:24,333 --> 00:36:26,294
(in English) This afternoon
was hard, wasn't it?

647
00:36:32,758 --> 00:36:33,968
DANIEL (in French):
I'm mad at myself.

648
00:36:35,386 --> 00:36:37,930
I thought I was sure, and then...

649
00:36:38,306 --> 00:36:39,974
(in English)
But you didn't lie, did you?

650
00:36:41,184 --> 00:36:42,310
No.

651
00:36:44,896 --> 00:36:47,398
I don't want you to change
your memories, you know.

652
00:36:48,316 --> 00:36:51,194
You have to tell them exactly
like you remember it.

653
00:36:52,320 --> 00:36:53,863
That can never hurt me.

654
00:36:58,451 --> 00:36:59,744
Give me your hand.

655
00:37:02,496 --> 00:37:03,664
Oui?

656
00:37:05,541 --> 00:37:07,168
(chuckles)

657
00:37:07,251 --> 00:37:09,378
(Sandra laughs)

658
00:37:09,462 --> 00:37:11,297
What do we do now?

659
00:37:11,380 --> 00:37:13,341
Huh? Huh?

660
00:37:13,424 --> 00:37:15,051
You want a drink?

661
00:37:15,134 --> 00:37:16,219
Whisky?

662
00:37:16,302 --> 00:37:17,970
(both laugh)

663
00:37:18,846 --> 00:37:20,014
Come on.

664
00:37:20,097 --> 00:37:21,474
SANDRA: Ahh...

665
00:37:21,557 --> 00:37:22,642
-SANDRA: Oh.
-DANIEL: Oh, sorry.

666
00:37:22,725 --> 00:37:23,726
SANDRA:
It's all right.

667
00:37:23,809 --> 00:37:25,186
(kisses)

668
00:37:27,396 --> 00:37:28,856
(in French)
All I can say is,

669
00:37:28,940 --> 00:37:33,486
the interrogation is in progress
and may continue for a while.

670
00:37:33,569 --> 00:37:36,239
REPORTER:
She's been in there for eight hours.

671
00:37:36,322 --> 00:37:37,657
Is she in trouble?

672
00:37:38,366 --> 00:37:40,535
Sandra Voyter is not in trouble.

673
00:37:40,618 --> 00:37:42,453
She maintains her innocence,

674
00:37:42,537 --> 00:37:44,539
so there will be no confession.

675
00:37:44,622 --> 00:37:48,167
REPORTER: You're confident,
but we've heard about a recording.

676
00:37:48,251 --> 00:37:49,752
Is it incriminating?

677
00:37:50,294 --> 00:37:52,213
You're not listening.

678
00:37:52,296 --> 00:37:56,050
She has not been indicted,
so nothing is incriminating.

679
00:37:56,801 --> 00:37:58,928
The so-called video is a myth so far.

680
00:37:59,011 --> 00:38:01,055
We've had no access to it.

681
00:38:01,138 --> 00:38:03,516
REPORTER:
So, you confirm it's a video?

682
00:38:04,225 --> 00:38:08,229
No, I confirm nothing.
I said precisely the opposite.

683
00:38:08,312 --> 00:38:10,857
REPORTER: If there's nothing new,
why the summons?

684
00:38:10,940 --> 00:38:13,234
I don't know what to tell you.

685
00:38:13,317 --> 00:38:15,903
We don't understand it
ourselves. Thank you.

686
00:38:18,072 --> 00:38:19,574
PROSECUTOR (in French):
Thank you for coming

687
00:38:20,575 --> 00:38:22,827
for the public prosecutor's statement.

688
00:38:24,537 --> 00:38:27,999
So, Sandra Voyter was indicted
this morning at 8:30 a.m.

689
00:38:28,499 --> 00:38:32,336
The investigation revealed elements
that justify this decision.

690
00:38:33,171 --> 00:38:35,131
Three elements in particular.

691
00:38:35,214 --> 00:38:38,593
Analyses of Mr. Maleski's blood spatter

692
00:38:38,676 --> 00:38:41,345
found at the couple's domicile

693
00:38:41,429 --> 00:38:46,184
indicate he may have received
a blunt force blow to the head

694
00:38:46,267 --> 00:38:49,312
when he was on the third-floor balcony.

695
00:38:49,812 --> 00:38:51,355
In addition,

696
00:38:51,439 --> 00:38:53,900
the reenactment done three days ago

697
00:38:53,983 --> 00:38:56,736
brought to light
a number of discrepancies.

698
00:38:57,486 --> 00:38:58,696
Lastly,

699
00:38:58,779 --> 00:39:04,118
a file was discovered on a USB key
belonging to Mr. Maleski.

700
00:39:04,202 --> 00:39:06,829
All I can say about it, for now,

701
00:39:06,913 --> 00:39:10,249
is that it's an audio recording
of the couple,

702
00:39:10,333 --> 00:39:11,959
made the day before his death.

703
00:39:13,252 --> 00:39:15,296
(people chattering)

704
00:39:15,379 --> 00:39:19,300
(in French) As I'm trying to tell you,
she can't come sign herself

705
00:39:19,383 --> 00:39:23,179
because she's held up
at the courthouse.

706
00:39:23,262 --> 00:39:26,140
So it'll be me,
her lawyer Vincent Renzi,

707
00:39:26,224 --> 00:39:29,101
coming to get the documents for her.

708
00:39:29,894 --> 00:39:31,562
No, I can't come at 11.

709
00:39:32,605 --> 00:39:34,899
I can be there in 20 minutes?

710
00:39:35,900 --> 00:39:38,319
Okay. Thanks, be right there.

711
00:39:38,402 --> 00:39:39,820
NOUR:
We have good news.

712
00:39:40,571 --> 00:39:44,242
The judge this afternoon
is not Da Silva, it's Bollène.

713
00:39:44,325 --> 00:39:45,576
VINCENT: Okay.

714
00:39:45,660 --> 00:39:46,953
I'm off to the bank.

715
00:39:47,036 --> 00:39:48,663
NOUR:
And the home equity loan?

716
00:39:48,746 --> 00:39:51,082
Ah, si, si, si.

717
00:39:51,165 --> 00:39:54,836
Less than we hoped.
They have money problems.

718
00:39:54,919 --> 00:39:56,587
Outstanding credit, etcetera.

719
00:39:56,671 --> 00:39:59,674
The bank will only do 50,000.

720
00:39:59,757 --> 00:40:02,718
NOUR:
Bail will be more than that.

721
00:40:03,886 --> 00:40:06,180
(in French)
Her son is a witness.

722
00:40:06,264 --> 00:40:08,349
He'll be testifying in court.

723
00:40:08,432 --> 00:40:12,770
There is obviously a risk
of her exerting pressure on him.

724
00:40:12,854 --> 00:40:14,772
As a consequence,

725
00:40:14,856 --> 00:40:17,525
release on bail is not an option.

726
00:40:17,608 --> 00:40:21,779
I'm asking you to place Ms. Voyter
in detention pending trial.

727
00:40:22,613 --> 00:40:25,283
Thank you.
Over to you, Ms. Boudaoud.

728
00:40:25,366 --> 00:40:28,661
Judge, how can we consider her
a flight risk,

729
00:40:28,744 --> 00:40:31,080
when she's responsible for her son?

730
00:40:31,163 --> 00:40:32,707
<i>That makes no sense.</i>

731
00:40:32,790 --> 00:40:34,917
<i>With a visually impaired child?</i>

732
00:40:35,001 --> 00:40:37,587
<i>And she's all over the media.</i>

733
00:40:37,670 --> 00:40:40,798
<i>Separating them
could compound his trauma.</i>

734
00:40:40,882 --> 00:40:44,260
<i>He had an accident at the age of four</i>

735
00:40:44,343 --> 00:40:45,428
<i>that damaged his sight.</i>

736
00:40:45,511 --> 00:40:47,180
<i>He's been traumatized,</i>

737
00:40:47,263 --> 00:40:49,891
<i>both psychologically
and emotionally.</i>

738
00:40:49,974 --> 00:40:50,975
SANDRA: Oh.

739
00:40:52,852 --> 00:40:54,562
REPORTER 1:
Ms. Boudaoud, your reaction?

740
00:40:55,313 --> 00:40:59,066
The judge's decision
is rare enough to merit praise.

741
00:40:59,150 --> 00:41:02,737
A judge refusing to give in
to repressive reflexes

742
00:41:02,820 --> 00:41:05,448
is a healthy sign,
especially in such a case.

743
00:41:05,531 --> 00:41:08,993
We feel the release
under judicial supervision

744
00:41:09,076 --> 00:41:11,245
underscores the weakness
of the case.

745
00:41:11,537 --> 00:41:13,039
REPORTER 2:
Is your client relieved?

746
00:41:16,000 --> 00:41:19,212
This is a rare decision
in a homicide accusation,

747
00:41:19,295 --> 00:41:21,881
and reads like
a repudiation of Judge Janvier.

748
00:41:21,964 --> 00:41:25,051
Reactions in the hallways
have been intense.

749
00:41:25,134 --> 00:41:28,221
<i>I quote,
"This decision is dangerous.</i>

750
00:41:28,513 --> 00:41:31,265
<i>"The suspect will be reunited
with a major witness.</i>

751
00:41:31,724 --> 00:41:34,936
<i>It's a real concern
for the upcoming trial."</i>

752
00:41:47,156 --> 00:41:48,950
VINCENT (in English): How could
you not tell me about it?

753
00:41:49,033 --> 00:41:50,618
SANDRA (in English):
I had no idea he recorded it.

754
00:41:50,701 --> 00:41:52,078
VINCENT:
Even if he hadn't, I mean,

755
00:41:52,161 --> 00:41:54,080
you had a fight
the day before he died.

756
00:42:02,880 --> 00:42:04,006
(car door closes)

757
00:42:12,348 --> 00:42:16,394
SANDRA:
That recording is not reality.

758
00:42:17,562 --> 00:42:18,980
It is a part of it, maybe.

759
00:42:19,063 --> 00:42:21,482
If you have
an extreme moment in life,

760
00:42:21,566 --> 00:42:23,192
an emotional peak,
and you focus on it,

761
00:42:23,276 --> 00:42:25,653
of course, it crushes everything.

762
00:42:25,736 --> 00:42:27,738
It may seem like irrefutable proof,

763
00:42:27,822 --> 00:42:29,615
but actually warps everything.

764
00:42:29,699 --> 00:42:31,033
It's not reality.

765
00:42:31,117 --> 00:42:33,119
It's our voices, that's true,
but it's not who we are.

766
00:42:33,202 --> 00:42:36,247
I don't give a fuck
about what is reality, okay?

767
00:42:36,330 --> 00:42:38,541
You-- you need to start
seeing yourself

768
00:42:38,624 --> 00:42:40,835
the way others are going
to perceive you.

769
00:42:40,918 --> 00:42:42,712
A trial is not about
"The Truth," it's about...

770
00:42:42,795 --> 00:42:44,172
I didn't know
there would be a trial.

771
00:42:44,255 --> 00:42:45,882
VINCENT: Well, there is.

772
00:42:56,517 --> 00:43:00,605
VINCENT: Now, what
will really count is, uh,

773
00:43:00,688 --> 00:43:02,732
who you have around you.

774
00:43:02,815 --> 00:43:04,066
There's nobody around me.

775
00:43:04,150 --> 00:43:06,444
-Yes, there is Daniel.
-Yeah.

776
00:43:06,527 --> 00:43:07,987
Daniel is important.

777
00:43:09,739 --> 00:43:12,283
And didn't you and Samuel
have any...

778
00:43:12,366 --> 00:43:13,826
any friends, someone...

779
00:43:13,910 --> 00:43:15,369
I should never have come here.

780
00:43:15,453 --> 00:43:17,997
I didn't want to,
I was so happy in London.

781
00:43:21,083 --> 00:43:22,877
It was him.
He insisted so much.

782
00:43:22,960 --> 00:43:26,047
He said there'd be
no more distractions from work,

783
00:43:26,130 --> 00:43:28,633
it would solve our financial problems...

784
00:43:28,716 --> 00:43:30,801
(dry chuckle)

785
00:43:34,680 --> 00:43:37,266
I left my shithole in Germany

786
00:43:37,350 --> 00:43:39,393
and ended up stuck here...
in his shithole.

787
00:43:39,477 --> 00:43:41,354
It's fucking absurd,
isn't it, come on?

788
00:43:46,859 --> 00:43:48,611
(people chattering in French)

789
00:43:49,529 --> 00:43:50,613
(Sandra and Nour, in French)
Hello.

790
00:43:52,740 --> 00:43:54,283
(in French)
Hi, kitten.

791
00:43:56,160 --> 00:43:57,828
NOUR (in French):
This is Ms. Berger,

792
00:43:57,912 --> 00:44:00,331
appointed by the Justice Minister.

793
00:44:00,414 --> 00:44:01,832
VINCENT: Bonjour.

794
00:44:01,916 --> 00:44:03,876
Vincent Renzi, I work with Nour.

795
00:44:03,960 --> 00:44:07,046
-NOUR: She'll be here regularly, with...
-MARGE: Bonjour.

796
00:44:07,839 --> 00:44:09,632
Daniel, and with you.

797
00:44:10,550 --> 00:44:12,176
The frequency will be specified.

798
00:44:12,260 --> 00:44:14,262
She's here...

799
00:44:15,263 --> 00:44:17,765
to ensure that everything goes well.

800
00:44:18,349 --> 00:44:22,144
And that no one
tries to influence Daniel,

801
00:44:22,228 --> 00:44:26,148
or make him say things
he doesn't want to say at the trial.

802
00:44:27,191 --> 00:44:31,028
The judge says
you must speak French in her presence.

803
00:44:33,155 --> 00:44:34,115
Right.

804
00:44:37,785 --> 00:44:38,828
NOUR: That's it.

805
00:44:40,913 --> 00:44:43,124
May I speak with Daniel in private?

806
00:44:43,666 --> 00:44:44,750
MARGE: Mm-hmm?

807
00:44:45,668 --> 00:44:47,920
VINCENT (in English):
Uh, okay, so we go?

808
00:44:48,004 --> 00:44:49,005
VINCENT (in French):
I'll call you.

809
00:44:49,088 --> 00:44:52,216
MARGE (in French): Your mother
will give us space to get acquainted.

810
00:44:58,973 --> 00:45:00,600
MARGE:
My name is Marge.

811
00:45:01,225 --> 00:45:03,102
We'll see each other a lot.

812
00:45:04,061 --> 00:45:06,230
Do you know why I'm here?

813
00:45:06,314 --> 00:45:08,065
-DANIEL: Mm. Mm-hmm.
-Are you okay with it?

814
00:45:09,525 --> 00:45:11,402
You can consider me a friend.

815
00:45:12,486 --> 00:45:14,655
Or not. That's your choice.

816
00:45:14,739 --> 00:45:16,073
What do you think?

817
00:45:16,824 --> 00:45:18,284
It's okay, I don't...

818
00:45:19,243 --> 00:45:20,995
I don't need us to be friends.

819
00:45:24,790 --> 00:45:27,460
MARGE: Well, I'm here
to protect your testimony.

820
00:45:28,211 --> 00:45:30,046
The law sent me, and...

821
00:45:30,880 --> 00:45:33,257
the law can't be someone's friend.

822
00:45:33,341 --> 00:45:36,636
Otherwise it couldn't be
someone else's friend,

823
00:45:36,719 --> 00:45:39,180
and the law must be
the same for everyone.

824
00:45:40,473 --> 00:45:42,767
So you're right,
I can't be your friend.

825
00:45:44,227 --> 00:45:47,813
You just have to tell me
if anything feels strange,

826
00:45:47,897 --> 00:45:50,775
if there's a problem,

827
00:45:50,858 --> 00:45:51,984
I don't know,

828
00:45:52,068 --> 00:45:53,945
for example with your mom,

829
00:45:54,028 --> 00:45:55,488
regarding the trial.

830
00:45:57,323 --> 00:46:01,285
I usually discuss stuff like that
with my friends.

831
00:46:03,871 --> 00:46:04,830
Right.

832
00:46:05,498 --> 00:46:08,209
Maybe this time
you don't really have a choice.

833
00:46:20,680 --> 00:46:22,014
(deeply exhales)

834
00:46:28,312 --> 00:46:30,022
-DANIEL: S'il vous plaît.
-SANDRA: S'il vous plaît.

835
00:46:30,106 --> 00:46:32,400
DANIEL (in French):
...with chocolate chips...

836
00:46:32,483 --> 00:46:34,485
(Sandra repeats Daniel)

837
00:46:34,569 --> 00:46:36,070
DANIEL:
and raspberries...

838
00:46:36,153 --> 00:46:37,238
(Sandra repeats Daniel)

839
00:46:37,321 --> 00:46:40,116
DANIEL: I know it doesn't exist,
but I want it.

840
00:46:40,199 --> 00:46:45,079
(Sandra laughs and repeats Daniel)

841
00:46:46,080 --> 00:46:48,583
The archduchess' socks...

842
00:46:48,666 --> 00:46:50,168
(Sandra partially repeats Daniel)

843
00:46:50,251 --> 00:46:51,169
SANDRA: What?

844
00:46:51,252 --> 00:46:52,211
(both laugh)

845
00:46:52,295 --> 00:46:55,381
DANIEL:
The archduchess' socks...

846
00:46:55,464 --> 00:46:57,967
(Sandra repeats Daniel)

847
00:46:58,050 --> 00:46:59,886
(church bell ringing in distance)

848
00:47:27,163 --> 00:47:28,706
SANDRA (in English):
<i>He was-- He was one of</i>

849
00:47:28,789 --> 00:47:30,333
the only persons I knew,

850
00:47:30,416 --> 00:47:32,919
when he walked into a room,

851
00:47:33,002 --> 00:47:35,171
something shifted.

852
00:47:35,254 --> 00:47:37,590
The-- The atmosphere changed.

853
00:47:37,673 --> 00:47:39,842
And I suppose
that's charm, isn't it?

854
00:47:39,926 --> 00:47:43,137
It's, um...
I-I fell in love with his charm.

855
00:47:44,263 --> 00:47:45,431
Um...

856
00:47:47,308 --> 00:47:49,977
I'd spent my whole life
not understanding

857
00:47:50,061 --> 00:47:52,980
my family and friends,

858
00:47:53,064 --> 00:47:54,482
and then he came along,

859
00:47:54,565 --> 00:47:56,400
and I felt like...

860
00:47:57,818 --> 00:47:59,695
I understood what he was saying,

861
00:47:59,779 --> 00:48:02,281
the signals
that he was sending me.

862
00:48:02,365 --> 00:48:03,824
The, um...

863
00:48:03,908 --> 00:48:05,785
We didn't necessarily agree,

864
00:48:05,868 --> 00:48:07,119
but we had...

865
00:48:08,579 --> 00:48:10,706
Uh, we had things
to tell each other.

866
00:48:10,790 --> 00:48:11,874
(lighter pings)

867
00:48:11,958 --> 00:48:13,209
And I realized it later

868
00:48:13,292 --> 00:48:14,752
when it was gone, so...

869
00:48:14,836 --> 00:48:16,420
Mm. Don't say it's gone.

870
00:48:18,172 --> 00:48:21,843
Just, um, focus on him,
how you met.

871
00:48:24,136 --> 00:48:26,097
When we met,
he'd just gotten a job

872
00:48:26,180 --> 00:48:28,474
at a university in London,

873
00:48:28,558 --> 00:48:30,977
so, ahem, we moved there together.

874
00:48:33,229 --> 00:48:34,480
He was a great teacher.

875
00:48:34,564 --> 00:48:35,648
(laughs) He was...

876
00:48:35,731 --> 00:48:36,983
He had a... He had a way

877
00:48:37,066 --> 00:48:40,862
of making everything sound alive
and accessible, it was great.

878
00:48:42,697 --> 00:48:45,908
But, um, that wasn't really enough,

879
00:48:45,992 --> 00:48:49,537
heh, so deep down,

880
00:48:49,620 --> 00:48:52,164
what he really wanted to do
was to write.

881
00:48:52,999 --> 00:48:55,293
And he was working on
a novel for years.

882
00:48:55,376 --> 00:48:56,586
I-I watched him struggle.

883
00:48:56,669 --> 00:48:58,254
It was hard.

884
00:48:58,337 --> 00:48:59,547
Um...

885
00:49:03,134 --> 00:49:04,844
And I came to realize

886
00:49:04,927 --> 00:49:08,055
that his relationship
with time, with, with work,

887
00:49:08,139 --> 00:49:12,351
was complicated,
unlike for me, for example.

888
00:49:12,435 --> 00:49:14,937
VINCENT: No, stop com--
Stop comparing yourself to him.

889
00:49:15,021 --> 00:49:16,105
Just, uh...

890
00:49:16,189 --> 00:49:17,815
go back to your relationship.

891
00:49:21,527 --> 00:49:25,072
SANDRA: Our relationship
revolved around...

892
00:49:25,156 --> 00:49:26,574
intellectual stimulation,

893
00:49:26,657 --> 00:49:29,619
even if it meant neglecting
everything else.

894
00:49:29,702 --> 00:49:30,786
Everything else?

895
00:49:31,871 --> 00:49:32,997
(in French)
Meaning Daniel?

896
00:49:34,874 --> 00:49:36,834
We should mention Daniel early on.

897
00:49:36,918 --> 00:49:38,669
VINCENT (in English):
The accident.

898
00:49:38,753 --> 00:49:41,214
SANDRA:
Okay. I didn't know it was sent.

899
00:49:42,340 --> 00:49:43,716
(laughs)

900
00:49:44,675 --> 00:49:45,760
VINCENT: It's okay?

901
00:49:45,843 --> 00:49:47,428
It's okay.

902
00:49:47,512 --> 00:49:49,305
It's just that, I didn't know

903
00:49:49,388 --> 00:49:52,558
that it was so, uh,
like this. Okay.

904
00:49:52,642 --> 00:49:53,684
Um...

905
00:49:53,768 --> 00:49:54,936
(door opens)

906
00:49:56,521 --> 00:49:57,897
Everything changed

907
00:49:57,980 --> 00:49:59,982
after the accident.

908
00:50:00,066 --> 00:50:02,068
Uh, Daniel was four.

909
00:50:03,736 --> 00:50:05,112
(sighs) That day,

910
00:50:05,196 --> 00:50:09,450
Samuel was supposed
to pick him up from school.

911
00:50:09,534 --> 00:50:11,536
But he was on a roll
with his writing,

912
00:50:11,619 --> 00:50:14,789
so he called a babysitter
at the last minute

913
00:50:14,872 --> 00:50:16,874
and the babysitter showed up late.

914
00:50:18,167 --> 00:50:19,544
And as they were crossing
the street,

915
00:50:19,627 --> 00:50:21,087
a motorcycle hit Daniel,

916
00:50:21,170 --> 00:50:23,714
his optic nerve
was permanently damaged.

917
00:50:29,136 --> 00:50:31,138
After that,

918
00:50:31,222 --> 00:50:34,559
Samuel became obsessive about it,

919
00:50:34,642 --> 00:50:36,227
he blamed himself on a loop:

920
00:50:36,310 --> 00:50:38,062
If only he'd
come pick him up on time...

921
00:50:38,145 --> 00:50:39,272
(vocalizes)

922
00:50:41,065 --> 00:50:43,526
He was overcome with guilt...

923
00:50:46,487 --> 00:50:48,656
and perhaps he never
truly escaped that feeling.

924
00:50:50,366 --> 00:50:54,954
We spent that whole year
at the hospital with Daniel.

925
00:50:56,289 --> 00:50:59,125
We began having
financial problems...

926
00:51:00,376 --> 00:51:03,254
and Samuel started taking
antidepressants.

927
00:51:04,714 --> 00:51:06,215
Sorry, can we please

928
00:51:06,299 --> 00:51:08,050
keep that clean, Vincent?

929
00:51:08,134 --> 00:51:09,886
I would really like to protect him,

930
00:51:09,969 --> 00:51:12,054
and his image, and spare Daniel.

931
00:51:14,098 --> 00:51:15,308
VINCENT:
We'll try.

932
00:51:15,391 --> 00:51:17,143
Okay.

933
00:51:17,226 --> 00:51:19,061
But it would be like that--
I have to--

934
00:51:19,145 --> 00:51:20,730
-I have to--
-VINCENT: Yes.

935
00:51:20,813 --> 00:51:23,232
I have to admit things.

936
00:51:25,234 --> 00:51:27,153
VINCENT (stammers):
You have to prepare yourself

937
00:51:27,236 --> 00:51:29,572
-to tell everything...
-(blows raspberry)

938
00:51:29,655 --> 00:51:31,616
and the challenge is
to do it in French.

939
00:51:33,868 --> 00:51:34,911
Okay.

940
00:51:40,666 --> 00:51:42,126
<i>(Daniel practicing Albeniz'
"Asturias (Leyenda)")</i>

941
00:52:12,448 --> 00:52:14,575
{\an8}ONE YEAR LATER

942
00:52:19,330 --> 00:52:21,165
{\an8}-ZOE (in English): <i>Okay...
-(Sandra laughs)</i>

943
00:52:21,249 --> 00:52:22,750
ZOE: <i>Are you really
interested in what...</i>

944
00:52:22,834 --> 00:52:24,001
SANDRA:
<i>In what interests you?</i>

945
00:52:24,085 --> 00:52:26,128
<i>Come on! Sure!</i>

946
00:52:26,212 --> 00:52:27,630
(playing over speakers)
<i>I never see anybody.</i>

947
00:52:27,713 --> 00:52:29,131
<i>I work here all day long.</i>

948
00:52:29,215 --> 00:52:30,132
<i>You come to see me,</i>

949
00:52:30,216 --> 00:52:31,217
<i>of course, you interest me.</i>

950
00:52:31,300 --> 00:52:32,343
<i>("P.I.M.P." playing in background)</i>

951
00:52:32,426 --> 00:52:34,595
ZOE:
<i>Okay, um...</i>

952
00:52:34,679 --> 00:52:36,472
-ZOE: <i>I run.
</i>-SANDRA: <i>Mm-hmm.</i>

953
00:52:36,556 --> 00:52:38,891
<i>It's one of my favorite things to do.</i>

954
00:52:38,975 --> 00:52:40,893
<i>It makes me feel high,
like I'm on drugs.</i>

955
00:52:40,977 --> 00:52:44,230
SANDRA (laughs): <i>What do
you know about drugs then?</i>

956
00:52:44,313 --> 00:52:46,065
<i>-Oh, a lot...
-That's the next question.</i>

957
00:52:46,148 --> 00:52:47,358
<i>(Zoe exhales; Sandra laughing)</i>

958
00:52:47,441 --> 00:52:48,526
ZOE: <i>Big subject.</i>

959
00:52:49,986 --> 00:52:51,279
SANDRA: <i>Maybe you don't
write everything down.</i>

960
00:52:51,362 --> 00:52:52,405
ZOE:
<i>No, no, surely not.</i>

961
00:52:52,488 --> 00:52:54,740
<i>("P.I.M.P." restarts in the background)</i>

962
00:52:57,493 --> 00:52:58,828
SANDRA (laughs):
<i>I told you...</i>

963
00:52:58,911 --> 00:53:01,205
<i>we should've done this in Grenoble.</i>

964
00:53:01,289 --> 00:53:02,623
ZOE: <i>It's-- It's fine.</i>

965
00:53:02,707 --> 00:53:04,417
<i>I'll write your answers down.</i>

966
00:53:04,500 --> 00:53:05,668
(playback stops)

967
00:53:07,587 --> 00:53:08,629
ADVOCATE GENERAL:
Bon.

968
00:53:10,089 --> 00:53:11,632
ADVOCATE GENERAL (in French):
Do you confirm this is

969
00:53:11,716 --> 00:53:13,593
your interview with Ms. Voyter?

970
00:53:13,926 --> 00:53:15,052
Yes.

971
00:53:15,136 --> 00:53:18,556
She refuses to talk about herself,
yet that's why you came.

972
00:53:18,848 --> 00:53:21,684
-ZOE: I came to talk about her work.
-Yes, yes.

973
00:53:21,767 --> 00:53:24,687
Right, but by constantly
changing the subject,

974
00:53:24,770 --> 00:53:27,231
what was she looking for,
do you suppose?

975
00:53:27,982 --> 00:53:31,027
ZOE: We can hear it.
She asks about me.

976
00:53:31,736 --> 00:53:35,823
She seemed to enjoy talking
about me more than herself.

977
00:53:36,741 --> 00:53:38,951
Was she inciting you
to talk about yourself?

978
00:53:39,744 --> 00:53:40,745
ZOE: Inciting...

979
00:53:41,662 --> 00:53:43,748
No, I wouldn't say that.

980
00:53:43,831 --> 00:53:46,334
She wasn't manipulative,
just relaxed.

981
00:53:46,417 --> 00:53:50,004
It felt natural.
She seemed to enjoy the conversation.

982
00:53:50,087 --> 00:53:54,342
You say "relaxed."
We hear her serve you wine at 1:45.

983
00:53:54,425 --> 00:53:56,969
Had she been drinking
before you arrived?

984
00:53:57,762 --> 00:53:58,679
ZOE: I think so.

985
00:53:58,763 --> 00:54:01,891
Would you say she did her utmost

986
00:54:01,974 --> 00:54:03,392
to make you comfortable,

987
00:54:03,476 --> 00:54:05,561
more than you might've expected

988
00:54:05,645 --> 00:54:08,272
when interviewing a writer?

989
00:54:08,356 --> 00:54:10,858
I wouldn't say that, no.

990
00:54:11,108 --> 00:54:14,195
It seemed like Sandra... Ms. Voyter,

991
00:54:14,278 --> 00:54:17,281
needed to escape, to decompress.

992
00:54:17,365 --> 00:54:18,533
-ADVOCATE GENERAL: Escape?
-Oui.

993
00:54:18,616 --> 00:54:22,245
Did you know that Sandra,
as you call her, was bisexual?

994
00:54:24,038 --> 00:54:24,997
ZOE: No.

995
00:54:25,081 --> 00:54:26,874
Did you sense it?

996
00:54:26,958 --> 00:54:27,959
ZOE: No.

997
00:54:28,960 --> 00:54:32,797
Hearing the conversation now,
with hindsight,

998
00:54:33,756 --> 00:54:35,800
would you call it seduction?

999
00:54:37,385 --> 00:54:41,389
I felt, and she told me herself,
that she didn't have

1000
00:54:41,472 --> 00:54:45,184
much of a social life
or many chances to talk

1001
00:54:45,268 --> 00:54:46,435
to new people.

1002
00:54:46,686 --> 00:54:50,815
I suppose you could call that
a form of seduction.

1003
00:54:51,399 --> 00:54:55,236
The court needs to know
if you would call it that.

1004
00:54:55,945 --> 00:54:57,530
Seduction means several things.

1005
00:54:57,613 --> 00:55:00,408
But the word seduction
always implies some...

1006
00:55:00,950 --> 00:55:01,868
seduction.

1007
00:55:01,951 --> 00:55:03,286
VINCENT:
The witness's answer

1008
00:55:03,536 --> 00:55:07,331
is clear enough,
as to what she means by seduction.

1009
00:55:07,415 --> 00:55:10,960
Ms. Voyter kept expressing
her interest in you.

1010
00:55:11,043 --> 00:55:13,588
She wanted to do the interview
in Grenoble.

1011
00:55:14,338 --> 00:55:15,464
Didn't you sense...

1012
00:55:15,548 --> 00:55:17,091
VINCENT:
She answered that question.

1013
00:55:17,175 --> 00:55:20,011
JUSTICE MINISTER: Not very clearly.
Please answer, Miss Solidor.

1014
00:55:20,094 --> 00:55:21,804
ZOE: Could you call me Ms.?

1015
00:55:22,388 --> 00:55:24,974
I dislike being reduced
to a marital status.

1016
00:55:25,057 --> 00:55:27,143
JUSTICE MINISTER:
Of course. That wasn't my intention.

1017
00:55:27,226 --> 00:55:29,937
-(Advocate General chuckles)
-I didn't feel seduced in the moment.

1018
00:55:30,021 --> 00:55:32,648
ADVOCATE GENERAL:
So you did wonder afterwards?

1019
00:55:33,733 --> 00:55:36,277
I found it atypical, nothing more.

1020
00:55:36,360 --> 00:55:40,448
How did you interpret the song
Samuel Maleski played?

1021
00:55:41,657 --> 00:55:43,743
I felt tension around the noise.

1022
00:55:43,826 --> 00:55:48,206
Samuel Maleski imposing
his presence without showing himself.

1023
00:55:48,539 --> 00:55:50,249
And Sandra's reaction...

1024
00:55:50,333 --> 00:55:51,834
What was her reaction?

1025
00:55:53,961 --> 00:55:55,838
She was a bit annoyed.

1026
00:55:56,547 --> 00:55:59,300
And when the song started over?

1027
00:55:59,717 --> 00:56:01,594
He was playing it on a loop.

1028
00:56:01,677 --> 00:56:02,637
(laughs) Right.

1029
00:56:02,720 --> 00:56:04,180
Clearly...

1030
00:56:04,639 --> 00:56:05,932
good deduction.

1031
00:56:06,015 --> 00:56:09,018
But how did it feel to you
in the moment?

1032
00:56:09,685 --> 00:56:11,312
ZOE:
It added to the strangeness.

1033
00:56:12,063 --> 00:56:14,565
I felt my presence was less...

1034
00:56:16,234 --> 00:56:17,527
It was less relaxed.

1035
00:56:17,610 --> 00:56:19,362
So you clearly felt tension.

1036
00:56:19,445 --> 00:56:22,281
-VINCENT: You're nitpicking.
-No, just clarifying.

1037
00:56:22,365 --> 00:56:23,991
Did you feel tension?

1038
00:56:24,242 --> 00:56:25,326
ZOE: Yes.

1039
00:56:25,409 --> 00:56:30,665
Did you feel that Mr. Maleski,
by playing that music,

1040
00:56:30,748 --> 00:56:34,085
wanted to disrupt, or interrupt,
your interview?

1041
00:56:34,710 --> 00:56:36,963
That was my first thought, yes.

1042
00:56:37,839 --> 00:56:42,176
But it's hard to read the intentions
of someone you can't see.

1043
00:56:42,802 --> 00:56:44,637
That's what they pay me for!

1044
00:56:44,720 --> 00:56:46,389
(gallery laughs)

1045
00:56:46,472 --> 00:56:47,765
Sandra Voyter,

1046
00:56:48,266 --> 00:56:51,519
you sought a connection
to divert the interview.

1047
00:56:51,602 --> 00:56:53,020
Correct?

1048
00:56:53,104 --> 00:56:54,730
That's a leading question.

1049
00:56:54,814 --> 00:56:56,524
There was no seduction.

1050
00:56:56,858 --> 00:56:58,985
ADVOCATE GENERAL: My question
concerns your connection.

1051
00:56:59,068 --> 00:57:03,239
In the recording you're chummy,
laughing, drinking wine.

1052
00:57:03,322 --> 00:57:06,409
Were you seeking escape
from a difficult home life

1053
00:57:06,492 --> 00:57:08,661
by connecting
with this young woman?

1054
00:57:08,744 --> 00:57:11,330
NOUR: Ms. Voyter
did not initiate the meeting.

1055
00:57:11,581 --> 00:57:13,499
Please answer, Ms. Voyter.

1056
00:57:14,292 --> 00:57:15,251
Uh...

1057
00:57:15,334 --> 00:57:17,545
Yes, I found her surprising.

1058
00:57:17,837 --> 00:57:20,756
I hadn't seen anyone new
in a while.

1059
00:57:20,840 --> 00:57:23,217
And yes, I needed a drink.

1060
00:57:23,301 --> 00:57:27,680
This person was intelligent
and nice, nothing more.

1061
00:57:28,347 --> 00:57:32,268
That interview was hardly enough
to base a thesis on!

1062
00:57:32,351 --> 00:57:34,353
VINCENT:
She can have a laugh with a student

1063
00:57:34,437 --> 00:57:36,772
whose questions don't thrill her.

1064
00:57:37,064 --> 00:57:40,234
Would you say the music
Mr. Maleski played

1065
00:57:40,318 --> 00:57:42,403
so aggressively

1066
00:57:42,486 --> 00:57:44,447
indicated he was jealous of you,

1067
00:57:44,530 --> 00:57:46,866
or Miss... Ms. Solidor? Sorry.

1068
00:57:46,949 --> 00:57:49,660
The music was a cover
of 50 Cent's "P.I.M.P.,"

1069
00:57:49,744 --> 00:57:52,079
a deeply misogynistic song.

1070
00:57:52,163 --> 00:57:54,040
It was an instrumental version.

1071
00:57:54,123 --> 00:57:55,583
JUSTICE MINISTER:
Answer, please.

1072
00:57:55,833 --> 00:57:59,670
Could your husband's song choice
express his jealousy?

1073
00:57:59,754 --> 00:58:00,796
SANDRA:
I can answer.

1074
00:58:02,215 --> 00:58:05,718
He often played that song.
I doubt it was intentional.

1075
00:58:06,761 --> 00:58:09,972
He loved loud music, it relaxed him.

1076
00:58:11,641 --> 00:58:14,477
He had purposefully installed...

1077
00:58:14,560 --> 00:58:15,770
(scoffs)

1078
00:58:15,853 --> 00:58:17,647
(in English)
How do you say "speaker," sorry?

1079
00:58:17,730 --> 00:58:18,689
(Vincent translates "speaker")

1080
00:58:18,773 --> 00:58:21,359
(in French)
a powerful speaker... sorry.

1081
00:58:22,235 --> 00:58:24,362
He worked a lot, it was noisy...

1082
00:58:24,445 --> 00:58:27,823
Ms. Solidor says
you ended the interview over that.

1083
00:58:27,907 --> 00:58:30,451
-Is that true?
-She never said that.

1084
00:58:30,535 --> 00:58:31,827
JUSTICE MINISTER:
If the defense

1085
00:58:32,453 --> 00:58:35,706
keeps reacting to every question,

1086
00:58:35,790 --> 00:58:37,708
I'll be very irritated.

1087
00:58:38,835 --> 00:58:40,795
Ms. Voyter, answer the question.

1088
00:58:43,464 --> 00:58:46,175
The music was just very loud.

1089
00:58:46,259 --> 00:58:48,511
And when it started over,

1090
00:58:48,594 --> 00:58:51,639
I realized it wasn't going to stop.

1091
00:58:52,390 --> 00:58:56,102
That made discussion difficult.

1092
00:58:57,436 --> 00:58:59,105
(stammers) So I...

1093
00:58:59,188 --> 00:59:00,940
I preferred to stop.

1094
00:59:01,274 --> 00:59:03,651
And I was tired, yes.

1095
00:59:03,734 --> 00:59:05,820
And I felt a bit...

1096
00:59:06,821 --> 00:59:08,698
woozy, from the wine.

1097
00:59:09,490 --> 00:59:13,202
Yet once alone, you didn't ask him
to explain his behavior?

1098
00:59:14,787 --> 00:59:17,081
As I said, it was habitual.

1099
00:59:17,164 --> 00:59:18,332
ADVOCATE GENERAL:
No. No.

1100
00:59:18,416 --> 00:59:21,919
You entertaining
an attractive young woman

1101
00:59:22,003 --> 00:59:25,590
while he toiled upstairs
was neither habitual, nor neutral.

1102
00:59:25,673 --> 00:59:28,593
He knew you liked women.
You'd recently cheated.

1103
00:59:28,676 --> 00:59:30,428
VINCENT:
That's beside the point.

1104
00:59:30,511 --> 00:59:31,345
And sexist.

1105
00:59:31,429 --> 00:59:33,139
ADVOCATE GENERAL:
I'd have said the same

1106
00:59:33,222 --> 00:59:34,557
if she were an attractive man.

1107
00:59:34,640 --> 00:59:38,352
Excuse me,
but this couple's conflicts matter here.

1108
00:59:38,436 --> 00:59:41,355
The situation
is objectively quite strange.

1109
00:59:41,439 --> 00:59:45,109
You say you went upstairs
to your room to work and sleep.

1110
00:59:45,193 --> 00:59:48,779
Right below the attic
with the deafening music.

1111
00:59:48,863 --> 00:59:52,116
Music that had made
the interview impossible.

1112
00:59:52,200 --> 00:59:54,619
In that big house,
you chose that spot?

1113
00:59:54,702 --> 00:59:58,414
Yes, that's where I work.
I always work in bed.

1114
00:59:59,665 --> 01:00:00,750
(Advocate General scoffs)

1115
01:00:00,833 --> 01:00:02,335
-ADVOCATE GENERAL: When Samuel came...
-Pardon?

1116
01:00:02,418 --> 01:00:04,212
...to talk to you, you didn't complain?

1117
01:00:04,295 --> 01:00:07,298
Deafening music overhead
is hardly normal.

1118
01:00:09,509 --> 01:00:11,093
I'm used to it, I don't mind.

1119
01:00:11,177 --> 01:00:14,013
I wanted to work,
I had my earplugs.

1120
01:00:14,096 --> 01:00:15,139
It was normal.

1121
01:00:15,932 --> 01:00:18,100
I can work in any situation.

1122
01:00:18,184 --> 01:00:20,895
You said you were tired,
woozy from the wine.

1123
01:00:20,978 --> 01:00:23,022
Yet you wanted to work?

1124
01:00:23,105 --> 01:00:24,023
Yes.

1125
01:00:24,106 --> 01:00:25,942
And I did. Not for long.

1126
01:00:26,025 --> 01:00:27,777
A translation was due.

1127
01:00:27,860 --> 01:00:30,238
I wanted to finish it before resting.

1128
01:00:30,655 --> 01:00:34,867
As I said, I can work
in any environment, any condition.

1129
01:00:34,951 --> 01:00:38,162
Apparently you can also rest
anywhere, anytime.

1130
01:00:38,246 --> 01:00:40,373
So all was well with the world.

1131
01:00:45,461 --> 01:00:46,379
That's all.

1132
01:00:50,091 --> 01:00:51,425
ADVOCATE GENERAL:
No further questions.

1133
01:00:54,595 --> 01:00:56,848
JUDGE JANVIER (on recording):
<i>Daniel, that's not what you told us.</i>

1134
01:00:56,931 --> 01:00:59,934
<i>Zoé Solidor saw you
leave the house after she left.</i>

1135
01:01:00,017 --> 01:01:03,312
<i>And your mom says
she spoke to your dad after that.</i>

1136
01:01:04,939 --> 01:01:06,107
DANIEL (on recording):
<i>I got mixed up.</i>

1137
01:01:06,983 --> 01:01:08,192
JUDGE:
<i>You got mixed up.</i>

1138
01:01:12,280 --> 01:01:13,447
JUSTICE MINISTER:
Bon.

1139
01:01:14,490 --> 01:01:16,784
Indeed there is a problem, Daniel.

1140
01:01:16,868 --> 01:01:17,910
Right?

1141
01:01:17,994 --> 01:01:20,705
You couldn't be two places at once.

1142
01:01:22,206 --> 01:01:24,542
DANIEL:
I think I went back inside.

1143
01:01:27,336 --> 01:01:31,507
What bothers me is how sure
you were before the reenactment.

1144
01:01:31,883 --> 01:01:34,177
You said in your statement:

1145
01:01:34,260 --> 01:01:37,096
"Each piece of tape feels different.

1146
01:01:37,180 --> 01:01:39,891
I wouldn't get it wrong."

1147
01:01:40,516 --> 01:01:43,269
And: "I was just below
the open window.

1148
01:01:43,352 --> 01:01:45,271
I know what I heard."

1149
01:01:45,354 --> 01:01:49,025
Then, during the reenactment,
you said something else entirely.

1150
01:01:49,108 --> 01:01:50,568
How come?

1151
01:01:53,446 --> 01:01:56,490
I thought
I remembered where I was, but...

1152
01:01:58,993 --> 01:02:02,747
Maybe the shock of what
happened next got me mixed up.

1153
01:02:03,122 --> 01:02:05,333
VINCENT:
A psychiatrist who met with Daniel

1154
01:02:05,416 --> 01:02:09,212
says emotional shock
may have altered some memories.

1155
01:02:09,712 --> 01:02:10,588
ADVOCATE GENERAL:
Of course.

1156
01:02:10,671 --> 01:02:13,508
Do you remember now
why you came back inside?

1157
01:02:15,718 --> 01:02:17,720
I think I must've forgotten...

1158
01:02:18,387 --> 01:02:20,014
my gloves or my phone.

1159
01:02:20,890 --> 01:02:22,183
ADVOCATE GENERAL:
But you're not sure?

1160
01:02:23,726 --> 01:02:25,561
I don't remember exactly.

1161
01:02:25,645 --> 01:02:29,232
ADVOCATE GENERAL: So, you went
from absolute certainty to uncertainty

1162
01:02:29,315 --> 01:02:31,609
about your memories of that day.

1163
01:02:31,901 --> 01:02:33,945
VINCENT:
This is very problematic.

1164
01:02:34,028 --> 01:02:37,073
You're fixating on one detail
in his memory

1165
01:02:37,156 --> 01:02:39,700
to cast doubt
on his whole memory.

1166
01:02:40,117 --> 01:02:41,911
What do you want us to believe?

1167
01:02:41,994 --> 01:02:45,414
That shock may have turned
yelling into calm voices?

1168
01:02:45,498 --> 01:02:48,501
You insinuate
he lied to protect his mother.

1169
01:02:48,584 --> 01:02:49,544
ADVOCATE GENERAL:
No.

1170
01:02:50,253 --> 01:02:52,630
I'm merely signaling
the witness's doubts.

1171
01:02:52,713 --> 01:02:55,049
But we are entitled to wonder.

1172
01:02:55,132 --> 01:02:59,053
Daniel Maleski says he would leave
when his parents fought.

1173
01:02:59,136 --> 01:03:02,431
Whereas on that day,
he happens to go out

1174
01:03:02,515 --> 01:03:05,351
right when an argument
is likely to erupt.

1175
01:03:05,434 --> 01:03:07,353
Thus, he doesn't hear a thing.

1176
01:03:07,812 --> 01:03:10,523
I didn't happen to go out.
I fled the music.

1177
01:03:10,606 --> 01:03:14,694
VINCENT: And he's very precise
about what he heard.

1178
01:03:14,777 --> 01:03:16,445
He's never budged on that.

1179
01:03:17,029 --> 01:03:20,324
The psychiatrist
and visual impairment expert

1180
01:03:20,408 --> 01:03:23,661
both observed
Daniel's excellent aural memory.

1181
01:03:25,705 --> 01:03:26,914
(dry chuckle)

1182
01:03:29,834 --> 01:03:33,337
JUSTICE MINISTER:
Clerk, please display

1183
01:03:33,421 --> 01:03:35,923
the elements provided by Mr. Balard.

1184
01:03:38,301 --> 01:03:39,927
We're listening.

1185
01:03:40,011 --> 01:03:43,639
EXPERT BALARD: The decisive element here
is the three blood spatters

1186
01:03:43,723 --> 01:03:45,141
on the woodshed,

1187
01:03:45,224 --> 01:03:47,852
as indicated on the sketch.

1188
01:03:48,811 --> 01:03:52,023
-Can we zoom in on the woodshed?
-(mouse clicks)

1189
01:03:52,899 --> 01:03:56,819
Their shape is typical of spatter
projected from high above.

1190
01:03:56,903 --> 01:03:59,280
They are long and narrow.

1191
01:03:59,363 --> 01:04:04,202
The longest measures
four centimeters, which is a lot.

1192
01:04:04,285 --> 01:04:05,912
So, according to our tests,

1193
01:04:05,995 --> 01:04:08,623
these spatters
could only have landed here

1194
01:04:08,706 --> 01:04:11,334
if Mr. Maleski
was struck on the head

1195
01:04:11,417 --> 01:04:14,003
while on the 3rd floor balcony.

1196
01:04:14,795 --> 01:04:18,007
He would have
to have been leaning over the balcony,

1197
01:04:18,090 --> 01:04:21,844
his head already quite far out
when the blow was struck,

1198
01:04:21,928 --> 01:04:24,639
for the spatter to land there.

1199
01:04:24,722 --> 01:04:26,599
No other explanation stands.

1200
01:04:26,682 --> 01:04:30,686
Did the violence of the blow
make Mr. Maleski fall?

1201
01:04:30,770 --> 01:04:32,021
EXPERT BALARD:
Most likely,

1202
01:04:32,104 --> 01:04:35,608
it was the combination
of a violent blow

1203
01:04:35,691 --> 01:04:37,735
and a deliberate push.

1204
01:04:37,818 --> 01:04:41,864
Would you say the aggressor
was in a state of extreme anger,

1205
01:04:41,948 --> 01:04:45,701
to provoke a fall
after administering such a violent blow?

1206
01:04:45,785 --> 01:04:47,995
EXPERT BALARD:
A state of rage, I'd say.

1207
01:04:48,079 --> 01:04:50,206
Hard to imagine anything less.

1208
01:04:50,289 --> 01:04:54,085
Such states
can increase physical strength.

1209
01:05:01,467 --> 01:05:02,510
(Vincent clears throat)

1210
01:05:05,429 --> 01:05:10,268
The guardrail is 1.2 meters high.

1211
01:05:10,351 --> 01:05:13,396
Comes up to about here.

1212
01:05:13,896 --> 01:05:16,649
Mr. Maleski was 1.82 meters tall

1213
01:05:16,732 --> 01:05:18,651
and weighed 85 kilos.

1214
01:05:19,318 --> 01:05:22,321
So, pushing him over that guardrail

1215
01:05:22,405 --> 01:05:26,242
would have required
a very deliberate push, right?

1216
01:05:26,325 --> 01:05:29,412
The entire act was very deliberate.

1217
01:05:29,495 --> 01:05:31,789
Such a blow is always intentional.

1218
01:05:31,873 --> 01:05:34,083
What I mean by very deliberate  is...

1219
01:05:34,166 --> 01:05:36,878
very coordinated. Methodical.

1220
01:05:37,128 --> 01:05:39,630
Based on his weight,
we can assume

1221
01:05:39,714 --> 01:05:43,259
it was necessary to lift his legs
to make him fall,

1222
01:05:43,342 --> 01:05:45,386
which hardly suggests rage.

1223
01:05:45,469 --> 01:05:47,346
Rage does not exclude will.

1224
01:05:47,430 --> 01:05:51,601
And Mr. Maleski was probably
already off-balance.

1225
01:05:51,684 --> 01:05:53,352
He may have fallen

1226
01:05:53,436 --> 01:05:56,981
as much from the blow
as from his own unstable position.

1227
01:05:57,064 --> 01:05:59,859
As I said,
we have no material elements...

1228
01:05:59,942 --> 01:06:02,069
Except those three drops of blood.

1229
01:06:03,154 --> 01:06:08,201
Everything else must be speculated
to explain those drops, right?

1230
01:06:08,284 --> 01:06:11,704
EXPERT BALARD: Okay, but the only
explanation is the one I gave.

1231
01:06:11,787 --> 01:06:15,041
You gave us a theory,
not an explanation.

1232
01:06:15,291 --> 01:06:16,876
Actually, two theories.

1233
01:06:16,959 --> 01:06:20,046
With and without a deliberate push.

1234
01:06:20,755 --> 01:06:22,548
According to your theories,

1235
01:06:22,632 --> 01:06:24,759
what type of object was used?

1236
01:06:24,842 --> 01:06:27,386
EXPERT BALARD:
A heavy object, probably in metal

1237
01:06:27,637 --> 01:06:29,680
or dense wood,

1238
01:06:29,764 --> 01:06:32,433
and undoubtedly with a sharp edge.

1239
01:06:32,517 --> 01:06:36,145
Did you examine any such objects
found on the premises?

1240
01:06:36,229 --> 01:06:38,940
ADVOCATE GENERAL:
You know no weapon was found.

1241
01:06:39,023 --> 01:06:40,816
They're easily disposed of.

1242
01:06:41,442 --> 01:06:42,944
VINCENT:
No further questions.

1243
01:06:45,154 --> 01:06:48,074
EXPERT BOGAERT: Two possible
explanations for these three spatters.

1244
01:06:48,157 --> 01:06:52,370
Either they came from here,
after a violent blow.

1245
01:06:52,912 --> 01:06:55,831
Or they resulted when the skull

1246
01:06:55,915 --> 01:06:57,750
hit this roof ledge,

1247
01:06:57,834 --> 01:06:59,252
approximately here.

1248
01:06:59,585 --> 01:07:01,504
The first hypothesis is unlikely.

1249
01:07:01,587 --> 01:07:06,050
It's inconsistent with the shape
and movement of the spatters.

1250
01:07:07,009 --> 01:07:08,970
Focusing on the second hypothesis,

1251
01:07:09,053 --> 01:07:12,807
we must take into account
the bounce caused by the impact

1252
01:07:12,890 --> 01:07:14,225
on the roof ledge.

1253
01:07:15,059 --> 01:07:18,229
I'll show you a video
of our in situ tests.

1254
01:07:23,734 --> 01:07:24,652
There.

1255
01:07:24,735 --> 01:07:28,364
As you can see
in our reenactment with a dummy,

1256
01:07:28,698 --> 01:07:31,909
such an impact
causes the body to turn abruptly.

1257
01:07:31,993 --> 01:07:35,454
And during that rollover, or spin,

1258
01:07:35,830 --> 01:07:38,040
a fraction of a second after impact,

1259
01:07:38,124 --> 01:07:42,128
these three spatters are projected

1260
01:07:42,211 --> 01:07:43,671
<i>onto this surface.</i>

1261
01:07:47,300 --> 01:07:49,177
The only valid explanation

1262
01:07:49,260 --> 01:07:52,889
is that Mr. Maleski
fell from the attic window.

1263
01:07:52,971 --> 01:07:54,390
I believe it's the only way

1264
01:07:54,473 --> 01:07:56,767
he could've bounced off the roof,

1265
01:07:57,225 --> 01:07:58,895
and sustained such an injury.

1266
01:07:58,978 --> 01:08:01,439
You use the cautious qualifier
"I believe."

1267
01:08:01,522 --> 01:08:02,982
So it's your opinion.

1268
01:08:03,399 --> 01:08:06,068
NOUR: How do you explain
the lack of DNA or trace tissue

1269
01:08:06,359 --> 01:08:09,738
at the point of impact,
or "bounce" as you call it?

1270
01:08:10,238 --> 01:08:11,908
I'll show you.

1271
01:08:11,991 --> 01:08:14,243
This is a test we carried out

1272
01:08:14,327 --> 01:08:16,203
under comparable conditions.

1273
01:08:16,287 --> 01:08:17,371
Voilà.

1274
01:08:17,455 --> 01:08:19,832
At the time of the incident,
there was a layer of ice

1275
01:08:19,916 --> 01:08:22,585
underneath a thick layer of snow.

1276
01:08:23,794 --> 01:08:27,048
We see the snow melting
in acceleration.

1277
01:08:27,131 --> 01:08:28,549
And we can see,

1278
01:08:28,633 --> 01:08:32,553
over the span of 1 hour
and 50 minutes, that the runoff

1279
01:08:33,054 --> 01:08:36,765
takes with it all residue
embedded at the point of impact.

1280
01:08:36,849 --> 01:08:38,559
It ends up with the blood

1281
01:08:38,643 --> 01:08:39,810
down here.

1282
01:08:39,894 --> 01:08:43,606
You call the violent blow
hypothesis "improbable."

1283
01:08:43,689 --> 01:08:45,816
Would you call it impossible?

1284
01:08:46,943 --> 01:08:48,903
No, but highly improbable.

1285
01:08:48,986 --> 01:08:50,904
ADVOCATE GENERAL:
Meaning it is possible.

1286
01:08:50,988 --> 01:08:53,950
As it's possible
I'll be president someday.

1287
01:08:54,033 --> 01:08:55,493
-(gallery murmuring)
-I know the definition.

1288
01:08:55,576 --> 01:08:57,118
EXPERT BOGAERT:
It's improbable for a reason.

1289
01:08:57,203 --> 01:09:00,497
In your hypothesis,
in order to explain the angle

1290
01:09:00,581 --> 01:09:02,082
of these three spatters,

1291
01:09:02,166 --> 01:09:05,627
we have to imagine
that Mr. Maleski's head

1292
01:09:05,711 --> 01:09:09,340
was leaning way out,
around 80 cm past the guardrail.

1293
01:09:09,423 --> 01:09:12,510
This implies the aggressor
forced him

1294
01:09:12,593 --> 01:09:14,595
to lean backwards over the void,

1295
01:09:15,179 --> 01:09:17,723
shoving him against the guardrail,

1296
01:09:17,807 --> 01:09:20,810
his entire torso pitched backwards.

1297
01:09:21,143 --> 01:09:26,023
The aggressor would have
to be leaning very far out

1298
01:09:26,107 --> 01:09:28,149
while holding a heavy object

1299
01:09:28,234 --> 01:09:31,487
and striking the victim
with powerful momentum.

1300
01:09:31,571 --> 01:09:32,947
All these elements,

1301
01:09:33,030 --> 01:09:35,992
in addition to
the defendant's body mass,

1302
01:09:36,075 --> 01:09:38,327
make this hypothesis
highly improbable.

1303
01:09:38,411 --> 01:09:39,579
ADVOCATE GENERAL:
But not impossible.

1304
01:09:39,662 --> 01:09:41,831
(gallery murmuring)

1305
01:09:44,000 --> 01:09:47,211
Okay. Listen, Daniel,
I asked to see you because...

1306
01:09:47,295 --> 01:09:50,631
I know you have
a vested interest in this case.

1307
01:09:50,715 --> 01:09:53,509
I've allowed you
to attend the trial so far.

1308
01:09:53,593 --> 01:09:55,094
But tomorrow will be

1309
01:09:55,178 --> 01:09:57,054
far more complicated.

1310
01:09:57,138 --> 01:10:00,016
We'll be covering
some disturbing details,

1311
01:10:00,099 --> 01:10:02,602
so I've decided
you won't be attending.

1312
01:10:03,728 --> 01:10:05,563
I think I can hear anything.

1313
01:10:05,646 --> 01:10:06,606
JUSTICE MINISTER:
What?

1314
01:10:06,689 --> 01:10:08,524
I think I can hear anything.

1315
01:10:08,941 --> 01:10:10,818
-Yeah?
-I'm prepared.

1316
01:10:10,902 --> 01:10:14,071
JUSTICE MINISTER: You can hear it,
but can you handle it?

1317
01:10:14,155 --> 01:10:15,823
We have a job to do.

1318
01:10:15,907 --> 01:10:19,577
We need to be able to work...
with serenity.

1319
01:10:19,660 --> 01:10:21,370
I've never disrupted the trial.

1320
01:10:21,454 --> 01:10:23,206
JUSTICE MINISTER (chuckles):
Disrupted...

1321
01:10:23,289 --> 01:10:25,166
That's not the point.

1322
01:10:26,334 --> 01:10:29,629
We need to be able
to evoke the facts bluntly.

1323
01:10:30,880 --> 01:10:33,049
We have to address everything,

1324
01:10:33,132 --> 01:10:35,510
without fear of hurting you.

1325
01:10:38,221 --> 01:10:39,972
I've already been hurt.

1326
01:10:41,682 --> 01:10:43,893
And that's why I need...

1327
01:10:45,269 --> 01:10:47,522
to hear, so I can get past it.

1328
01:10:47,605 --> 01:10:49,815
JUSTICE MINISTER:
The trial is not about you hearing.

1329
01:10:49,899 --> 01:10:52,360
It's about establishing the truth,

1330
01:10:52,443 --> 01:10:54,654
without being forced
to censor ourselves.

1331
01:10:54,737 --> 01:10:58,157
(scoffs) When has anyone
censored themselves?

1332
01:10:59,325 --> 01:11:01,577
Even if you forbid me to come,

1333
01:11:02,411 --> 01:11:05,039
I'll find out.
I'll know what happened

1334
01:11:05,122 --> 01:11:06,958
from TV, radio, Internet.

1335
01:11:07,834 --> 01:11:09,460
I'll be obsessed.

1336
01:11:16,551 --> 01:11:21,430
(people moving about and settling in)

1337
01:11:21,514 --> 01:11:23,516
ADVOCATE GENERAL:
Ms. Voyter, you claim

1338
01:11:23,599 --> 01:11:26,561
your husband attempted suicide
six months before he died.

1339
01:11:27,311 --> 01:11:30,565
You remembered late,
which is quite surprising.

1340
01:11:30,648 --> 01:11:33,526
Can you describe
the episode in detail?

1341
01:11:33,609 --> 01:11:34,735
SANDRA: Oui.

1342
01:11:40,783 --> 01:11:45,288
It happened a few weeks
after he stopped his medication.

1343
01:11:46,414 --> 01:11:48,916
I found him lying on the floor...

1344
01:11:49,959 --> 01:11:52,295
early in the morning, in his room.

1345
01:11:54,046 --> 01:11:55,214
He'd...

1346
01:11:55,590 --> 01:11:57,341
had a lot to drink...

1347
01:11:58,092 --> 01:12:00,803
the night before, and passed out.

1348
01:12:02,388 --> 01:12:05,808
He'd vomited,
and in the vomit, I saw aspirin.

1349
01:12:06,684 --> 01:12:10,062
The pills had nearly dissolved.

1350
01:12:12,148 --> 01:12:14,942
<i>At first I didn't understand
what it was.</i>

1351
01:12:15,693 --> 01:12:18,154
<i>But later, I found...</i>

1352
01:12:18,863 --> 01:12:21,657
<i>empty blister packs
in the kitchen garbage.</i>

1353
01:12:22,783 --> 01:12:25,411
I cleaned it all up
and put him in bed.

1354
01:12:26,037 --> 01:12:27,330
Later,

1355
01:12:27,413 --> 01:12:29,165
when he felt better,

1356
01:12:29,248 --> 01:12:31,250
he didn't want to discuss it.

1357
01:12:31,334 --> 01:12:34,128
He just said
he'd stopped his meds too soon.

1358
01:12:34,212 --> 01:12:37,590
JUSTICE MINISTER:
Mm. You had separate bedrooms?

1359
01:12:38,758 --> 01:12:42,178
It was his office,
and he usually slept there, yes.

1360
01:12:43,679 --> 01:12:44,680
JUSTICE MINISTER:
I see.

1361
01:12:44,764 --> 01:12:48,226
What made you
go into his room so early?

1362
01:12:48,309 --> 01:12:50,937
I wake up very early.
He did too, sometimes.

1363
01:12:51,020 --> 01:12:54,273
We occasionally spent that time
together, talking.

1364
01:12:54,357 --> 01:12:55,942
JUSTICE MINISTER:
At six in the morning?

1365
01:12:56,025 --> 01:12:58,486
Yes, if I saw the light on.

1366
01:12:59,278 --> 01:13:02,448
We'd stopped sharing a bed,
but we were very close.

1367
01:13:02,532 --> 01:13:04,367
I would often...

1368
01:13:05,451 --> 01:13:08,454
finish the night with him,
in the office bed.

1369
01:13:09,956 --> 01:13:11,958
I'd gone down to make coffee.

1370
01:13:12,041 --> 01:13:15,044
I saw his door was ajar, and...

1371
01:13:15,586 --> 01:13:17,630
I saw him lying on the floor.

1372
01:13:18,047 --> 01:13:20,216
JUSTICE MINISTER:
No one else witnessed that?

1373
01:13:20,299 --> 01:13:21,551
No.

1374
01:13:21,634 --> 01:13:24,053
JUSTICE MINISTER:
Thank you, you may sit down.

1375
01:13:26,389 --> 01:13:27,765
Did you know that?

1376
01:13:27,849 --> 01:13:28,766
DANIEL: No.

1377
01:13:29,559 --> 01:13:31,310
Which antidepressant
did you prescribe?

1378
01:13:31,394 --> 01:13:33,187
JAMMAL:
Escitalopram, 20 mg per day.

1379
01:13:33,437 --> 01:13:35,481
-Was it his choice to stop?
-Yes.

1380
01:13:35,898 --> 01:13:39,193
About seven months before he died
he wanted to wean off.

1381
01:13:39,277 --> 01:13:43,155
I recommended a tapering plan
with weekly check-ins.

1382
01:13:43,239 --> 01:13:44,907
Any suicidal ideation?

1383
01:13:45,491 --> 01:13:47,493
No, Samuel wasn't depressive.

1384
01:13:47,577 --> 01:13:50,830
I'd prescribed Escitalopram
as an emotional shield

1385
01:13:50,913 --> 01:13:54,375
to help him cope
after his son's accident.

1386
01:13:54,458 --> 01:13:58,921
Can sudden withdrawal from
a low dose trigger a suicide attempt?

1387
01:13:59,755 --> 01:14:02,091
Anything's possible in theory,

1388
01:14:02,175 --> 01:14:06,512
but why would he have asked me
to help him wean off,

1389
01:14:06,596 --> 01:14:09,640
then stop behind my back?
Makes no sense.

1390
01:14:09,724 --> 01:14:12,685
And no mention of it
in our weekly sessions?

1391
01:14:13,644 --> 01:14:14,729
ADVOCATE GENERAL:
Bon.

1392
01:14:25,615 --> 01:14:28,951
Have you ever had
a patient commit suicide,

1393
01:14:29,035 --> 01:14:30,536
or attempt suicide?

1394
01:14:30,828 --> 01:14:33,164
In French, "committing suicide"

1395
01:14:33,247 --> 01:14:37,001
means both trying and succeeding.

1396
01:14:37,084 --> 01:14:38,169
It's the action.

1397
01:14:38,252 --> 01:14:39,795
Thanks for the language lesson.

1398
01:14:39,879 --> 01:14:41,881
No patient has committed suicide.

1399
01:14:41,964 --> 01:14:43,841
Aside from Mr. Maleski,

1400
01:14:43,925 --> 01:14:46,802
since we're here
to rule on the question.

1401
01:14:47,220 --> 01:14:48,596
In any case,

1402
01:14:48,679 --> 01:14:51,557
we can't consider you
an expert on suicide,

1403
01:14:51,641 --> 01:14:52,975
failed or successful.

1404
01:14:53,559 --> 01:14:57,063
You said your husband
refused to discuss it with you,

1405
01:14:57,146 --> 01:14:58,981
or anyone else, apparently.

1406
01:14:59,065 --> 01:15:00,358
Why, do you think?

1407
01:15:01,901 --> 01:15:04,487
SANDRA:
Uh, because he was ashamed.

1408
01:15:04,570 --> 01:15:06,822
He had a lot of...

1409
01:15:10,284 --> 01:15:11,410
Um...

1410
01:15:11,494 --> 01:15:12,495
(in English)
It's too complicated.

1411
01:15:12,578 --> 01:15:13,955
Can I change
the language, please?

1412
01:15:15,373 --> 01:15:16,457
SANDRA (in French):
Thanks.

1413
01:15:16,541 --> 01:15:18,334
Um...

1414
01:15:18,417 --> 01:15:19,961
SANDRA (in English): Yeah, I think
because he was ashamed.

1415
01:15:20,044 --> 01:15:21,712
(translator whispering)

1416
01:15:21,796 --> 01:15:24,966
-Samuel had a lot of issues with shame.
-(translation playing over earbud)

1417
01:15:25,049 --> 01:15:27,051
It's complicated, there were...

1418
01:15:27,134 --> 01:15:28,803
He, uh...

1419
01:15:28,886 --> 01:15:30,429
He was, uh, frustrated

1420
01:15:30,513 --> 01:15:31,848
with teaching in the first place,

1421
01:15:31,931 --> 01:15:33,099
it had become a burden.

1422
01:15:34,183 --> 01:15:36,018
And he wanted to write.

1423
01:15:36,102 --> 01:15:38,855
Um, he'd been working
on a novel for years,

1424
01:15:38,938 --> 01:15:41,315
before and after
Daniel's accident.

1425
01:15:41,399 --> 01:15:44,235
Um, I read everything
he wrote back then,

1426
01:15:44,318 --> 01:15:46,279
and I thought it was really good
and I told him so,

1427
01:15:46,362 --> 01:15:49,198
but from one day
to another, he just...

1428
01:15:49,282 --> 01:15:50,283
couldn't do it anymore.

1429
01:15:50,366 --> 01:15:53,369
He just stopped and, uh...

1430
01:15:53,452 --> 01:15:55,496
it made him feel like a coward.

1431
01:15:55,580 --> 01:15:59,876
He-- He would belittle
himself and, um...

1432
01:15:59,959 --> 01:16:02,837
He ended up convincing himself
that he could not write

1433
01:16:02,920 --> 01:16:06,048
because of his dependency
on the medication,

1434
01:16:06,132 --> 01:16:08,009
and he wanted
to free himself of that.

1435
01:16:08,092 --> 01:16:10,553
-And he could not of course...
-(Jammal speaking in French)

1436
01:16:10,636 --> 01:16:12,263
-I'm sorry, I'm not finished.
-(Jammal stops)

1437
01:16:12,346 --> 01:16:14,640
He could not talk about
the suicide attempt

1438
01:16:14,724 --> 01:16:18,603
because his feelings of failure
were just too painful. And...

1439
01:16:18,686 --> 01:16:19,854
JAMMAL (in French):
He never spoke of that.

1440
01:16:19,937 --> 01:16:21,814
-...it was all a--
-JAMMAL: Not once.

1441
01:16:21,898 --> 01:16:23,983
No, he blamed you for getting him
hooked on the pills

1442
01:16:24,066 --> 01:16:26,903
from the very first session,
and it drove him mad...

1443
01:16:26,986 --> 01:16:28,571
(in French)
He and I decided together.

1444
01:16:28,654 --> 01:16:32,158
You can't deny you're at the center
of this equation.

1445
01:16:32,575 --> 01:16:36,078
Samuel came to see me
because he felt guilty,

1446
01:16:36,162 --> 01:16:38,915
but mostly because you blamed him.

1447
01:16:38,998 --> 01:16:41,501
He described your behavior

1448
01:16:41,584 --> 01:16:43,669
as quite castrating.

1449
01:16:44,086 --> 01:16:46,047
You made him pay

1450
01:16:46,380 --> 01:16:48,257
for the accident

1451
01:16:48,341 --> 01:16:51,844
by forcing him to give up
what mattered most to him:

1452
01:16:51,928 --> 01:16:52,970
writing.

1453
01:16:53,804 --> 01:16:57,350
You put him on
an emotional rollercoaster.

1454
01:16:57,433 --> 01:16:59,602
On the one hand, it's true,

1455
01:16:59,685 --> 01:17:02,772
you encouraged him to write,
wanted him to succeed.

1456
01:17:02,855 --> 01:17:06,359
But if he had,
it would've been unbearable for you.

1457
01:17:06,442 --> 01:17:09,278
That's the problem.
It may have been subconscious.

1458
01:17:10,446 --> 01:17:13,866
All the material
and psychological burdens

1459
01:17:13,950 --> 01:17:16,577
resulting from the accident
were his to bear.

1460
01:17:16,661 --> 01:17:19,664
It's as though you said,
"This is your problem.

1461
01:17:19,747 --> 01:17:21,832
"You're responsible. Deal with it."

1462
01:17:21,916 --> 01:17:24,836
"I want to free myself
from that, to write."

1463
01:17:24,919 --> 01:17:26,587
Material burdens

1464
01:17:26,671 --> 01:17:29,882
were managed by Ms. Voyter
as much as her husband.

1465
01:17:29,966 --> 01:17:33,511
We have their bank statements,
receipts, etc.

1466
01:17:33,594 --> 01:17:36,305
I'm also talking about
the emotional load.

1467
01:17:36,389 --> 01:17:39,267
Responsibilities, sense of purpose,

1468
01:17:39,767 --> 01:17:41,060
anxiety.

1469
01:17:41,143 --> 01:17:45,648
In those areas,
Samuel felt an unbearable imbalance.

1470
01:17:45,731 --> 01:17:48,192
So what, your patients
tell you is the truth?

1471
01:17:48,276 --> 01:17:50,486
As a psychoanalyst,

1472
01:17:50,570 --> 01:17:53,364
you never wondered
whether Samuel Maleski

1473
01:17:53,447 --> 01:17:57,243
might've needed to imagine
an unbearable imbalance

1474
01:17:57,326 --> 01:17:59,412
to prevent himself from writing?

1475
01:17:59,495 --> 01:18:03,624
After a while, I can tell
what's real and what isn't.

1476
01:18:03,708 --> 01:18:04,959
VINCENT:
Lucky you.

1477
01:18:05,042 --> 01:18:06,961
(in English) I'm sorry
to interrupt, I'm sorry.

1478
01:18:07,044 --> 01:18:11,507
But... I don't know,
you, you come here,

1479
01:18:11,591 --> 01:18:13,551
okay, with your,
maybe your opinion,

1480
01:18:13,634 --> 01:18:18,222
and you tell me who Samuel was,

1481
01:18:18,306 --> 01:18:20,016
and what we were going through...

1482
01:18:20,099 --> 01:18:22,685
But what you say is just a...

1483
01:18:22,768 --> 01:18:24,353
it is just...

1484
01:18:24,437 --> 01:18:28,482
a little part of the whole
situation, you know?

1485
01:18:29,734 --> 01:18:31,527
I mean, sometimes...

1486
01:18:31,611 --> 01:18:36,032
Sometimes a couple
is kind of a chaos.

1487
01:18:36,115 --> 01:18:38,826
And everybody is lost. No?

1488
01:18:38,910 --> 01:18:40,411
And sometimes we fight together

1489
01:18:40,494 --> 01:18:41,829
and sometimes we fight alone

1490
01:18:41,913 --> 01:18:44,373
and sometimes we fight
against each other,

1491
01:18:44,457 --> 01:18:46,417
that happens, and I think

1492
01:18:46,501 --> 01:18:49,253
it's possible that Samuel needed

1493
01:18:49,337 --> 01:18:52,548
to see things the way
you describe them, but...

1494
01:18:52,632 --> 01:18:53,758
(scoffs)

1495
01:18:53,841 --> 01:18:55,927
if-- if I'd been seeing a therapist,

1496
01:18:56,010 --> 01:18:57,553
he could stand here too

1497
01:18:57,637 --> 01:18:59,722
and say very ugly things
about Samuel.

1498
01:18:59,805 --> 01:19:02,475
But would those things be true?

1499
01:19:03,935 --> 01:19:05,353
ADVOCATE GENERAL:
Madame Voyter...

1500
01:19:10,942 --> 01:19:14,737
(in French) Did you resent your husband
after your son's accident?

1501
01:19:18,741 --> 01:19:20,368
(in English)
We were both dealing

1502
01:19:20,451 --> 01:19:24,038
with very different emotions
at that time.

1503
01:19:25,623 --> 01:19:27,166
(in French)
Yes or no?

1504
01:19:30,044 --> 01:19:31,838
(in English)
Yes, for a few days,

1505
01:19:31,921 --> 01:19:33,172
Daniel was on his watch--

1506
01:19:33,256 --> 01:19:34,715
ADVOCATE GENERAL (in French):
A few days?

1507
01:19:35,091 --> 01:19:38,261
-Your son practically lost his sight...
-(Sandra clears throat)

1508
01:19:38,344 --> 01:19:40,805
and you only resented him
for a few days?

1509
01:19:42,014 --> 01:19:43,391
(in English)
Yeah, about his responsibility

1510
01:19:43,474 --> 01:19:47,019
for the accident, yes, of course.

1511
01:19:48,354 --> 01:19:50,815
I mean, maybe, the doctor earlier

1512
01:19:50,898 --> 01:19:53,526
said something about
a tragic situation, I...

1513
01:19:53,609 --> 01:19:57,154
I immediately refused
to see it that way.

1514
01:19:57,238 --> 01:20:00,283
I never saw Daniel as handicapped.

1515
01:20:00,366 --> 01:20:01,367
You know?

1516
01:20:01,450 --> 01:20:02,910
I-- I wanted to protect him

1517
01:20:02,994 --> 01:20:04,245
from that perception.

1518
01:20:04,328 --> 01:20:06,455
Because as soon as you mark
a child that way,

1519
01:20:06,539 --> 01:20:09,166
you condemn him to not, to not...

1520
01:20:09,250 --> 01:20:11,085
see his life as his own,

1521
01:20:11,169 --> 01:20:12,837
whereas, he should feel

1522
01:20:12,920 --> 01:20:13,880
that it's his best life,

1523
01:20:13,963 --> 01:20:15,464
because it's
the only life he's got,

1524
01:20:15,548 --> 01:20:17,550
it is his own.

1525
01:20:17,633 --> 01:20:20,511
He... He reads books,

1526
01:20:20,595 --> 01:20:23,764
he goes on social media
like any other kid,

1527
01:20:23,848 --> 01:20:26,350
he plays the piano, he dreams,

1528
01:20:26,434 --> 01:20:27,435
he cries, he laughs...

1529
01:20:27,518 --> 01:20:30,229
He's a, he's a very lively kid.

1530
01:20:30,313 --> 01:20:32,440
He's okay!

1531
01:20:32,523 --> 01:20:33,566
Yeah?

1532
01:20:35,776 --> 01:20:37,236
So perhaps...

1533
01:20:37,320 --> 01:20:39,697
yeah, I...

1534
01:20:39,780 --> 01:20:41,324
I resented Samuel

1535
01:20:41,407 --> 01:20:44,118
for projecting his own pain
onto Daniel, yes.

1536
01:20:47,079 --> 01:20:48,039
ADVOCATE GENERAL (in French):
Thank you.

1537
01:20:56,088 --> 01:20:57,089
(dry chuckle)

1538
01:21:07,016 --> 01:21:08,726
(Sandra sniffs)

1539
01:21:08,809 --> 01:21:10,228
SANDRA (in English):
I want to drink all night.

1540
01:21:12,230 --> 01:21:13,606
VINCENT (in English):
Yeah, same.

1541
01:21:13,689 --> 01:21:16,859
I will drink, to forget.

1542
01:21:16,943 --> 01:21:17,985
Oh, come on!

1543
01:21:18,069 --> 01:21:18,986
You're the only lawyer...

1544
01:21:19,070 --> 01:21:22,198
(both laughing)

1545
01:21:22,281 --> 01:21:23,574
VINCENT:
Okay, once again.

1546
01:21:23,658 --> 01:21:26,369
No, you're really
the only lawyer I know.

1547
01:21:27,745 --> 01:21:29,121
Is it a great reason for placing

1548
01:21:29,205 --> 01:21:31,374
your life in someone's hands?

1549
01:21:31,457 --> 01:21:32,458
Is it?

1550
01:21:32,542 --> 01:21:34,252
No, but you're good too, right?

1551
01:21:34,335 --> 01:21:35,711
-VINCENT: Ah? Yeah?
-Aren't you? You're good.

1552
01:21:35,795 --> 01:21:37,463
-I don't know.
-Oh, come on!

1553
01:21:37,547 --> 01:21:38,923
(chuckles)

1554
01:21:39,006 --> 01:21:40,591
You look like a dog.

1555
01:21:40,675 --> 01:21:41,843
(both laugh)

1556
01:21:41,926 --> 01:21:43,678
-VINCENT: Oh, I'm-- No, no.
-What, excuse me?

1557
01:21:43,761 --> 01:21:46,097
A beautiful dog.
You know, the...

1558
01:21:46,180 --> 01:21:48,391
How do you say?
The... un basset?

1559
01:21:48,474 --> 01:21:50,184
Basset? Basset? You say that?

1560
01:21:50,268 --> 01:21:51,811
SANDRA:
It's funny you say that.

1561
01:21:51,894 --> 01:21:54,856
I can't trust someone if I can't
put an animal's head on them.

1562
01:21:54,939 --> 01:21:57,066
Really? So, what am I?

1563
01:21:58,776 --> 01:22:01,195
SANDRA:
Um, I'm not sure yet.

1564
01:22:02,989 --> 01:22:05,032
-What?
-I don't know.

1565
01:22:05,116 --> 01:22:07,368
-After all this time?
-SANDRA: Mmm.

1566
01:22:07,451 --> 01:22:08,828
You still don't know.

1567
01:22:11,289 --> 01:22:12,290
Okay.

1568
01:22:15,877 --> 01:22:17,128
(speaks French)

1569
01:22:18,087 --> 01:22:19,088
(Vincent chuckles)

1570
01:22:20,673 --> 01:22:21,924
SANDRA: Vincent?

1571
01:22:22,008 --> 01:22:22,967
Sandra?

1572
01:22:24,343 --> 01:22:25,261
SANDRA:
Do you...

1573
01:22:25,344 --> 01:22:26,888
Do you remember me
from before?

1574
01:22:26,971 --> 01:22:28,890
When we first met?

1575
01:22:28,973 --> 01:22:30,641
Yes, I do, of course.

1576
01:22:30,725 --> 01:22:32,435
I don't. What was I like?

1577
01:22:34,812 --> 01:22:36,606
VINCENT:
You were...

1578
01:22:36,689 --> 01:22:41,027
a bit lost,
as I can remember, and...

1579
01:22:41,110 --> 01:22:44,071
lonely, and...

1580
01:22:45,323 --> 01:22:46,490
ambitious.

1581
01:22:47,825 --> 01:22:50,036
And I was hopelessly in love.

1582
01:22:50,119 --> 01:22:51,412
(Vincent chuckles)

1583
01:22:58,252 --> 01:23:00,087
Can't remember a thing.

1584
01:23:03,007 --> 01:23:04,383
VINCENT: Okay. Hmm.

1585
01:23:11,766 --> 01:23:12,850
SANDRA:
But I'm innocent.

1586
01:23:12,934 --> 01:23:14,143
You know that, right?

1587
01:23:14,227 --> 01:23:15,853
Yes.

1588
01:23:15,937 --> 01:23:17,522
SANDRA:
I mean, really.

1589
01:23:20,066 --> 01:23:22,318
-VINCENT: Yes.
-I don't know what you're thinking really.

1590
01:23:24,403 --> 01:23:28,449
I think a lot of things
I don't tell you.

1591
01:23:28,533 --> 01:23:29,992
Otherwise, you'd fire me right now.

1592
01:23:30,076 --> 01:23:31,202
SANDRA:
No, no, no, Vincent.

1593
01:23:31,285 --> 01:23:33,204
In your head, you're thinking,

1594
01:23:33,287 --> 01:23:35,164
aren't you, because sometimes,
when you look at me,

1595
01:23:35,248 --> 01:23:36,999
just like right now,

1596
01:23:37,083 --> 01:23:38,918
I can feel
that you are judging me.

1597
01:23:40,294 --> 01:23:42,588
I don't know what you think.

1598
01:23:42,672 --> 01:23:45,424
VINCENT:
Sandra, I believe you.

1599
01:23:45,508 --> 01:23:46,634
I'm not judging you.

1600
01:24:07,488 --> 01:24:09,031
SANDRA (whispering):
My love...

1601
01:24:10,449 --> 01:24:12,368
I just want you to know one thing.

1602
01:24:12,451 --> 01:24:15,580
I'm not... I am not that, that...

1603
01:24:15,663 --> 01:24:18,207
I'm not that monster, you know?

1604
01:24:18,291 --> 01:24:21,002
Everything you hear in the trial,

1605
01:24:21,085 --> 01:24:23,087
uh, it's just...

1606
01:24:24,839 --> 01:24:27,466
It's twisted, you know?

1607
01:24:27,550 --> 01:24:30,678
And it wasn't
like that, you know.

1608
01:24:30,761 --> 01:24:32,847
Uh, your father...

1609
01:24:32,930 --> 01:24:35,600
Your father was my soul mate...

1610
01:24:35,683 --> 01:24:38,311
We chose each other
and I loved him...

1611
01:24:41,898 --> 01:24:43,566
But how do you prove that?

1612
01:24:49,697 --> 01:24:51,407
I just wish you would be shielded

1613
01:24:51,490 --> 01:24:53,534
from all this, you know,
that you could do...

1614
01:24:54,827 --> 01:24:56,787
That you could do children's stuff,

1615
01:24:56,871 --> 01:24:59,957
just a little bit,
that you could be a child,

1616
01:25:00,041 --> 01:25:02,001
just a bit longer, you know?

1617
01:25:12,970 --> 01:25:14,555
(gallery murmuring)

1618
01:25:16,891 --> 01:25:18,684
-(bell rings)
-BAILIFF (in French): All rise!

1619
01:25:27,401 --> 01:25:29,153
JUSTICE MINISTER:
You may be seated.

1620
01:25:31,072 --> 01:25:32,156
We'll begin

1621
01:25:32,240 --> 01:25:35,660
by calling
the Chief Investigator to the bar.

1622
01:25:35,743 --> 01:25:37,286
(assistant whispering
indistinctly in French)

1623
01:25:40,456 --> 01:25:42,166
ASSISTANT:
He insists, it's important.

1624
01:25:42,250 --> 01:25:46,754
(gallery murmuring)

1625
01:26:22,707 --> 01:26:23,708
(door thumps in distance)

1626
01:26:28,462 --> 01:26:30,256
You may be seated.

1627
01:26:32,425 --> 01:26:34,927
The Chief Investigator
has surely arrived,

1628
01:26:35,011 --> 01:26:37,388
so we'll start with him.

1629
01:26:38,264 --> 01:26:41,767
JUSTICE MINISTER:
Clerk, please cue Exhibit 31.

1630
01:26:43,978 --> 01:26:47,148
Bailiff, prepare to hand out

1631
01:26:47,231 --> 01:26:50,943
the transcription
of the recording to the jurors.

1632
01:26:52,403 --> 01:26:53,446
JUSTICE MINISTER:
Voilà.

1633
01:26:57,783 --> 01:26:59,076
Clerk?

1634
01:27:00,411 --> 01:27:01,662
SANDRA (on recording):
<i>What do you expect me to do?</i>

1635
01:27:01,746 --> 01:27:02,872
<i>I mean, it's part of the job,</i>

1636
01:27:02,955 --> 01:27:04,707
<i>you have to organize
yourself differently.</i>

1637
01:27:04,790 --> 01:27:05,958
<i>I'm not going to cancel.</i>

1638
01:27:06,042 --> 01:27:07,001
SAMUEL: <i>How am I supposed
to get organized</i>

1639
01:27:07,084 --> 01:27:08,669
<i>differently on my own?</i>

1640
01:27:08,753 --> 01:27:10,463
<i>You know we have
to plan things together.</i>

1641
01:27:13,007 --> 01:27:14,675
<i>I'm not just going
to leave Daniel alone</i>

1642
01:27:14,759 --> 01:27:16,093
<i>because you're off
doing your own thing.</i>

1643
01:27:16,177 --> 01:27:19,305
SANDRA: <i>Leave him with Monica,
what's the big deal?</i>

1644
01:27:19,388 --> 01:27:20,389
SAMUEL:
<i>Three days a week?</i>

1645
01:27:20,473 --> 01:27:22,308
<i>We'd have to pay her for that.</i>

1646
01:27:22,391 --> 01:27:23,684
<i>We can't afford it.</i>

1647
01:27:26,771 --> 01:27:28,356
SAMUEL:
<i>I need time.</i>

1648
01:27:28,439 --> 01:27:30,983
Not just a few hours,

1649
01:27:31,067 --> 01:27:32,777
I'm talking about blocking out
time for myself

1650
01:27:32,860 --> 01:27:34,487
for the whole year.

1651
01:27:34,570 --> 01:27:36,739
This isn't working
for me anymore.

1652
01:27:36,822 --> 01:27:39,408
(Samuel drinks beer,
sets down bottle)

1653
01:27:39,492 --> 01:27:41,911
Well, organize
your time differently

1654
01:27:41,994 --> 01:27:43,412
if you want to, it's up to you.

1655
01:27:43,496 --> 01:27:44,956
SAMUEL: When's the last time
you've helped him

1656
01:27:45,039 --> 01:27:46,332
-doing his homework?
-It's delicious.

1657
01:27:46,415 --> 01:27:47,959
There's a ton of things
you don't give a shit about,

1658
01:27:48,042 --> 01:27:50,795
but that's the time
I'm talking about.

1659
01:27:50,878 --> 01:27:52,713
SANDRA:
Darling, the book just came out,

1660
01:27:52,797 --> 01:27:54,841
you know very well
it's just this time--

1661
01:27:54,924 --> 01:27:57,677
It's always "just this time."

1662
01:27:59,512 --> 01:28:01,180
Whether you have a book out,

1663
01:28:01,264 --> 01:28:02,974
or you're writing,

1664
01:28:03,057 --> 01:28:05,768
or you need space to figure out
what to write...

1665
01:28:08,187 --> 01:28:10,731
I mean, I've been following
your lead for years.

1666
01:28:12,024 --> 01:28:14,443
I can't do anything with my time,

1667
01:28:14,527 --> 01:28:15,611
do you understand?

1668
01:28:19,407 --> 01:28:21,492
It's not my time, it's yours!

1669
01:28:26,497 --> 01:28:29,125
Do I force you to teach?

1670
01:28:30,835 --> 01:28:33,337
Do I force you
to homeschool Daniel?

1671
01:28:34,672 --> 01:28:36,507
No one's forcing you.

1672
01:28:36,591 --> 01:28:38,217
If you want to make
more time for yourself,

1673
01:28:38,301 --> 01:28:39,719
-I've never stopped you.
-Are you fucking serious?

1674
01:28:39,802 --> 01:28:41,012
(plate clatters)

1675
01:28:41,095 --> 01:28:43,306
I cut my course load
in half this year

1676
01:28:43,389 --> 01:28:46,017
to gain more time,
and it's still not enough.

1677
01:28:46,100 --> 01:28:47,810
I have to finish the renovation,

1678
01:28:47,894 --> 01:28:49,854
plus I'm dealing
with everything else.

1679
01:28:51,147 --> 01:28:54,025
Why do you refuse to talk about it?

1680
01:28:54,108 --> 01:28:56,110
Why can't you just admit
that it has to do

1681
01:28:56,194 --> 01:28:57,737
with how things
are divided between us?

1682
01:28:57,820 --> 01:28:59,071
SANDRA:
Because you are wrong,

1683
01:28:59,155 --> 01:29:01,991
I don't owe you any time,
I do my part.

1684
01:29:02,074 --> 01:29:06,120
C'mon, let's not start taking
inventory here, please.

1685
01:29:06,204 --> 01:29:07,622
Let's relax.

1686
01:29:14,462 --> 01:29:15,755
SANDRA (softly):
I love you.

1687
01:29:22,678 --> 01:29:25,473
SANDRA: When you decided
to homeschool Daniel,

1688
01:29:25,556 --> 01:29:27,767
I told you, "Be careful,"

1689
01:29:27,850 --> 01:29:29,685
it's a beautiful and generous choice,

1690
01:29:29,769 --> 01:29:32,021
and I thank you for it,
but you don't have to do it,

1691
01:29:32,104 --> 01:29:33,648
and I told you
it would force you to...

1692
01:29:33,731 --> 01:29:34,774
-SAMUEL: What?
-...cut your...

1693
01:29:34,857 --> 01:29:36,734
Force me to spend more time
with my son?

1694
01:29:38,194 --> 01:29:39,529
Well, I'm glad I did.

1695
01:29:40,780 --> 01:29:42,073
I wouldn't have the relationship

1696
01:29:42,156 --> 01:29:43,741
I have with him today if I didn't.

1697
01:29:47,203 --> 01:29:49,539
Yeah, the relationship
that I don't have with him

1698
01:29:49,622 --> 01:29:51,290
-is what you meant to say.
-No, I didn't say that.

1699
01:29:51,374 --> 01:29:52,750
-No.
-No.

1700
01:29:56,879 --> 01:30:00,800
SAMUEL:
I'm saying maybe, just maybe,

1701
01:30:00,883 --> 01:30:03,177
things are little
out of balance between us,

1702
01:30:03,261 --> 01:30:04,679
and I want you
to take a look at that.

1703
01:30:04,762 --> 01:30:06,138
Why is this so hard to discuss?

1704
01:30:06,222 --> 01:30:07,431
First of all, I don't believe

1705
01:30:07,515 --> 01:30:09,058
in the notion
of reciprocity in a couple.

1706
01:30:09,141 --> 01:30:11,185
It's naive and, frankly,
it's depressing.

1707
01:30:11,269 --> 01:30:12,478
Yes.

1708
01:30:12,562 --> 01:30:15,523
And I think discussing it
is a waste of time,

1709
01:30:15,606 --> 01:30:18,317
considering the state
you're in, seriously.

1710
01:30:18,401 --> 01:30:22,488
All this blah, blah, blah here
and more time is gone,

1711
01:30:22,572 --> 01:30:25,324
all this time spent chitchatting
could be spent in silence,

1712
01:30:25,408 --> 01:30:26,909
doing whatever you want to do,

1713
01:30:26,993 --> 01:30:28,244
if only you knew what it is that...

1714
01:30:28,327 --> 01:30:29,787
SAMUEL:
I want time to start writing,

1715
01:30:29,871 --> 01:30:31,539
just the same as you.

1716
01:30:31,622 --> 01:30:32,874
SANDRA: Do it.

1717
01:30:32,957 --> 01:30:34,375
I don't know a single writer
who doesn't write

1718
01:30:34,458 --> 01:30:36,460
just because he has a son
and a house and groceries to buy.

1719
01:30:36,544 --> 01:30:38,921
Stop whining
about your scheduling bullshit

1720
01:30:39,005 --> 01:30:40,840
and drop this logic which
comes down to casting blame

1721
01:30:40,923 --> 01:30:42,800
on me for what you did or didn't do.

1722
01:30:42,884 --> 01:30:45,636
I live with you,
I plan my life around you.

1723
01:30:47,388 --> 01:30:50,808
If I imposed on you
what you're imposing on me,

1724
01:30:50,892 --> 01:30:52,602
neither of us
would be able to write.

1725
01:30:52,685 --> 01:30:55,646
SANDRA: Don't worry about me,
I always manage to write.

1726
01:30:55,730 --> 01:30:58,566
-Great. Perfect.
-SANDRA: Yeah.

1727
01:30:58,649 --> 01:31:00,776
If you're so sure of yourself,
adapt-- that's all I'm asking.

1728
01:31:00,860 --> 01:31:03,237
I do adapt.
I take Daniel to school.

1729
01:31:03,321 --> 01:31:04,405
SAMUEL:
Once a week.

1730
01:31:04,488 --> 01:31:05,823
We have Monica
on Tuesdays, c'mon.

1731
01:31:05,907 --> 01:31:07,366
SAMUEL:
No, Sandra, don't be dishonest.

1732
01:31:07,450 --> 01:31:09,160
(scoffs) I'm not,
you're the one nitpicking.

1733
01:31:09,243 --> 01:31:10,286
SAMUEL:
I've given you too much--

1734
01:31:10,369 --> 01:31:12,747
too much time,
too many concessions.

1735
01:31:12,830 --> 01:31:16,626
I want this time back
and you owe it to me, be fair!

1736
01:31:16,709 --> 01:31:18,920
(laughs) I'm sorry,
but no, are you insane?

1737
01:31:19,003 --> 01:31:22,048
I don't owe you anything, really.

1738
01:31:22,131 --> 01:31:24,217
This is about
your relationship with your son

1739
01:31:24,300 --> 01:31:25,551
and to protect yourself
and your comfort

1740
01:31:25,635 --> 01:31:26,928
and because you got scared
and you put yourself

1741
01:31:27,011 --> 01:31:28,638
in that position.

1742
01:31:28,721 --> 01:31:32,266
It was your choice to come here
and start this renovation.

1743
01:31:32,350 --> 01:31:34,352
This is your own trap.

1744
01:31:34,435 --> 01:31:36,562
-Okay, now you're talking about the past.
-It's your own trap-- No!

1745
01:31:36,646 --> 01:31:38,231
-I could answer point by point.
-I'm not taking time from you!

1746
01:31:38,314 --> 01:31:39,398
-But fuck that!
-You wasted it all on your own!

1747
01:31:39,482 --> 01:31:41,150
I want things to change now.

