01:41:17,435 --> 01:41:20,104
But I couldn't, so we,
we hear them shattering.

1989
01:41:20,188 --> 01:41:22,481
(in French) Aside from that slap,
did you hit him?

1990
01:41:22,565 --> 01:41:23,608
No.

1991
01:41:25,276 --> 01:41:26,819
(in English)
What we hear next

1992
01:41:26,903 --> 01:41:29,405
is Samuel repeatedly hitting himself

1993
01:41:29,488 --> 01:41:31,574
in the face and in the head,

1994
01:41:31,657 --> 01:41:34,410
and then, uh, punching the wall.

1995
01:41:34,493 --> 01:41:35,912
You can still see the dent.

1996
01:41:35,995 --> 01:41:38,706
Um, there are a few of them
around the house.

1997
01:41:38,789 --> 01:41:40,416
It's not the first time
he'd done that.

1998
01:41:40,499 --> 01:41:42,293
Uh, years ago,

1999
01:41:42,376 --> 01:41:44,879
he already broke, um, a finger,

2000
01:41:44,962 --> 01:41:47,673
uh, punching the wall
during an episode.

2001
01:41:49,926 --> 01:41:52,678
(in French) We have photos
of those dents in the wall.

2002
01:41:52,762 --> 01:41:54,430
Thank you. Here.

2003
01:41:54,514 --> 01:41:56,974
And the X-ray
of his fractured finger,

2004
01:41:57,058 --> 01:42:00,686
taken in June 2017
at the hospital in Grenoble.

2005
01:42:01,896 --> 01:42:03,272
Is it fair to say

2006
01:42:03,356 --> 01:42:08,361
your depiction of the violence
is interpretive and not objective?

2007
01:42:09,987 --> 01:42:12,782
She repeatedly lied to us,
so believing her...

2008
01:42:12,865 --> 01:42:14,784
Thus, this is about believing,

2009
01:42:14,867 --> 01:42:16,244
or not believing.

2010
01:42:16,577 --> 01:42:18,538
It's a subjective opinion,

2011
01:42:18,621 --> 01:42:20,873
based on an ambiguous recording.

2012
01:42:21,832 --> 01:42:24,794
You link the argument
to the day of the death.

2013
01:42:24,877 --> 01:42:27,672
You call it a "dress rehearsal."

2014
01:42:27,755 --> 01:42:29,632
Do you have any direct proof?

2015
01:42:29,715 --> 01:42:32,844
The recording
is direct proof of a fight.

2016
01:42:32,927 --> 01:42:34,679
VINCENT:
I mean the day of the death.

2017
01:42:35,888 --> 01:42:39,308
With no witnesses or confessions,
we must interpret.

2018
01:42:41,769 --> 01:42:44,981
In fact, this violent fight is...

2019
01:42:45,064 --> 01:42:48,150
phantasmal--
it exists only as fantasy.

2020
01:42:48,776 --> 01:42:50,319
You float the idea,

2021
01:42:50,403 --> 01:42:52,154
the prosecutor floats it,

2022
01:42:52,238 --> 01:42:55,116
over or around the facts,

2023
01:42:55,199 --> 01:42:58,536
making it omnipresent
here in court, but...

2024
01:43:00,371 --> 01:43:03,624
We risk turning this fantasy
into a reality

2025
01:43:03,708 --> 01:43:07,253
simply because
there was indeed a fight

2026
01:43:07,336 --> 01:43:10,131
the day before Mr. Maleski died.

2027
01:43:10,673 --> 01:43:14,552
Don't substitute the day
before for the next day.

2028
01:43:15,761 --> 01:43:19,515
We can't fill the blanks
with a supposition,

2029
01:43:19,599 --> 01:43:23,436
simply because we have sounds
for one and not the other.

2030
01:43:23,519 --> 01:43:24,520
JUSTICE MINISTER:
Ms. Voyter,

2031
01:43:24,604 --> 01:43:28,566
did you know he'd recorded you
before you were told?

2032
01:43:29,901 --> 01:43:31,277
SANDRA (in English):
No. But I knew that

2033
01:43:31,360 --> 01:43:33,821
he often recorded moments
of our lives.

2034
01:43:33,905 --> 01:43:36,282
JUSTICE MINISTER (in French):
He didn't always let you know?

2035
01:43:36,365 --> 01:43:38,409
What were these recordings?

2036
01:43:39,160 --> 01:43:41,245
(in English) Um, at first,
he would mention it,

2037
01:43:41,329 --> 01:43:44,415
yes, but after a while he did it
without us really knowing.

2038
01:43:44,498 --> 01:43:49,587
He recorded conversations,
Daniel's piano lessons...

2039
01:43:49,670 --> 01:43:53,174
and sometimes just himself,
talking to himself.

2040
01:43:53,257 --> 01:43:55,801
And I think he did that because
he wanted to gather material

2041
01:43:55,885 --> 01:43:57,595
to help him start writing again.

2042
01:43:59,180 --> 01:44:02,600
Now, with hindsight,
it seems possible

2043
01:44:02,683 --> 01:44:04,519
that he could have
provoked this fight

2044
01:44:04,602 --> 01:44:06,187
just to record it.

2045
01:44:06,270 --> 01:44:08,523
ADVOCATE GENERAL (in French):
Wait, are you implying

2046
01:44:08,606 --> 01:44:10,608
you're the victim of a twisted man?

2047
01:44:10,691 --> 01:44:11,817
NOUR: Seriously?

2048
01:44:12,401 --> 01:44:15,905
He recorded her in secret.
It's a valid question.

2049
01:44:15,988 --> 01:44:18,574
You forget the situation is perverse.

2050
01:44:19,408 --> 01:44:20,785
Now the victim is on trial!

2051
01:44:20,868 --> 01:44:22,870
NOUR:
No, but my client has a point.

2052
01:44:22,954 --> 01:44:26,332
Can you explain
what he means by cheating,

2053
01:44:26,415 --> 01:44:27,917
and how he found out?

2054
01:44:28,835 --> 01:44:30,002
(Sandra sighs)

2055
01:44:30,086 --> 01:44:31,379
(in English)
He went through my phone

2056
01:44:31,462 --> 01:44:33,589
and he discovered messages
from a woman

2057
01:44:33,673 --> 01:44:35,550
I'd met at the beginning
of that year.

2058
01:44:35,633 --> 01:44:38,344
ADVOCATE GENERAL (in French):
What do you mean by "met"?

2059
01:44:38,427 --> 01:44:39,637
(in English)
It was sexual.

2060
01:44:39,720 --> 01:44:41,013
We slept together twice.

2061
01:44:41,097 --> 01:44:42,223
ADVOCATE GENERAL (in French):
Twice?

2062
01:44:42,306 --> 01:44:43,391
(in French)
Yes.

2063
01:44:43,474 --> 01:44:46,102
ADVOCATE GENERAL:
On the recording you said once.

2064
01:44:47,103 --> 01:44:49,146
(in English)
It meant with just one person.

2065
01:44:50,064 --> 01:44:51,774
(in French)
Hang on...

2066
01:44:51,858 --> 01:44:55,444
Samuel mentions
numerous affairs in the past.

2067
01:44:55,528 --> 01:44:58,322
It sounds like
you cheated constantly.

2068
01:44:58,406 --> 01:44:59,949
(in English)
That's not-- That's not true.

2069
01:45:00,032 --> 01:45:02,368
Uh, I had a few flings, um,

2070
01:45:02,451 --> 01:45:04,245
the year of Daniel's accident.

2071
01:45:04,328 --> 01:45:06,205
And it wasn't cheating,
because Samuel knew.

2072
01:45:06,289 --> 01:45:08,249
ADVOCATE GENERAL (in French):
He found out each time?

2073
01:45:08,332 --> 01:45:09,792
(in English)
No, I told him.

2074
01:45:10,793 --> 01:45:12,211
It was a tricky year. Heh.

2075
01:45:12,295 --> 01:45:14,797
ADVOCATE GENERAL (in French):
You want us to believe he agreed to it?

2076
01:45:14,881 --> 01:45:16,716
(in English)
Uh, I'm not saying that,

2077
01:45:16,799 --> 01:45:20,052
I'm just saying I was honest about it.

2078
01:45:20,136 --> 01:45:21,929
(in French)
Interesting take on honesty.

2079
01:45:22,013 --> 01:45:25,474
But the year he died,
you quit being honest, why?

2080
01:45:27,143 --> 01:45:28,311
(sighs)

2081
01:45:28,394 --> 01:45:30,104
(in English)
Things were different...

2082
01:45:30,188 --> 01:45:33,608
I felt that it would hurt him
too much, at that time, so...

2083
01:45:33,691 --> 01:45:36,611
(in French) Because you had feelings
for that woman?

2084
01:45:36,694 --> 01:45:38,362
(in English) No, I felt
it would hurt him too much

2085
01:45:38,446 --> 01:45:39,780
because he was fragile.

2086
01:45:39,864 --> 01:45:42,867
And, uh, as I said,

2087
01:45:42,950 --> 01:45:44,660
with her, it was just sexual.

2088
01:45:44,744 --> 01:45:47,288
And the person I had
feelings for was Samuel.

2089
01:45:47,371 --> 01:45:49,540
(in French)
Interesting take on feelings.

2090
01:45:49,624 --> 01:45:51,042
I'm trying to understand.

2091
01:45:51,125 --> 01:45:54,420
At first you agreed
on an open relationship,

2092
01:45:54,504 --> 01:45:56,214
then that changed?

2093
01:45:57,006 --> 01:45:58,925
(in English) Uh, I don't even know
what that means, really I'm sorry.

2094
01:45:59,008 --> 01:46:00,635
-(A.G. speaks French)
-No, pardon.

2095
01:46:00,718 --> 01:46:02,595
(in English) No, we never had
that kind of agreement,

2096
01:46:02,678 --> 01:46:04,263
or something like that.

2097
01:46:04,347 --> 01:46:06,182
After the accident, we were both

2098
01:46:06,265 --> 01:46:08,518
trying to feel better,

2099
01:46:08,601 --> 01:46:10,478
and I needed that
to keep it together,

2100
01:46:10,561 --> 01:46:11,812
and I was honest about it.

2101
01:46:11,896 --> 01:46:15,733
(in French) But then you quit being honest
and he held you accountable.

2102
01:46:15,816 --> 01:46:18,319
He doesn't sound "fragile."

2103
01:46:18,402 --> 01:46:20,863
-Do you admit he was jealous?
-Yes.

2104
01:46:20,947 --> 01:46:23,032
Had he become obsessed?

2105
01:46:23,115 --> 01:46:24,992
(in English)
No, I don't-- I don't know.

2106
01:46:25,076 --> 01:46:27,203
He was hurt, that's true.

2107
01:46:27,286 --> 01:46:29,956
And, uh,
sometimes when we fought,

2108
01:46:30,039 --> 01:46:32,875
he brought it up, but he didn't
think about all the time.

2109
01:46:34,168 --> 01:46:35,336
According to your logic,

2110
01:46:35,419 --> 01:46:36,921
all of Samuel's problems

2111
01:46:37,004 --> 01:46:39,298
were my fault, that's not true.

2112
01:46:39,382 --> 01:46:41,342
I mean, his pain came
from deeper places.

2113
01:46:41,425 --> 01:46:45,680
(in French) According to his logic,
you're to blame, as we heard.

2114
01:46:45,763 --> 01:46:49,308
What does he mean when he says
his work was plundered?

2115
01:46:49,392 --> 01:46:50,643
(in English)
No. There never was any--

2116
01:46:50,726 --> 01:46:52,645
There wasn't any plundering.

2117
01:46:52,728 --> 01:46:54,856
In the that book he abandoned,
and that's important,

2118
01:46:54,939 --> 01:46:56,399
there was
a very interesting passage--

2119
01:46:56,482 --> 01:46:58,776
ADVOCATE GENERAL (in French):
A passage? How many pages?

2120
01:46:58,860 --> 01:47:00,319
(in English)
About twenty.

2121
01:47:00,403 --> 01:47:01,362
(in French)
Twenty-seven.

2122
01:47:01,445 --> 01:47:02,738
(in English)
Oui. Yeah, it was just

2123
01:47:02,822 --> 01:47:04,198
a rough outline, and I thought

2124
01:47:04,282 --> 01:47:05,575
the idea was brilliant.

2125
01:47:05,658 --> 01:47:06,868
ADVOCATE GENERAL (in French):
Can you summarize it?

2126
01:47:06,951 --> 01:47:09,787
NOUR: Must we enter
into a literary debate?

2127
01:47:09,871 --> 01:47:11,873
ADVOCATE GENERAL:
This isn't literary, it's concrete.

2128
01:47:12,123 --> 01:47:13,833
It's the heart of their conflict.

2129
01:47:14,166 --> 01:47:17,503
I don't know how else
to present it to the jurors.

2130
01:47:17,587 --> 01:47:18,671
Nor do I.

2131
01:47:18,754 --> 01:47:19,797
Proceed.

2132
01:47:19,881 --> 01:47:21,924
(in English)
Well, this passage

2133
01:47:22,008 --> 01:47:24,302
was about a guy imagining
how his life would've been

2134
01:47:24,385 --> 01:47:27,138
without the accident
that killed his brother.

2135
01:47:27,221 --> 01:47:28,681
One day, he wakes up, finds himself

2136
01:47:28,764 --> 01:47:30,266
in two different realities:

2137
01:47:30,349 --> 01:47:32,185
One where the accident
is the center of his life,

2138
01:47:32,268 --> 01:47:34,604
and one where the accident
never happened.

2139
01:47:34,687 --> 01:47:37,148
I told Samuel I loved it.

2140
01:47:37,231 --> 01:47:40,610
He had me read everything
he wrote back then.

2141
01:47:40,693 --> 01:47:43,905
And soon after,
he abandoned the whole book.

2142
01:47:43,988 --> 01:47:46,949
I asked him if I could
use the idea and he said yes.

2143
01:47:47,033 --> 01:47:48,659
No.

2144
01:47:48,743 --> 01:47:51,454
(in French) He couldn't have said yes,
he calls it plundering.

2145
01:47:51,537 --> 01:47:53,372
SANDRA (in English):
It's an argument.

2146
01:47:53,456 --> 01:47:56,542
People exaggerate and alter
facts when they argue.

2147
01:47:56,626 --> 01:47:59,962
(in French) It's no exaggeration to say
his book became yours: <i>Eclipse.</i>

2148
01:48:00,588 --> 01:48:02,507
(scoffs, stammers)

2149
01:48:02,590 --> 01:48:04,008
ADVOCATE GENERAL:
Non?

2150
01:48:04,091 --> 01:48:07,803
(in English)
All I took was this idea.

2151
01:48:07,887 --> 01:48:10,681
My characters are a woman
and her daughter,

2152
01:48:10,765 --> 01:48:13,476
and I developed the story
over 300 pages.

2153
01:48:15,228 --> 01:48:17,688
(scoffs)
I can't believe I must tell you

2154
01:48:17,772 --> 01:48:20,399
what is the difference
between an outline and a novel.

2155
01:48:20,483 --> 01:48:23,736
He agreed to it,
and when he read it, he told me

2156
01:48:23,819 --> 01:48:26,322
I-- I did something
very different with it.

2157
01:48:26,405 --> 01:48:28,074
And sometimes,
yes, when we argued,

2158
01:48:28,157 --> 01:48:31,410
it came out,
because he was upset,

2159
01:48:31,494 --> 01:48:33,204
because he couldn't write.

2160
01:48:33,287 --> 01:48:37,083
(in French) The only thing we know
for sure is that "it came out."

2161
01:48:37,166 --> 01:48:38,876
Did the two of you...

2162
01:48:39,460 --> 01:48:42,505
argue again
before the time of his death?

2163
01:48:42,588 --> 01:48:44,882
It must've been very tense.

2164
01:48:47,426 --> 01:48:49,679
(in English)
We were...

2165
01:48:49,762 --> 01:48:51,556
We were both really shaken.

2166
01:48:51,639 --> 01:48:53,558
We were
both keeping to ourselves.

2167
01:48:53,641 --> 01:48:56,060
And Samuel, he was...

2168
01:48:56,143 --> 01:48:57,895
I don't know, something was gone,

2169
01:48:57,979 --> 01:49:00,648
he was depleted,
his energy was just gone.

2170
01:49:00,731 --> 01:49:01,816
ADVOCATE GENERAL (in French):
In the audio,

2171
01:49:01,899 --> 01:49:04,485
I hear Samuel Maleski
arguing strenuously.

2172
01:49:04,569 --> 01:49:07,947
I hear a man determined
to regain control of his life.

2173
01:49:08,030 --> 01:49:11,075
In no way a man
who has decided to give up.

2174
01:49:11,158 --> 01:49:15,788
Samuel's psychiatrist said
he was combative in their last sessions.

2175
01:49:15,872 --> 01:49:20,585
Do you kill yourself after fighting
for time and self-esteem?

2176
01:49:20,668 --> 01:49:25,298
Do you kill yourself after pleading
so fiercely and energetically

2177
01:49:25,381 --> 01:49:28,885
for balance and justice
in your relationship? No.

2178
01:49:29,886 --> 01:49:32,763
That's the main flaw
in the suicide theory.

2179
01:49:32,847 --> 01:49:36,142
You say he seemed "depleted."

2180
01:49:36,225 --> 01:49:37,810
His energy was gone.

2181
01:49:38,144 --> 01:49:42,231
I'd like to read from one of Ms. Voyter's
recent books, <i>The Black House.</i>

2182
01:49:42,315 --> 01:49:44,233
NOUR:
We judge facts, not books.

2183
01:49:44,317 --> 01:49:47,111
Judge, this is a slippery slope.

2184
01:49:47,195 --> 01:49:50,698
In 2017, Sandra Voyter herself
declared, and I quote,

2185
01:49:50,781 --> 01:49:53,993
"My books are linked to my life
and those in it."

2186
01:49:54,076 --> 01:49:57,163
Objection!
She's always said her work is fiction.

2187
01:49:57,580 --> 01:50:00,124
First book is her mother's death!

2188
01:50:00,208 --> 01:50:02,043
Second, a rift with her father.

2189
01:50:02,126 --> 01:50:04,420
Third, her son's accident, etc.

2190
01:50:04,504 --> 01:50:06,672
Her books are part of this trial.

2191
01:50:06,756 --> 01:50:09,717
Her life is in them,
her relationship in particular.

2192
01:50:09,800 --> 01:50:11,636
Go ahead, but keep it brief.

2193
01:50:12,303 --> 01:50:15,640
This is a wife
talking about her husband.

2194
01:50:18,267 --> 01:50:21,646
"He'd stopped complaining.
He'd given up.

2195
01:50:21,729 --> 01:50:25,024
"She studied him,
repulsed by his resignation.

2196
01:50:25,733 --> 01:50:29,111
"An idea sprouted in her mind,
a seed of deliverance.

2197
01:50:29,195 --> 01:50:30,780
The possibility of his death."

2198
01:50:30,863 --> 01:50:32,031
NOUR:
Give us the context.

2199
01:50:32,114 --> 01:50:34,033
Later: "How does one kill?"

2200
01:50:34,116 --> 01:50:36,994
"What about the body? Its weight?

2201
01:50:37,078 --> 01:50:38,996
"She could think of nothing else.

2202
01:50:39,789 --> 01:50:43,626
"She saw him dead,
his body a lump no longer desired.

2203
01:50:43,709 --> 01:50:45,545
-(Nour interjects)
-"The body she'd loved

2204
01:50:45,628 --> 01:50:47,964
was now in the way and had to go."

2205
01:50:48,047 --> 01:50:49,966
NOUR:
I'll provide the context.

2206
01:50:50,049 --> 01:50:53,553
This is a minor character going insane

2207
01:50:53,636 --> 01:50:55,721
who doesn't act on her thoughts.

2208
01:50:55,805 --> 01:50:58,307
A novel is not life!
An author is not her characters.

2209
01:50:58,391 --> 01:51:01,769
But an author can express herself
through her characters.

2210
01:51:01,853 --> 01:51:03,396
You flagged this passage.

2211
01:51:03,479 --> 01:51:05,439
How can we not see a link?

2212
01:51:05,523 --> 01:51:07,567
Is Stephen King a serial killer?

2213
01:51:07,650 --> 01:51:10,736
ADVOCATE GENERAL: Did his wife
turn up dead in suspicious circumstances?

2214
01:51:10,820 --> 01:51:12,071
Focus on the facts!

2215
01:51:12,154 --> 01:51:15,575
Mr. Renzi, I strongly advise you
to calm down.

2216
01:51:15,658 --> 01:51:19,495
Prosecutor, I advise you
to follow Mr. Renzi's advice.

2217
01:51:19,579 --> 01:51:21,747
Focus on the facts.

2218
01:51:25,001 --> 01:51:26,752
Aside from the slap

2219
01:51:26,836 --> 01:51:29,338
you admitted to,
did you ever hit your husband?

2220
01:51:29,422 --> 01:51:31,048
-SANDRA: Non.
-ADVOCATE GENERAL: Non? Never?

2221
01:51:31,132 --> 01:51:32,008
SANDRA: Non.

2222
01:51:32,091 --> 01:51:33,176
-ADVOCATE GENERAL: That was it?
-Oui.

2223
01:51:33,467 --> 01:51:36,179
You were always a good,
admirable soul,

2224
01:51:37,013 --> 01:51:38,890
altruistic, reasonable,

2225
01:51:38,973 --> 01:51:41,184
trying to save him from himself,

2226
01:51:41,267 --> 01:51:43,352
except on this recording?
Rotten luck!

2227
01:51:43,436 --> 01:51:44,812
(gallery murmuring)

2228
01:51:45,396 --> 01:51:47,481
Any more questions for the witness?

2229
01:51:47,565 --> 01:51:49,692
VINCENT:
I have one more, if I may.

2230
01:51:50,985 --> 01:51:53,654
I'd like to know if Maleski

2231
01:51:53,738 --> 01:51:55,865
sent the transcripts to anyone?

2232
01:51:55,948 --> 01:51:58,659
He sent them to a publisher friend,
Paul Nachez,

2233
01:51:58,743 --> 01:52:00,536
slated to publish his first novel.

2234
01:52:00,620 --> 01:52:04,624
Email from August 9, 2017:
"I'm writing again, I need your eye.

2235
01:52:04,707 --> 01:52:06,250
Still rough, eager to talk."

2236
01:52:06,334 --> 01:52:07,668
Nachez's response:

2237
01:52:07,752 --> 01:52:10,129
"Sure, send it and I'll read it."

2238
01:52:10,213 --> 01:52:13,257
Up to his death,
Maleski sent four texts a week.

2239
01:52:13,341 --> 01:52:15,259
What was their communication like?

2240
01:52:15,343 --> 01:52:17,011
CHIEF INVESTIGATOR:
The publisher never replied.

2241
01:52:17,845 --> 01:52:20,556
Apparently he was busy
and the project mystified him.

2242
01:52:21,265 --> 01:52:23,017
His friend's silence

2243
01:52:23,100 --> 01:52:26,687
must've hurt Mr. Maleski's
already low self-esteem.

2244
01:52:27,438 --> 01:52:28,981
He feels rejected.

2245
01:52:29,482 --> 01:52:32,318
When we read all the writing he sent,

2246
01:52:32,401 --> 01:52:34,779
it's difficult to identify a storyline.

2247
01:52:34,862 --> 01:52:36,531
At best, it's a project.

2248
01:52:36,614 --> 01:52:38,199
Maleski is a "project man."

2249
01:52:38,282 --> 01:52:40,785
His first abandoned novel,
the chalet...

2250
01:52:41,494 --> 01:52:45,540
So, since we're being asked
to mix justice and literature,

2251
01:52:45,623 --> 01:52:47,583
to imagine what we don't know,

2252
01:52:47,667 --> 01:52:51,546
let's imagine
Samuel Maleski's final year.

2253
01:52:51,629 --> 01:52:53,548
ADVOCATE GENERAL:
And I'm dabbling in fantasy?

2254
01:52:53,631 --> 01:52:55,842
VINCENT: Give me half the time
you took to read a book!

2255
01:52:55,925 --> 01:52:57,593
(Advocate General responds)

2256
01:52:57,677 --> 01:52:59,011
JUSTICE MINISTER:
Get to the point.

2257
01:52:59,679 --> 01:53:01,848
What was
Samuel Maleski's final year like?

2258
01:53:03,266 --> 01:53:07,520
After accumulating debt
from medical procedures in London,

2259
01:53:07,603 --> 01:53:10,731
he insists on returning
to his hometown.

2260
01:53:10,815 --> 01:53:14,485
He finds a chalet to fix up and rent.
They'll pay off their debts.

2261
01:53:14,569 --> 01:53:17,530
He'll quit teaching
and start writing full-time.

2262
01:53:17,947 --> 01:53:21,868
Renovation proves tricky.
They have to take out a loan.

2263
01:53:22,451 --> 01:53:24,537
A vicious circle begins.

2264
01:53:24,620 --> 01:53:28,708
Samuel needs his teaching wages.
Renovations drag on.

2265
01:53:28,791 --> 01:53:31,043
A year and a half later,

2266
01:53:31,127 --> 01:53:32,503
he feels trapped.

2267
01:53:32,837 --> 01:53:34,505
He's a wounded man.

2268
01:53:34,589 --> 01:53:36,465
His son's accident,
his abandoned novel,

2269
01:53:36,549 --> 01:53:38,926
his wife publishing book after book...

2270
01:53:39,677 --> 01:53:41,095
He must write!

2271
01:53:43,431 --> 01:53:46,851
He quits the antidepressants
and starts recording his life,

2272
01:53:46,934 --> 01:53:49,604
embarking on a kind of autofiction,

2273
01:53:49,687 --> 01:53:52,815
perhaps inspired by Sandra's method.

2274
01:53:52,899 --> 01:53:55,902
And why not?
She borrows from their lives.

2275
01:53:55,985 --> 01:53:58,070
She did borrow his idea.

2276
01:53:58,154 --> 01:53:59,488
Save it for your plea.

2277
01:53:59,572 --> 01:54:03,659
VINCENT: He's running,
but refuses to see that transcribing

2278
01:54:03,743 --> 01:54:04,869
is not writing.

2279
01:54:04,952 --> 01:54:07,622
His publisher friend's silence
humiliates him.

2280
01:54:08,873 --> 01:54:11,792
What do we hear
in the March 4th fight?

2281
01:54:12,126 --> 01:54:15,087
The energy, the willfulness...
What is it?

2282
01:54:15,463 --> 01:54:17,131
The energy of despair.

2283
01:54:17,215 --> 01:54:20,051
The final push before giving up.

2284
01:54:23,346 --> 01:54:27,600
In his final days, this man
isn't facing a war in his marriage.

2285
01:54:28,809 --> 01:54:30,895
He's facing his own failures.

2286
01:54:32,605 --> 01:54:34,815
Sandra Voyter is only guilty

2287
01:54:34,899 --> 01:54:37,568
of succeeding
where her husband failed.

2288
01:54:41,614 --> 01:54:46,035
Despite appearances, those were
not Mr. Renzi's closing arguments.

2289
01:54:46,118 --> 01:54:47,286
(gallery murmuring)

2290
01:54:47,370 --> 01:54:48,538
SANDRA (in English):
That was not Samuel--

2291
01:54:48,621 --> 01:54:50,790
JUSTICE MINISTER:
Bon. It's Friday evening,

2292
01:54:50,873 --> 01:54:52,834
we have a weekend ahead of us.

2293
01:54:53,501 --> 01:54:56,128
Before I adjourn,
I have an announcement.

2294
01:54:56,212 --> 01:54:59,549
I've decided to call Daniel
back to the bar on Monday.

2295
01:54:59,966 --> 01:55:02,385
He has new information of interest.

2296
01:55:02,468 --> 01:55:05,972
Since the witness
is the defendant's son

2297
01:55:06,430 --> 01:55:08,766
-and lives with his mother...
-(Nour whispering)

2298
01:55:08,850 --> 01:55:12,019
I'm asking everyone
to refrain from contacting him.

2299
01:55:12,478 --> 01:55:15,982
Obviously, if contact is inevitable,

2300
01:55:16,065 --> 01:55:19,068
refrain from discussing the trial.

2301
01:55:19,151 --> 01:55:20,486
Ms. Berger,

2302
01:55:20,570 --> 01:55:23,656
you'll stay with Daniel all weekend.

2303
01:55:24,657 --> 01:55:28,202
See to it these rules are respected.

2304
01:55:28,286 --> 01:55:30,204
I insist that no one,

2305
01:55:30,288 --> 01:55:33,833
absolutely no one,
can ask him about his testimony.

2306
01:55:33,916 --> 01:55:35,376
Voilà.

2307
01:55:35,459 --> 01:55:37,753
Have a good weekend,
get some rest.

2308
01:55:37,837 --> 01:55:39,547
Court is adjourned.

2309
01:55:39,630 --> 01:55:41,674
(people chattering and moving about)

2310
01:56:27,678 --> 01:56:29,847
-(in French) Come get warm.
-SANDRA (in French): Ready in 10!

2311
01:56:36,145 --> 01:56:37,230
MARGE (in French):
You okay?

2312
01:56:43,194 --> 01:56:44,529
DANIEL (in French):
I think...

2313
01:56:44,612 --> 01:56:46,697
I think I want to be alone.

2314
01:56:48,157 --> 01:56:49,325
MARGE:
Okay.

2315
01:56:51,035 --> 01:56:53,412
-MARGE: You can eat in your room.
-DANIEL: No.

2316
01:56:53,496 --> 01:56:55,373
I want to be alone this weekend.

2317
01:56:55,873 --> 01:56:57,083
Before I testify.

2318
01:56:57,166 --> 01:56:58,167
MARGE:
Alone?

2319
01:56:58,251 --> 01:56:59,877
Just you and me?

2320
01:57:00,878 --> 01:57:02,004
Is that it?

2321
01:57:03,506 --> 01:57:05,258
Are you sure?

2322
01:57:06,342 --> 01:57:09,595
We can find other solutions.
It's a big house.

2323
01:57:10,221 --> 01:57:11,722
DANIEL:
I want her to leave.

2324
01:57:13,182 --> 01:57:14,267
MARGE (whispers):
Okay.

2325
01:57:20,314 --> 01:57:21,274
MARGE: Sandra...

2326
01:57:22,692 --> 01:57:24,235
MARGE:
I just spoke to Daniel.

2327
01:57:25,319 --> 01:57:28,072
He wants to be alone this weekend.

2328
01:57:28,155 --> 01:57:29,866
Until the end of the trial.

2329
01:57:30,992 --> 01:57:31,993
SANDRA:
Oh.

2330
01:57:33,202 --> 01:57:34,370
SANDRA:
Daniel?

2331
01:57:44,172 --> 01:57:46,257
(in English)
Is-- Is that what you want?

2332
01:57:51,262 --> 01:57:53,055
Okay, is it because
of what you heard today?

2333
01:57:53,139 --> 01:57:55,224
Because, uh...
I couldn't talk to you

2334
01:57:55,308 --> 01:57:57,310
about all that before,
do you understand?

2335
01:57:57,393 --> 01:57:59,103
We just weren't allowed
to talk to you about it...

2336
01:57:59,187 --> 01:58:00,479
MARGE (in French):
Please...

2337
01:58:01,189 --> 01:58:02,398
No trial talk.

2338
01:58:02,481 --> 01:58:05,276
(in French)
I know, I'm just talking to my son.

2339
01:58:05,359 --> 01:58:09,030
(in English)
Okay? Um, I totally understand

2340
01:58:09,113 --> 01:58:12,283
that you need calm, but I can
just mind my own business,

2341
01:58:12,366 --> 01:58:14,660
keep to myself-- I won't talk
to you if you don't want to.

2342
01:58:14,744 --> 01:58:16,746
-MARGE (in French): Wait.
-(in English) Can we try that?

2343
01:58:16,829 --> 01:58:17,997
MARGE (in French):
No speaking English.

2344
01:58:18,080 --> 01:58:21,083
SANDRA (in French):
Daniel, you can talk to me.

2345
01:58:22,168 --> 01:58:26,339
Couldn't you and I discuss this,
and then you decide?

2346
01:58:28,508 --> 01:58:30,510
MARGE:
I think he's made his decision.

2347
01:58:39,227 --> 01:58:41,187
Um...

2348
01:58:41,270 --> 01:58:43,481
(in English) Yeah, I will
just get my, my stuff.

2349
01:59:10,007 --> 01:59:13,052
(in English)
Somebody said, "Of course,

2350
01:59:13,135 --> 01:59:15,096
"money doesn't make you happy,

2351
01:59:15,179 --> 01:59:18,766
but it's still better to, to cry
in a car than in the subway."

2352
01:59:18,850 --> 01:59:22,228
(Vincent and Sandra laughing)

2353
01:59:22,311 --> 01:59:23,479
VINCENT (in English):
Who said that?

2354
01:59:23,563 --> 01:59:25,481
SANDRA:
I don't know.

2355
01:59:29,777 --> 01:59:32,154
(both laugh)

2356
01:59:41,706 --> 01:59:43,040
(Sandra deeply sighs)

2357
01:59:46,210 --> 01:59:47,670
(sobbing)

2358
02:00:26,542 --> 02:00:27,793
SANDRA (in French):
Sorry.

2359
02:00:32,548 --> 02:00:34,425
(muffled chattering outside)

2360
02:00:43,935 --> 02:00:46,020
(Snoop's paws clacking on floor)

2361
02:00:53,486 --> 02:00:54,529
DANIEL (in French):
Go on.

2362
02:01:01,410 --> 02:01:02,703
Eat up.

2363
02:01:05,331 --> 02:01:06,666
(kisses)

2364
02:01:10,127 --> 02:01:12,088
(rain pattering on window)

2365
02:01:30,565 --> 02:01:31,858
(dishes clattering in distance)

2366
02:01:31,941 --> 02:01:33,067
(whispers)
Snoop...

2367
02:01:33,150 --> 02:01:34,610
(Snoop breathing lightly)

2368
02:01:34,694 --> 02:01:38,072
(louder)
Snoop? Snoop? Snoop?

2369
02:01:38,155 --> 02:01:39,365
(Daniel panting and gasping)

2370
02:01:39,448 --> 02:01:41,617
-(Snoop grunting softly)
-Snoop?

2371
02:01:45,288 --> 02:01:46,455
Marge!

2372
02:01:48,875 --> 02:01:51,169
Marge, come quick, please!

2373
02:01:54,005 --> 02:01:55,256
Snoop?

2374
02:01:55,339 --> 02:01:57,633
-(Daniel sobbing)
-(footsteps approaching)

2375
02:01:57,717 --> 02:01:59,093
MARGE: What is it?

2376
02:02:01,637 --> 02:02:04,140
I gave him aspirin,
I messed up bad.

2377
02:02:05,224 --> 02:02:07,351
-MARGE: You gave him aspirin?
-DANIEL: Yes!

2378
02:02:07,435 --> 02:02:09,061
MARGE: How much?

2379
02:02:09,145 --> 02:02:11,606
DANIEL:
Eight or ten, I can't remember.

2380
02:02:11,689 --> 02:02:12,773
A lot.

2381
02:02:13,566 --> 02:02:15,026
DANIEL:
Make him vomit.

2382
02:02:15,109 --> 02:02:16,986
MARGE:
Why'd you do that?

2383
02:02:17,069 --> 02:02:18,029
DANIEL:
Make him vomit!

2384
02:02:18,112 --> 02:02:19,906
-Please!
-MARGE: Okay, hang on.

2385
02:02:19,989 --> 02:02:21,616
(Marge sighs deeply)

2386
02:02:22,241 --> 02:02:23,534
"Make a dog vomit."

2387
02:02:24,118 --> 02:02:25,411
MARGE: Hang on.

2388
02:02:25,494 --> 02:02:28,164
We need saltwater.
Be right back.

2389
02:02:28,247 --> 02:02:29,832
(Daniel continues sobbing)

2390
02:02:30,708 --> 02:02:32,043
(faucet running nearby)

2391
02:02:38,341 --> 02:02:39,550
DANIEL: He's not moving!

2392
02:02:39,634 --> 02:02:41,219
Daniel, help me.

2393
02:02:42,470 --> 02:02:43,846
Open his mouth.

2394
02:02:44,722 --> 02:02:45,723
Easy. Easy.

2395
02:02:51,729 --> 02:02:55,233
(Marge speaking French)

2396
02:02:55,316 --> 02:02:56,859
MARGE: That's right.

2397
02:02:56,943 --> 02:03:02,240
(Marge speaking French)

2398
02:03:02,323 --> 02:03:03,574
MARGE: That's good.

2399
02:03:03,658 --> 02:03:06,118
(Marge speaks French)

2400
02:03:06,202 --> 02:03:07,954
MARGE:
He's coming around.

2401
02:03:10,540 --> 02:03:13,084
-What's happening?
-He's going to vomit.

2402
02:03:13,751 --> 02:03:14,919
(wretches)

2403
02:03:15,002 --> 02:03:16,212
(Marge speaks French)

2404
02:03:17,213 --> 02:03:18,881
(Marge vocalizes calming noises)

2405
02:03:18,965 --> 02:03:20,007
MARGE (whispering):
That's it.

2406
02:03:20,091 --> 02:03:21,425
He'll be okay.

2407
02:03:23,261 --> 02:03:25,096
(Marge speaks French)

2408
02:03:25,179 --> 02:03:26,597
MARGE:
Good dog.

2409
02:03:26,681 --> 02:03:30,393
(Marge speaks French)

2410
02:03:30,476 --> 02:03:31,853
Oh, oui.

2411
02:03:31,936 --> 02:03:34,605
(Marge speaks French)

2412
02:03:34,689 --> 02:03:37,525
MARGE: He's okay, he's breathing.
Looking at us.

2413
02:03:37,608 --> 02:03:40,486
(Marge speaks French, sighs)

2414
02:03:42,947 --> 02:03:44,198
MARGE: Can you explain?

2415
02:03:44,282 --> 02:03:45,491
(Daniel sobbing)

2416
02:03:47,994 --> 02:03:49,370
DANIEL: You know, I...

2417
02:03:50,079 --> 02:03:52,123
I'd never heard about...

2418
02:03:53,583 --> 02:03:55,751
my dad's suicide attempt.

2419
02:03:56,878 --> 02:03:59,213
I'd never heard about...

2420
02:03:59,964 --> 02:04:02,717
the shrink, the medicine...

2421
02:04:03,634 --> 02:04:04,886
the vomit and aspirin.

2422
02:04:06,012 --> 02:04:08,806
When my mom talked about it,
I remembered something

2423
02:04:08,890 --> 02:04:10,474
from around that time.

2424
02:04:11,559 --> 02:04:12,810
One morning,

2425
02:04:12,894 --> 02:04:15,229
Snoop was lying on my bedroom floor.

2426
02:04:15,313 --> 02:04:17,481
Not moving.
He smelled like vomit.

2427
02:04:19,483 --> 02:04:21,527
I figured he'd vomited.

2428
02:04:22,987 --> 02:04:24,822
I cleaned his muzzle.

2429
02:04:25,865 --> 02:04:28,034
I figured he'd...

2430
02:04:28,534 --> 02:04:32,288
I don't know, caught a virus
or something, because...

2431
02:04:33,080 --> 02:04:35,625
he acted strange for days.

2432
02:04:35,875 --> 02:04:37,960
He just slept or drank.

2433
02:04:38,961 --> 02:04:43,299
See? Now I'm thinking
maybe he ate my dad's vomit,

2434
02:04:43,382 --> 02:04:44,967
and that made him sick,

2435
02:04:45,051 --> 02:04:47,094
and Mom told the truth!

2436
02:04:48,638 --> 02:04:51,557
So my experiment with the aspirin

2437
02:04:51,641 --> 02:04:53,684
was to see how he'd react.

2438
02:04:53,768 --> 02:04:54,936
And you saw.

2439
02:04:55,019 --> 02:04:58,731
He slept for 14 hours.
Now he's drinking all the time.

2440
02:04:58,814 --> 02:05:00,816
He smells exactly the same!

2441
02:05:01,484 --> 02:05:02,401
Everything!

2442
02:05:02,485 --> 02:05:04,529
Everything's exactly the same!

2443
02:05:06,113 --> 02:05:07,615
But since...

2444
02:05:08,241 --> 02:05:11,577
since yesterday,
I'm not sure if I believe her or not.

2445
02:05:11,827 --> 02:05:13,704
I knew they fought, but...

2446
02:05:18,209 --> 02:05:19,752
It wasn't...

2447
02:05:20,878 --> 02:05:23,506
I didn't think it was that violent.

2448
02:05:23,589 --> 02:05:25,424
MARGE:
Bon...

2449
02:05:25,508 --> 02:05:27,969
Your memories are all you're sure of,

2450
02:05:28,052 --> 02:05:30,137
and it's important to tell the jury.

2451
02:05:30,221 --> 02:05:32,098
But you're just a witness.

2452
02:05:32,181 --> 02:05:34,475
DANIEL: Do you think
she could've killed him?

2453
02:05:36,352 --> 02:05:37,895
(Marge sighs)

2454
02:05:37,979 --> 02:05:39,480
MARGE:
It's not for me to judge.

2455
02:05:39,564 --> 02:05:42,608
I know, but you
could at least tell me!

2456
02:05:42,692 --> 02:05:46,070
I can't answer that.
My role is to protect you...

2457
02:05:46,153 --> 02:05:47,947
Fucking help me!

2458
02:06:25,276 --> 02:06:26,569
MARGE: Actually,

2459
02:06:26,652 --> 02:06:28,946
when we lack an element

2460
02:06:29,030 --> 02:06:31,657
to judge something,
and the lack is unbearable,

2461
02:06:32,658 --> 02:06:34,744
all we can do is decide.

2462
02:06:36,245 --> 02:06:37,413
You see?

2463
02:06:38,080 --> 02:06:41,000
To overcome doubt,
sometimes we have to...

2464
02:06:41,083 --> 02:06:43,753
decide to sway
one way rather than the other.

2465
02:06:45,713 --> 02:06:49,717
Since you need to believe one thing
but have two choices,

2466
02:06:49,800 --> 02:06:51,302
you must choose.

2467
02:06:52,386 --> 02:06:54,597
So you have to invent your belief?

2468
02:06:54,931 --> 02:06:57,099
MARGE:
Yes, well... in a sense.

2469
02:06:57,183 --> 02:07:00,019
So that means, I'm not sure...

2470
02:07:00,937 --> 02:07:03,481
and you're saying
I have to pretend I'm sure?

2471
02:07:03,564 --> 02:07:04,732
MARGE: No.

2472
02:07:05,358 --> 02:07:07,360
No, I'm saying decide.

2473
02:07:09,028 --> 02:07:10,613
That's different.

2474
02:07:42,270 --> 02:07:44,397
LITERARY CRITIC (on TV):
<i>What strikes me is</i>

2475
02:07:44,480 --> 02:07:46,023
<i>we don't know who's more lyrical.</i>

2476
02:07:46,107 --> 02:07:49,026
<i>-The author or the character?
-Both, no doubt!</i>

2477
02:07:49,110 --> 02:07:50,987
<i>Voyter plays with confusion.</i>

2478
02:07:51,070 --> 02:07:53,030
<i>Her second book goes further,</i>

2479
02:07:53,114 --> 02:07:56,367
<i>telling how her father
couldn't stand the first.</i>

2480
02:07:56,450 --> 02:07:57,660
<i>Undoubtedly true.</i>

2481
02:07:57,743 --> 02:08:01,622
<i>The rift degenerates,
forcing her to leave her country.</i>

2482
02:08:01,706 --> 02:08:05,877
<i>Fearing her father's rage,
she falls prey to horrifying visions.</i>

2483
02:08:05,960 --> 02:08:10,339
<i>I found this troubling quote
in an interview. She says,</i>

2484
02:08:10,423 --> 02:08:12,592
<i>"My job is to cover the tracks,</i>

2485
02:08:12,675 --> 02:08:15,595
<i>so fiction can destroy reality."</i>

2486
02:08:17,013 --> 02:08:18,931
LITERARY CRITIC:
<i>Yes, and what excites people</i>

2487
02:08:19,015 --> 02:08:21,184
<i>about the Samuel Maleski case,</i>

2488
02:08:21,267 --> 02:08:24,270
<i>is that it seems to come
from one of her books.</i>

2489
02:08:24,353 --> 02:08:26,856
<i>It feels like she's already written it.</i>

2490
02:08:26,939 --> 02:08:30,693
<i>Even the doubts surrounding
his death, the way he died,</i>

2491
02:08:30,776 --> 02:08:34,197
<i>Voyter's murky personality,
the amoral, deceptive traits</i>

2492
02:08:34,280 --> 02:08:35,740
<i>she seems to overplay...</i>

2493
02:08:35,823 --> 02:08:38,367
<i>It all reads like her books.</i>

2494
02:08:38,451 --> 02:08:40,953
<i>I don't think it matters how he died.</i>

2495
02:08:41,037 --> 02:08:44,707
<i>The fact is, the idea of
a writer killing her husband</i>

2496
02:08:44,790 --> 02:08:48,586
<i>is far more compelling
than a teacher killing himself.</i>

2497
02:08:48,669 --> 02:08:49,712
(turns off TV)

2498
02:08:59,889 --> 02:09:02,934
(playing Chopin's
"Opus 28 No. 4")

2499
02:10:03,494 --> 02:10:06,831
<i>(Daniel continues
playing composition)</i>

2500
02:10:54,295 --> 02:10:55,546
(piano stops)

2501
02:10:59,217 --> 02:11:01,928
If I imagine my mother doing it,
I don't understand.

2502
02:11:04,388 --> 02:11:06,307
But if I imagine my father...

2503
02:11:08,559 --> 02:11:10,770
I think I can understand.

2504
02:11:16,984 --> 02:11:19,153
JUSTICE MINISTER:
Prosecutor, any questions?

2505
02:11:19,987 --> 02:11:22,031
ADVOCATE GENERAL:
Bon...

2506
02:11:22,114 --> 02:11:24,909
The experiment on his dog
proves nothing.

2507
02:11:24,992 --> 02:11:26,869
It's not documented.

2508
02:11:26,953 --> 02:11:29,956
More problematic
are these providential memories,

2509
02:11:30,039 --> 02:11:33,417
clearly jarred
by what he heard during the trial.

2510
02:11:34,043 --> 02:11:37,255
No event can be placed
convincingly on our timeline.

2511
02:11:37,338 --> 02:11:40,007
The timeframe of six months
before Maleski's death

2512
02:11:40,091 --> 02:11:44,220
comes from testimony
given by the defendant herself.

2513
02:11:47,974 --> 02:11:49,392
I'd like to know...

2514
02:11:53,104 --> 02:11:54,272
Daniel...

2515
02:11:56,065 --> 02:11:57,567
Did you ever wonder

2516
02:11:57,650 --> 02:12:00,695
if the overdose
your father supposedly took

2517
02:12:00,778 --> 02:12:04,282
might've resulted
not from a suicide attempt,

2518
02:12:04,365 --> 02:12:07,285
but from an attempt
by your mother to poison him?

2519
02:12:07,368 --> 02:12:10,162
I'm not accusing,
just making a point.

2520
02:12:10,246 --> 02:12:12,748
So, taking these speculations,

2521
02:12:12,832 --> 02:12:15,501
why choose one over the other?

2522
02:12:15,585 --> 02:12:19,672
Your memories speak to
the consequences, not the causes.

2523
02:12:20,882 --> 02:12:23,217
DANIEL:
Yes, I thought about that, but...

2524
02:12:24,177 --> 02:12:26,596
I don't see why
she would've done it.

2525
02:12:27,138 --> 02:12:29,640
It feels like when we lack proof

2526
02:12:29,724 --> 02:12:32,393
to make us sure
how something happened,

2527
02:12:32,935 --> 02:12:35,855
we have to look further,
as the trial is doing.

2528
02:12:36,606 --> 02:12:40,026
When we've looked everywhere
and still don't understand

2529
02:12:40,109 --> 02:12:42,653
how the thing happened,

2530
02:12:42,737 --> 02:12:45,615
I think we have to ask
why it happened.

2531
02:12:50,620 --> 02:12:51,913
Thank you, Daniel.

2532
02:12:52,747 --> 02:12:53,873
Are you finished?

2533
02:13:02,298 --> 02:13:03,257
No.

2534
02:13:05,176 --> 02:13:06,928
I want to say something else.

2535
02:13:14,018 --> 02:13:18,439
Since my dog was sick for days,
Dad and I went to the vet.

2536
02:13:19,899 --> 02:13:22,109
Dad was really quiet in the car.

2537
02:13:22,193 --> 02:13:25,655
He didn't even play music.
He usually always does.

2538
02:13:28,074 --> 02:13:31,035
After a while,
he started talking about Snoop.

2539
02:13:32,620 --> 02:13:33,746
He said...

2540
02:13:33,829 --> 02:13:35,456
DANIEL:
<i>"You know, he could get sick.</i>

2541
02:13:36,249 --> 02:13:39,502
<i>"Even die. You know that.
You need to be ready."</i>

2542
02:13:41,087 --> 02:13:42,713
<i>I didn't want to hear that.</i>

2543
02:13:43,464 --> 02:13:46,801
<i>Snoop was doing better.
He was still young.</i>

2544
02:13:46,884 --> 02:13:48,135
<i>He'd never been sick.</i>

2545
02:13:48,219 --> 02:13:50,471
<i>I told him he wasn't going to die.</i>

2546
02:13:52,557 --> 02:13:53,933
But he kept going.

2547
02:13:54,475 --> 02:13:58,729
He said, "You need to be aware of it.
It'll happen someday.

2548
02:13:59,689 --> 02:14:02,775
"And it's no wonder Snoop gets tired.

2549
02:14:02,859 --> 02:14:04,861
"He's not so young in dog years.

2550
02:14:08,072 --> 02:14:09,740
DANIEL: <i>"Can you imagine his life?</i>

2551
02:14:11,826 --> 02:14:13,536
<i>"He's not just any dog.</i>

2552
02:14:14,620 --> 02:14:16,205
<i>"He's a great dog.</i>

2553
02:14:17,748 --> 02:14:19,625
<i>"An outstanding dog.</i>

2554
02:14:20,626 --> 02:14:23,588
<i>"Think about it.
He anticipates your needs,</i>

2555
02:14:24,005 --> 02:14:26,215
<i>"foresees your movements,</i>

2556
02:14:26,799 --> 02:14:28,551
<i>"keeps you safe from danger.</i>

2557
02:14:30,344 --> 02:14:32,680
<i>"He spends his life
imagining your needs,</i>

2558
02:14:32,763 --> 02:14:35,057
<i>"thinking about what you can't see.</i>

2559
02:14:38,644 --> 02:14:40,062
<i>"Maybe he's tired.</i>

2560
02:14:40,479 --> 02:14:42,148
<i>"Always caring for others.</i>

2561
02:14:42,940 --> 02:14:44,901
<i>"Maybe one day, he'll be done.</i>

2562
02:14:45,776 --> 02:14:47,069
<i>That could happen."</i>

2563
02:14:52,158 --> 02:14:54,035
And I remember at the end,

2564
02:14:55,870 --> 02:14:57,914
he said, "One day,

2565
02:14:57,997 --> 02:15:00,958
"when it's time
for him to go, he'll go.

2566
02:15:02,084 --> 02:15:05,755
"You won't be able to help it.
Prepare yourself, it'll be hard.

2567
02:15:05,838 --> 02:15:08,090
But it won't be the end of your life."

2568
02:15:14,764 --> 02:15:16,307
He meant himself.

2569
02:15:17,141 --> 02:15:18,392
Now...

2570
02:15:19,810 --> 02:15:21,938
Now I know he meant himself.

2571
02:15:26,901 --> 02:15:27,777
ADVOCATE GENERAL:
Bon.

2572
02:15:28,653 --> 02:15:31,948
I implore the jurors to bear in mind

2573
02:15:32,031 --> 02:15:33,991
this story is extremely subjective.

2574
02:15:34,700 --> 02:15:38,621
In no way does it qualify
as any form of proof.

2575
02:15:53,511 --> 02:15:54,679
(people chattering)

2576
02:15:59,016 --> 02:16:02,979
Yes, Serge, we are still outside
the courthouse in Grenoble.

2577
02:16:03,062 --> 02:16:06,065
The trial was scheduled
to end on Friday,

2578
02:16:06,148 --> 02:16:08,692
but Sandra Voyter's son Daniel

2579
02:16:08,776 --> 02:16:11,195
insisted on testifying again
this morning.

2580
02:16:11,279 --> 02:16:12,989
The jury is still...

2581
02:16:13,072 --> 02:16:14,740
(Daniel playing Chopin's
"Opus 28 No. 4")

2582
02:16:14,824 --> 02:16:16,868
(Snoop panting;
paws clacking on floor)

2583
02:16:18,952 --> 02:16:20,663
(Snoop drinking water from bowl)

2584
02:16:26,209 --> 02:16:28,004
(Snoops paws clacking on floor)

2585
02:16:28,087 --> 02:16:29,964
MARGE: Daniel!

2586
02:16:30,047 --> 02:16:33,425
REPORTER 1 (on TV):
<i>Ms. Voyter, how do you feel...</i>

2587
02:16:33,885 --> 02:16:36,012
<i>after being acquitted?</i>

2588
02:16:36,094 --> 02:16:37,013
SANDRA: <i>Uh...</i>

2589
02:16:37,096 --> 02:16:40,683
<i>There were too many words
in this trial.</i>

2590
02:16:41,017 --> 02:16:42,434
{\an8}<i>I've nothing more to say.</i>

2591
02:16:42,934 --> 02:16:46,355
{\an8}<i>I want to call my son and go home.</i>

2592
02:16:47,272 --> 02:16:51,402
<i>Obviously I thank my lawyers,
who always believed in me.</i>

2593
02:16:51,485 --> 02:16:54,197
REPORTER 1:
<i>Mr. Renzi, are you relieved?</i>

2594
02:16:54,280 --> 02:16:56,449
VINCENT:
<i>I commend the jury...</i>

2595
02:16:56,531 --> 02:16:59,326
-(reporters clamoring)
-who <i>saw Sandra Voyter as she is...</i>

2596
02:17:01,120 --> 02:17:02,996
(clamoring continues)

2597
02:17:10,338 --> 02:17:11,880
(Marge speaking indistinctly)

2598
02:17:16,886 --> 02:17:19,096
(reporters clamoring)

2599
02:17:50,002 --> 02:17:51,379
(sighs)

2600
02:18:01,180 --> 02:18:03,014
SANDRA (in French):
Marge, it's Sandra.

2601
02:18:04,600 --> 02:18:07,937
(Sandra laughs)
Yes, it's incredible, we're relieved.

2602
02:18:08,020 --> 02:18:09,355
Oui.

2603
02:18:11,732 --> 02:18:13,942
Does Daniel want to talk to me?

2604
02:18:16,404 --> 02:18:18,781
Of course, he must be tired,

2605
02:18:18,865 --> 02:18:20,074
I understand.

2606
02:18:21,909 --> 02:18:24,954
Does he mind if I come home tonight?

2607
02:18:25,037 --> 02:18:26,914
Would he prefer tomorrow, or...

2608
02:18:31,502 --> 02:18:32,587
Okay.

2609
02:18:32,837 --> 02:18:34,172
Okay. Okay. Okay.

2610
02:18:34,254 --> 02:18:37,842
We'll get some dinner,
then I'll be home. See you then.

2611
02:18:37,924 --> 02:18:39,427
(Sandra happily moans)

2612
02:18:41,094 --> 02:18:42,847
SANDRA (in English):
I need a drink.

2613
02:18:42,930 --> 02:18:45,433
(both laugh)

2614
02:18:47,393 --> 02:18:48,394
(in English)
Another!

2615
02:18:48,477 --> 02:18:50,188
(laughter)

2616
02:18:52,481 --> 02:18:53,858
(in English)
Okay, deal!

2617
02:18:55,692 --> 02:18:57,486
(stammers)

2618
02:18:57,570 --> 02:18:59,530
Do you always... Do you...

2619
02:18:59,614 --> 02:19:01,574
When you win,
do you always, like that?

2620
02:19:01,656 --> 02:19:03,284
-I mean, this is happening...
-VINCENT: We never win.

2621
02:19:03,367 --> 02:19:05,244
(laughter)

2622
02:19:05,327 --> 02:19:06,745
VINCENT:
That's the fucking first time

2623
02:19:06,829 --> 02:19:08,289
in our life we win!

2624
02:19:08,371 --> 02:19:09,790
-No...
-VINCENT: Yes. Of course!

2625
02:19:09,874 --> 02:19:11,459
You told me
you're a good lawyer,

2626
02:19:11,541 --> 02:19:12,834
and what is happening now?

2627
02:19:12,919 --> 02:19:15,338
(laughter)

2628
02:19:15,421 --> 02:19:16,755
-SANDRA: No, that's not true!
-No?

2629
02:19:16,839 --> 02:19:18,049
VINCENT:
It's not spicy.

2630
02:19:18,132 --> 02:19:19,759
SANDRA:
You have to try this, really.

2631
02:19:19,842 --> 02:19:21,093
VINCENT:
Sandra, I ate too much.

2632
02:19:21,177 --> 02:19:22,512
YOUNG FEMALE LAWYER:
I'm gonna throw up.

2633
02:19:22,594 --> 02:19:24,138
(in French)
A quick smoke first.

2634
02:19:24,513 --> 02:19:25,640
Be right back.

2635
02:19:28,184 --> 02:19:31,479
VINCENT (in English):
Okay, no, that you first, please.

2636
02:19:31,562 --> 02:19:33,898
-(bell rings nearby)
-(people chattering)

2637
02:19:45,326 --> 02:19:46,786
It's not so easy, no?

2638
02:19:46,869 --> 02:19:50,456
No. It's not,
it's with all the bones and...

2639
02:19:55,002 --> 02:19:56,796
After this, we go?

2640
02:19:56,879 --> 02:19:59,215
You're ready to go home?

2641
02:19:59,298 --> 02:20:00,550
I can... I can drive.

2642
02:20:00,633 --> 02:20:02,844
I can... I can drop you off.

2643
02:20:02,927 --> 02:20:04,387
SANDRA:
One more.

2644
02:20:04,470 --> 02:20:06,013
For... For the road.

2645
02:20:06,097 --> 02:20:07,682
(both chuckle)

2646
02:20:07,765 --> 02:20:09,225
VINCENT: Of course,
for the driver.

2647
02:20:10,476 --> 02:20:11,644
VINCENT: Okay, same?

2648
02:20:11,727 --> 02:20:13,396
-SANDRA: Mm-hmm.
-(sake cups clattering)

2649
02:20:13,479 --> 02:20:14,647
(Vincent clears throat)

2650
02:20:19,944 --> 02:20:21,821
VINCENT (in French):
Can I just get...

2651
02:20:21,904 --> 02:20:24,073
two more of these? Thanks.

2652
02:20:27,910 --> 02:20:28,995
VINCENT (whispers):
Merci, monsieur.

2653
02:20:29,078 --> 02:20:30,538
(Vincent speaks French)

2654
02:20:35,209 --> 02:20:37,253
-VINCENT: Okay.
-SANDRA: Okay.

2655
02:20:38,588 --> 02:20:40,214
-(sighs) Yeah.
-(sighs) Yeah.

2656
02:20:40,298 --> 02:20:42,049
-To you.
-To you.

2657
02:20:49,015 --> 02:20:50,057
(Vincent clears throat)

2658
02:20:56,647 --> 02:20:57,940
Are you all right?

2659
02:20:58,024 --> 02:21:00,234
(deeply inhales, exhales)

2660
02:21:00,318 --> 02:21:01,903
(Sandra clears throat)

2661
02:21:01,986 --> 02:21:02,945
-Tell me.
-I...

2662
02:21:03,029 --> 02:21:04,947
No. I just...

2663
02:21:05,031 --> 02:21:06,115
I thought...

2664
02:21:07,533 --> 02:21:09,869
I thought I'd feel relieved.

2665
02:21:09,952 --> 02:21:11,037
Well...

2666
02:21:11,120 --> 02:21:13,331
(chuckles, sniffs)

2667
02:21:13,414 --> 02:21:14,999
It doesn't come right away.

2668
02:21:15,082 --> 02:21:16,834
(sniffs, clears throat)

2669
02:21:16,918 --> 02:21:18,753
(shudders)
You sure?

2670
02:21:18,836 --> 02:21:21,214
-VINCENT: I'm not sure.
-(nervous laugh)

2671
02:21:21,297 --> 02:21:23,299
Well...

2672
02:21:23,382 --> 02:21:26,260
It's just, you know,
when you lose, you lose.

2673
02:21:26,344 --> 02:21:28,012
It's the worst thing
that can happen.

2674
02:21:28,095 --> 02:21:29,889
And if you win, you...

2675
02:21:31,390 --> 02:21:35,770
kind of expect some reward...

2676
02:21:37,021 --> 02:21:38,689
but there isn't any.

2677
02:21:38,773 --> 02:21:40,483
-VINCENT: Hmm.
-It's just...

2678
02:21:42,485 --> 02:21:43,945
It's just over.

2679
02:21:48,783 --> 02:21:51,452
Maybe sometimes,
we expect too much...

2680
02:21:54,705 --> 02:21:55,915
Yeah, maybe.

2681
02:23:00,855 --> 02:23:01,898
(Sandra sighs)

2682
02:23:01,981 --> 02:23:05,568
SANDRA (in French):
Hi. Sorry.

2683
02:23:07,570 --> 02:23:09,322
(in French) He tried
to wait up but fell asleep.

2684
02:23:09,405 --> 02:23:10,656
SANDRA: Oh, oui.

2685
02:23:12,283 --> 02:23:13,409
SANDRA:
Okay.

2686
02:23:23,377 --> 02:23:25,796
(whispers in French)

2687
02:23:59,497 --> 02:24:01,123
MARGE (whispering):
I'll be going now.

2688
02:24:01,207 --> 02:24:02,500
SANDRA (whispering):
Not staying over?

2689
02:24:02,583 --> 02:24:04,418
MARGE:
No, I'll leave you be.

2690
02:24:05,044 --> 02:24:06,128
SANDRA: Oh.

2691
02:24:06,212 --> 02:24:07,588
(both chuckle quietly)

2692
02:24:10,800 --> 02:24:12,093
BOTH:
Goodbye.

2693
02:24:29,151 --> 02:24:31,237
DANIEL:
I was afraid of you coming home.

2694
02:24:33,030 --> 02:24:36,117
Me too, I was afraid to come home.

2695
02:25:22,997 --> 02:25:24,081
(kisses)

2696
02:26:22,974 --> 02:26:24,183
(softly groans)

2697
02:26:26,686 --> 02:26:28,187
(sighs)

2698
02:26:29,105 --> 02:26:31,440
(Snoop's paws clacking on floor)

2699
02:26:38,739 --> 02:26:40,074
(Sandra chuckles)

2700
02:26:58,801 --> 02:27:03,973
<i>(Daniel playing
Chopin's "Opus 28 No. 4")</i>

2701
02:28:16,879 --> 02:28:19,799
{\an8}(composition continues)

